<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines, Pentagon Agree on Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Six of the nation's major airlines signed an  
agreement with the Pentagon on Thursday under which the airlines 
will check the safety of foreign partners who help them fly 
American troops overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, which grew out of a 1985 charter crash in  
Newfoundland that killed 248 U.S. soldiers, should also help 
prevent commercial passengers from ending up on foreign carriers 
with substandard safety records. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. airlines plan to certify within the next year that  
their foreign partners have processes for ensuring safety and have 
trained safety inspectors and that their flight crews get training 
through manuals that meet international flight safety standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Future inspections will be conducted at two-year intervals, or  
as the need arises. The participating carriers are American 
Airlines, Continental Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Northwest 
Airlines, TWA and United Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is going to be a standard of safety that we are going to  
test to,'' Capt. Edmond Soliday, vice president of corporate safety 
at United, said at a news conference. ``We're trying to get, to the 
best of our ability, a seamless level of compliance with 
standards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Northwest said the government will get an added  
benefit since the carriers will even check the safety of airlines 
that do not fly to the United States. The U.S. government is 
empowered to check only airlines that fly in and out of the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a faster way for us to bring foreign airlines up to  
Western European and United States-level standards,'' said Clayton 
Foushee, Northwest's vice president of regulatory affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The safety of foreign carriers has become an issue for U.S.  
airlines because many of them now have partnerships with overseas 
airlines known as ``code-shares.'' There were 61 such partnerships 
in 1994; now there are now more than 160. 
</P>
<P>
	Under such an arrangement, the carriers buy tickets on each  
other's planes and then sell them to passengers on connecting 
flights as if they were their own. 
</P>
<P>
	A passenger with a United Airlines ticket, for example, may fly  
on a United plane to New York and then transfer for a flight to 
Europe with the airline's German partner, Lufthansa, even though 
the ticket still reads ``United'' and has a United flight number. 
</P>
<P>
	Both carriers have excellent safety records, and airlines favor  
such partnerships because it allows them to project the image of a 
larger route network. It also gives passengers the ability to make 
seamless connections between airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, however, Delta Air Lines halted its code-sharing  
arrangement with Korean Air after the Asian carrier suffered a 
cargo plane crash in China -- the latest in a series of fatal 
accidents or aircraft losses for Korean Air. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta had said previously that it would not team up with an  
airline it deemed unsafe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon has a travel budget of $1.2 billion a year and has  
used its clout to push the airlines into taking visible steps to 
ensure the safety of foreign partners who might carry U.S. troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the advent of code-sharing has changed the  
rules and changed the concept a little bit and we believe that was 
an area that really needed to be addressed from a safety 
standpoint,'' said Mary Lou McHugh, assistant deputy defense 
undersecretary for transportation policy. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
