<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Game of Gunplay Leads to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- It started out as a night of youthful bragging  
between two friends to see who was the quicker draw with handguns 
they thought were unloaded. 
</P>
<P>
	It ended with one teen dead and the other paralyzed from the  
neck down and charged with reckless homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, a prosecutor said paralyzed 17-year-old Eduardo  
Rivera will still be tried, but as a juvenile. He said he would not 
ask for jail time because of the boy's condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel it's very important that Mr. Rivera be held  
accountable for what he did, even if he may not be incarcerated 
because of it,'' prosecutor Steven V. Licata said. 
</P>
<P>
	A preliminary hearing in the case is scheduled to continue  
Friday in children's court regarding the death in January of 
15-year-old Efrain Casas. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera and Casas had known each other for just two weeks when  
they went back to Casas's house to hang out after school on Jan. 5, 
according to police reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The boys spent part of the night on the phone with a girl Casas  
was dating, Jacquelyn Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	At some point they opened an unlocked plastic box under the bed  
of Casas's father and pulled out a pair of handguns. One of them 
suggested they see ``who can draw and cock the gun the fastest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jacquelyn was on the phone with Casas when she heard him say,  
``Eddie, are you ready?'' and then count ``One, two, three!'' She 
heard a loud gunshot, followed by silence. Minutes later, she heard 
Rivera's faint voice asking her to call 911. 
</P>
<P>
	Thinking the boys were joking, she hung up.  
</P>
<P>
	When Casas's father returned at 2 a.m. the next morning, he  
heard Rivera in a bedroom calling, ``Hello? Hello?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He found the boy sprawled on the bed, unable to move and his son  
motionless on the floor. The elder Casas immediately called for 
help. His son died later that day at a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Licata said one reason he decided to prosecute was Rivera's  
prior conviction for stealing a 1987 Oldsmobile Cutlass for a joy 
ride. Rivera received probation, but because the crime would have 
been a felony for an adult, the judge told him he could never again 
possess a firearm under state law. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time we focus on Mr. Rivera in his wheelchair, there's a  
woman in the back of the room whose son is dead,'' Licata said. 
``We don't want to forget about her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robin Shellow, Rivera's attorney, did not return repeated  
messages Thursday from The Associated Press seeking comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
