<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Corn Fall; Cocoa Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Forecasts for rain in the parched Midwest sent soybean futures  
prices plummeting Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, while 
corn futures also fell. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, pork belly futures also dropped and cocoa  
futures rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures had rallied sharply in the past week  
as hot, dry weather has hurt crops in Illinois and points east. 
</P>
<P>
	But forecasts for rain that could quench thirsty soybean and  
corn crops sent prices falling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a weather market,'' said Don Roose, a grains analyst  
and president of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities Inc. ``We're trying to 
figure out, 'Does it or doesn't it rain? Will it or won't it be 
hot.''' 
</P>
<P>
	While soybean futures also got pressure from lackluster export  
sales, analysts said corn and soybeans also were down due to 
profit-taking selling as traders cashed in on the big gains of the 
past week amid fears that prices are too high for the world market. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, wheat futures prices were up.  
</P>
<P>
	Roose said traders were, in part, anticipating an increased  
demand for winter wheat since the spring crops were relatively 
smaller. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of trading Thursday, wheat for December delivery rose  
1 3/4 cents to $2.94 1/2 a bushel; December corn fell 1 1/2 cents to $2.35 a 
bushel; December oats fell 3/4 cent to $1.17 1/2 a bushel; and November 
soybeans dropped 14 cents to $4.80 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of pork bellies, or uncured bacon, tumbled on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange in what analysts said was heavy profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the downward trend is likely temporary. They said  
there has been a great deal of movement in the U.S. pork belly 
market -- 5 million pounds last week, compared with half that the 
previous week -- as many grocers begin to offer bacon as a summer 
sale item. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday, August pork bellies fell 3 cents to 53.72 a  
pound; August live cattle rose 0.07 cent to 64.42 cents a pound; 
August feeder cattle were up 0.35 cent to 76.42 cents a pound; and 
August lean hogs fell 0.13 cent to 50.32 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, cocoa futures rose on the Board of Trade of the City  
of New York on news that Ghana had abruptly stopped selling its 
midyear crop. Analysts said there is speculation that the African 
country may wait until October to continue selling -- though others 
said the selling was halted in an attempt to curb cocoa smuggling 
to the Ivory Coast. September cocoa was up $6 to $988 a ton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
