<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 5, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 119.05  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks managed their strongest rally in more  
than a week today as bargain-hunting investors stepped into a 
market driven down by fears of higher interest rates. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed up 119.05 at 10,793.82. In morning 
trading, the Dow had fallen 108 points. Broader stock indicators 
were mixed, with any gains hard-fought in a session of rapid shifts 
between positive and negative territory. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 
index gained, and the Nasdaq composite index, heavily weighted with 
technology stocks, eked out its first gain since last Wednesday. 
The Nasdaq composite rose 25.81 to 2,565.81. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,793.82  + 119.05
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1198  Declines 1823  Unchgd  490
NYSE Volume:         836,974,300
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online82 7/8   - 4 9/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1311.83  + 6.50
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          776.09   -  0.87
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,565.81  + 25.81
Gold(final) -    $256.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   $5.440  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	Workers' Productivity Growth Slows  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The productivity of U.S. workers has slowed  
its growth and unit labor costs are up, the Labor Department said 
today. Productivity, the amount of output for each hour worked, 
grew at an annual rate of 1.3 percent in the April-June quarter, 
compared to 3.6 percent growth in the first three months of the 
year. Meanwhile, unit labor costs, considered a key measure of wage 
pressures, surged at an annual rate of 3.8 percent in the second 
quarter, the worst showing for this measurement since the end of 
1997. Analysts had expected a rise of around 2.2 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales Top Expectations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The raging U.S. economy combined with a heat  
wave blanketing much of the country gave Americans a reason to head 
to the nation's air-conditioned stores and malls in July, boosting 
retail sales to surprisingly strong levels. The 
better-than-expected July sales reported today followed big gains 
in May and June. As a result, Wall Street analysts expect to see 
robust second-quarter profits when retailers begin to report 
earnings next week. The Merrill Lynch retail index, the investment 
firm's barometer of sales performance at department stores and 
discount chains, rose 4.5 percent in July. It rose 6.3 percent in 
June and 5.4 percent in May. 

</P>
<P>
	Chicago, London Markets in Pact  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Mercantile Exchange and the London  
International Financial Futures and Options Exchange have formed an 
alliance to give customers electronic access to each other's 
products, a move aimed at cutting traders' costs and improving 
their efficiency. The connection will allow customers to trade 
futures contracts for securities pegged to short-term interest 
rates for both markets on one computer screen, officials for the 
two exchanges said in a joint news conference today with 
participants in Chicago and London. The alliance is set to begin 
early next year and will provide the exchanges' customers access to 
both the Merc's Globex2 and LIFFE's CONNECT electronic trading 
systems. 

</P>
<P>
	Bear Stearns Settles for $38.5M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Investors defrauded by a small brokerage will  
get $30 million from Bear Stearns &AMP; Cos. Inc., a big Wall Street 
firm that processed their transactions. The settlement announced 
today, which totals $38.5 million and was accompanied by the 
resignation of a top Bear Stearns executive, closes a two-year 
investigation by federal and New York City authorities into Bear 
Stearns' relationship with the smaller brokerage, A.R. Baron &AMP; Co. 
Bear Stearns neither admitted nor denied wrongdoing in agreeing to 
the settlement. Bear Stearns processed trades, a lucrative 
financial function known as clearing, for A.R. Baron from mid-1995 
through mid-1996. The now-defunct A.R. Baron failed in 1997 and is 
in bankruptcy proceedings. Customers, some of whom have sued, have 
contended they lost a total of $75 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Offers Plan for Steel Biz  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration presented a plan  
today to bolster the troubled steel industry against unfair trade 
practices, including a proposal to fight international loans that 
would subsidize imports. Administration officials presented the 
proposals to industry chiefs and labor leaders at a White House 
meeting as Congress sent President Clinton a $1.5 billion loan plan 
aimed in part at helping steel producers. Among the proposals were 
a pledge to block World Bank and International Monetary Fund loans 
that would further subsidize foreign steel industries and ensure 
that the next round of World Trade Organization talks maintains 
strong sanctions against unfair trade. 

</P>
<P>
	Via Technologies Aiming at Intel  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In another move to take on Intel Corp. in the  
chip-set-making industry, Via Technologies Inc. said it has agreed 
to buy the microprocessing unit of Integrated Device Technology. 
The Taipei-based Via said in a statement today that it will acquire 
the WinChip microprocessor unit and x86-architecture 
microprocessing design team from Integrated Device Technology, 
based in Santa Clara, Calif. Via and Integrated also agreed to a 
patent cross-license agreement for each company's chip technology. 

</P>
<P>
	BMW Plans Thailand Output  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- German luxury car maker BMW AG will  
start rolling sedans off the production lines at a new plant in 
Thailand early next year, hoping to capitalize on a nascent 
economic recovery. Jesus Cordoba, president of BMW (Thailand), told 
The Associated Press in an interview that production targets of 
10,000 vehicles per year should be reached by 2004 and will 
initially be aimed at the Thai market. 

</P>
<P>
	GM May Build Cars in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will consider becoming the  
first American automaker to build vehicles in Japan since before 
World War II in an effort to boost sales there. GM, the world's 
largest automaker, sold only about 53,000 cars and trucks in Japan 
last year, a small number in a market where more than 4 million 
vehicles are sold each year. Spokesman Henry Wong said today GM's 
strategy would include ``establishing a manufacturing presence'' in 
Japan, along with building its dealer base, importing models, and 
relying on its ties to Japan's Isuzu Motors Ltd. and Suzuki Motor 
Corp. Wong declined to elaborate. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan May Cancel Boeing 777 Order  
</P>
<P>
	TACOMA, Wash. (AP) -- Taiwan's flagship airline apparently has  
been told by the Taiwanese government to cancel an order for 12 
Boeing 777s in protest against the Clinton administration's 
mainland China policy. Boeing had been expecting the $2 billion 
deal to be formally announced at any time. Taiwan's China Airlines 
signed a letter of intent to buy the jets in 1995. Citing 
congressional and industry sources, the Tacoma News Tribune 
reported today that instead China Airlines is expected to announce 
a major purchase of A-340 planes from the European consortium 
Airbus Industrie, perhaps as early as next week. China Airlines is 
still expected to announce the purchase of 13 Boeing 747s. 

</P>
<P>
	BBC Confronts Digital TV Era  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A government panel recommends raising the  
television license fee paid by British households to help the 
British Broadcasting Corp. convert to digital broadcasting. The 
panel also called today for the BBC to sell assets, cut costs and 
increase revenues to fund the transition. The BBC complained that 
the proposed funding would be insufficient, while BBC rivals 
protested that the BBC was being given an unfair edge in the race 
to digitize. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: up 4,000 to 279,000  
</P>
<P>
	Productivity: up 1.3 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Unemployment  



  	   	
</P>
