<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Extradition of Rwandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAREDO, Texas (AP) -- An elderly Rwandan clergyman accused of  
offering refuge to people in his homeland, then taking part in 
their massacre, must be turned over to a war crimes tribunal, the 
5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	In an opinion released Thursday, the New Orleans-based appeals  
court upheld an earlier ruling by a federal judge stating there is 
probable cause that Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, 75, committed genocide 
and crimes against humanity. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges were lodged against the pastor by the United  
Nations' International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda. The tribunal 
is based in Arusha, Tanzania. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Ntakirutimana could be sentenced to life in  
prison. He can appeal the appeals court ruling to the U.S. Supreme 
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Hutu extremists in Rwanda killed more than 500,000  
people, mostly minority Tutsis. Ntakirutimana was pastor of the 
Seventh-day Adventist Church in Mugonero in the Kibuye district of 
the East African country at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses say he urged a large, mostly Tutsi group of men, women  
and children to seek refuge in a church and hospital complex, then 
took part in a daylong gun and machete attack on the Tutsis that 
left hundreds of people dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Ntakirutimana then continued the attacks against Tutsis who  
escaped the church massacre, the tribunal indictment alleges. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested in September 1996 in Laredo, where his son  
lives. He moved there legally with a permanent resident visa. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there is no extradition treaty between the United  
States and the tribunal, Congress passed a law in 1996 that allows 
Ntakirutimana's extradition. 
</P>
<P>
	Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark represents  
Ntakirutimana. He argued that the tribunal was formed in violation 
of the U.N. charter, and that evidence was not sufficient to 
warrant the pastor's extradition. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
