<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Holds Turkish Man in Custody </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A Turkish man removed from a flight before it  
left for Istanbul was being held for an expired visa as the FBI 
investigated what it would refer to only as suspicious behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakan Caglar, 35, attracted the suspicion of law enforcement  
officials when he retrieved his luggage from a U-Haul truck on 
Tuesday and paid cash for a one-way ticket to Turkey at a Valdosta 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Caglar, who had been in the United States since March 7, was  
being held by the Immigration and Naturalization Service because 
his visa expired June 6, said Thomas Fisher, district director for 
the INS. 
</P>
<P>
	``He overstayed and that's the primary reason that we are  
holding him right now,'' Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said INS officials are interviewing Caglar about his  
activities in the United States. He said Caglar drove from Florida 
to Valdosta, where he caught a plane to Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI has not accused Caglar of committing a crime or planning  
to commit one. Agency spokeswoman Celestine Armstead said the fact 
Caglar paid for his ticket with cash was not all that called him to 
the agency's attention, but she would not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	All 217 passengers on Delta Air Lines Flight 40 were asked to  
get off the plane at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport on 
Tuesday night for a security sweep that included luggage. Five 
passengers sitting near the man were questioned and released. The 
flight departed more than four hours late. 
</P>
<P>
	Upon the plane's arrival in Istanbul, Turkish authorities  
questioned the same five passengers, along with a child, the 
semiofficial Anatolia news agency reported. The six Turkish 
citizens were released. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
