<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coors Can't Use NFL Trademark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Coors Brewing Co. cannot use the NFL trademark  
in its new beer promotion, a judge has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal judge Denise L. Cote granted a temporary injunction  
Wednesday preventing the NFL Players Association from launching a 
nationwide campaign that identifies Coors as ``the official beer of 
NFL players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players Inc., the licensing arm of the union, entered into a  
deal with Coors which the league opposed as trademark infringement. 
NFL attorneys also said the promotion was inherently false because 
active players cannot promote alcohol products amd the players 
association does not represent every player. 
</P>
<P>
	The union said it would appeal the decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``We respectfully disagree with Judge Cote's decision to grant  
preliminary relief in this case,'' said Gene Upshaw, executive 
director of the union, and chairman of Players Inc. ``We will 
appeal her decision, which we believe is misguided, misinterprets 
the facts and misapplies the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Gertzog, NFL senior vice president of business affairs and  
general counsel, said the injunction proves the NFL has sole rights 
to its trademark. Gertzog said the league would not have objected 
if the promotion had used the phrase ``Official Beer of Players, 
Inc.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coors spokesman Dave Taylor said Coors still plans to launch the  
promotion in mid-August as planned and run it through the Labor Day 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Allen, assistant executive director of the union, said  
certain elements of the words would be changed on certain of the 
pieces but that the promotion would go forth as would the appeal. 
``This is far from over,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Coors competitors, Miller Brewing and Anheuser-Busch, are  
NFL beer sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL and NFL Properties are seeking to make the injunction  
permanent. A date for a trial on that request will be set in a 
hearing in New York on Aug. 18, Gertzog said. 






  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
