<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marines Probe Racial Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- The Marine Corps is investigating alleged  
racial hostility at a Marine-supported youth camp after a 
13-year-old black boy said a slur was written in his locker and his 
room was ransacked. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked,'' Mike Kessler, incoming director of the Young  
Marines camp, said Thursday. ``I was angered and embarrassed all at 
the same time. These poor kids didn't deserve this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The base said it learned of the incident when The Washington  
Post reported it Thursday and an investigation is underway. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident happened at Camp Lejeune, a Marines basic training  
camp where an encampment was held last month for members of Young 
Marines, a Marine-supported group of youngsters with units across 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of children attended a Young Marines summer session  
from July 18-24. They slept in reserve barracks, ran the obstacle 
course and were shown displays of military equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The racial epithet was written in toothpaste inside the locker  
of the camper, who is from the Washington, D.C., area, officials 
said. A photograph was torn up and the room he shared with three 
other black campers was ransacked twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Young Marines said it had sent one camper home last month for  
uttering a racial epithet. The same youth is now suspected of 
writing on the locker and being part of a group believed to have 
trashed the room. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard McFerson, commander of the Nation's Capitol Young  
Marines, a unit based in Washington, D.C., told the newspaper he 
never will return to Camp Lejeune. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try to get (youths) out of the city and show them something  
different, and if that's what they're going to see, I might as well 
let them run around the street and be gang members,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The youth group said it will add racial sensitivity sessions to  
training classes for adult leaders. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
