<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Murrah Plaza Reopens in Oklahoma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The plaza adjacent to where the Alfred P.  
Murrah Federal Building once stood reopened quietly today, a serene 
space for workers and visitors to stop amid the sounds of a 
cascading fountain and reflect on their memories. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaza used to be a perfect lunchtime hangout, with workers  
eating from brown bags in the midday sun. That was before April 19, 
1995, when a bomb ripped apart the building, killing 168 people and 
injuring hundreds of others. 
</P>
<P>
	The restoration by the General Services Administration is  
respectful of the plaza's place in history, remembered as a staging 
area and triage center for the rescue effort that terrible day, but 
also as a popular spot for employee gatherings in years past. 
</P>
<P>
	Now sounds of water cascading over a semi-cylindrical Carnelian  
granite fountain will soothe workers taking a break or visitors 
observing progress of building the Oklahoma City National Memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``For some of us there's bad memories here, but it's a lot nicer  
now,'' said John Cresswell, who was a GSA maintenance mechanic at 
the Murrah building. He was at the plaza this morning to check it 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's beautiful. It adds to the healing process,'' said  
GSA employee Ron Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Another GSA worker, Robert Breaux, said he hoped coins tossed in  
the fountain would go toward the bombing memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the most peaceful thing I've ever seen in an urban  
area,'' George Hozendorf, special assistant to the regional 
administrator of the GSA, said Wednesday. ``Just so calming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elevated plaza is located over the garage immediately south  
of where the federal building once stood. There are native trees 
and plants in 47 planters, selected to closely match the original 
1977 landscaping. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really nice. I loved it. I appreciated that they tried to  
put back the original,'' said Jim Denny, father of survivors 
Brandon and Rebecca, who were in the building's day-care center the 
day of the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	The project also has interpretive signs referring to different  
reference points and three new flagpoles put up in partnership with 
the national memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who planned to return is bombing survivor Paul  
Heath, a psychologist in the Department of Veterans Affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a wonderful step forward,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Not being able to bring someone back doesn't rob you from  
having the opportunity of experiencing the positive memory of those 
people when you walk around on the plaza,'' Heath said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
