<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Turk Detained in Atlanta Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A man who was yanked off a plane and detained for  
an expired visa was released Thursday after an FBI investigation 
failed to yield criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakan Caglar, 35, drew the suspicion of authorities Tuesday at  
the Valdosta airport after he retrieved his luggage from a U-Haul 
truck and paid cash for a one-way ticket to Istanbul, with a change 
of planes in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said at the time they received a tip that Caglar was ``a  
potential threat to national security.'' All 217 passengers on the 
flight were taken off the plane for a security check and five 
seated near Caglar were questioned. 
</P>
<P>
	Caglar was never charged with a crime and FBI spokeswoman  
Celestine Armstead refused Thursday to say what agents suspected he 
might have done. 
</P>
<P>
	``No federal charges are going to be filed,'' Ms. Armstead said.  
``We're not embarassed at all. We stand firmly behind what we 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Caglar, who had been in the United States since March 7, was  
detained until Thursday by the Immigration and Naturalization 
Service because his visa expired June 6. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
