<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hollinquest To Miss Four Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Green Bay Packers linebacker Lamont  
Hollinquest will miss the team's first four games this season for 
violating the NFL's substance-abuse policy, a newspaper said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Green Bay Press-Gazette said Hollinquest, who was signed by  
the Packers on Tuesday after having been waived by the Kansas City 
Chiefs, would not identify the substance for which he tested 
positive. 
</P>
<P>
	But it said he confirmed he tested positive twice over a short  
span of time this spring, prompting the suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	``People make mistakes,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	When a player tests positive and enters the NFL's  
substance-abuse program, the team is not involved in his mandatory 
evaluation and treatment. That program is run directly by the NFL, 
as spelled out in the collective-bargaining agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollinquest said the Chiefs asked him to take additional  
treatment steps beyond the NFL's program, but he declined, in part 
on advice from the NFL, the Press-Gazette said. 
</P>
<P>
	He played for the Packers the last three years. But he signed a  
two-year contract with Kansas City during the offseason and said he 
was disappointed the Chiefs did not stick with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you tell a guy, `We're not going to back you up because you  
made a mistake?' '' Hollinquest told the Press-Gazette. ``Or are 
you going to say, `Let's fix this problem, do what you have to do, 
then come back and we accept you.' That's not what we got with 
them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
