<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Voting on Tax Compromise Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The house is set to vote today on the  
Republican plan for a 10-year, $792 billion tax cut in defiance of 
repeated veto threats from President Clinton. The Senate is 
expected to follow later in the day or tomorrow. GOP leaders will 
not send the bill to the White House until September, hoping to 
build public support during the August recess. Clinton and most 
Democrats on Capitol Hill prefer that projected budget surpluses be 
used to first safeguard Social Security and Medicare. 

</P>
<P>
	Nevada Gets Help To Fight Fires  
</P>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Reinforcements are being sent from around the  
West today to help fight dozens of lightning-sparked fires that 
have burned more than 300 square miles of northern Nevada range 
land. The fires had charred an estimated 200,000 acres by early 
today, threatening ranches and forcing closures along Interstate 
80. Early this morning, a 10-mile stretch of the I-80 between 
Argenta and Battle Mountain was closed for several hours as flames 
came within a quarter mile of the highway. 

</P>
<P>
	Kurdish Rebels Agree To Leave Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- In a dramatic step in their 15-year war,  
Kurdish rebels agreed today to heed the call of their imprisoned 
leader to lay down their arms and withdraw to bases outside Turkey. 
Abdullah Ocalan, who was sentenced to death in June, urged his 
followers on Tuesday to give up the armed struggle and pull out of 
southeast Turkey by Sept. 1. ``Our party openly declares its full 
compliance with comrade president Ocalan's call,'' the rebel group 
said in a statement. Earlier, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said his 
government will not ``bargain'' over the Kurdish question. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinian Meeting Postponed  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- A reconciliation meeting scheduled next week  
between PLO chairman Yasser Arafat and the leader of a radical 
Palestinian faction has been postponed. Nayef Hawatmeh, the leader 
of the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, will not 
be able to travel to Cairo for the Wednesday meeting, group 
spokesman Ali Badran said today. He said the meeting will be 
postponed ``for not less than ten days.'' Arafat is seeking to 
unite the Palestinian ranks before he begins the final stage of 
negotiations with Israel for a Palestinian statehood. 

</P>
<P>
	Montenegro Seeks New Confederation  
</P>
<P>
	PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Montenegro, Serbia's rebellious  
partner in Yugoslavia, today proposed abolishing the current 
federation and forming a loose confederation with a different name. 
If Serbia rejects a draft proposal for sweeping changes, Montenegro 
will hold a referendum on independence, the republic's leaders 
said. The proposal would change the name of Yugoslavia to the 
``Association of Montenegro and Serbia,'' abolish the current 
constitution and introduce separate army commands. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan May Cancel Boeing Order  
</P>
<P>
	TACOMA, Wash. (AP) -- Taiwan's flagship airline reportedly has  
been told by the Taiwanese government to cancel an order for 12 
Boeing 777s in protest of the Clinton administration's mainland 
China policy. Boeing had been expecting the $2 billion deal to be 
formally announced at any time. Taiwan's China Airlines signed a 
letter of intent to buy the jets in 1995. Citing industry and 
congressional sources, the Tacoma News Tribune reported today that 
China Airlines is expected to announce a major purchase of A-340 
planes from the European consortium Airbus Industrie. 

</P>
<P>
	Hindu Group Takes On Mother Teresa  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- The vice president of a radical Hindu  
group said today that the Vatican was acting with undue haste to 
canonize Mother Teresa, a news agency reported. Giriraj Kishore, of 
the Vishwa Hindu Parishad, or World Hindu Council, said that the 
Vatican's intention in rushing the canonization is to encourage 
Christian missionary activity in India, Mother Teresa's adopted 
home, the Press Trust of India reported. The Hindu Council has led 
a campaign against missionaries, who it argues are forcing poor 
Indians to convert. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Gains 6 Early On  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average is up six  
points in today's early going. Losers on the New York Stock 
Exchange hold a 9-8 lead over gainers. The Nasdaq Composite Index 
is down a point. 

</P>
<P>
	Hollinquest To Miss Four Games  
</P>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Green Bay Packers linebacker Lamont  
Hollinquest will miss the team's first four games this season for 
violating the NFL's substance-abuse policy, a newspaper said today. 
The Green Bay Press-Gazette said Hollinquest, who was signed by the 
Packers on Tuesday after having been waived by the Kansas City 
Chiefs, would not identify the substance for which he tested 
positive. But it said he confirmed he tested positive twice over a 
short span of time this spring, prompting the suspension. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
