<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna Starts External Review System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna U.S. Healthcare, the nation's largest  
health insurer, says its HMO members can now appeal coverage 
denials to independent doctor panels. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna is not the first health plan to offer such an external  
review process, but it is now the biggest. Congress is debating 
whether to mandate all health maintenance organizations to offer an 
external review system. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna, which in January announced its intention to start such a  
program, has agreed to be bound by the decisions of the independent 
doctor review boards. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna has contracted with Hayes Plus, The Center for Health  
Dispute Resolution, Island Peer Review Organization and CORE. The 
firms contract with doctors who will conduct the reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	About 5.6 million of Aetna's 16 million members have access to  
the program. Consumers who are in Aetna's self-insured plans or 
Aetna's indemnity or preferred provider organization plans are not 
eligible for the external reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	The external review will generally be available to HMO members  
who have exhausted Aetna's internal grievance or appeals procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Members may request an external review if Aetna denies coverage  
after the internal appeals panel has determined that the proposed 
service is not covered because it is unnecessary or inappropriate, 
or is experimental or investigational in nature. The cost of the 
treatment or service at issue must exceed $500. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
