<HEADLINE> Dollar Up After Slump Vs. Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar slumped against the yen and the euro  
Thursday but ended the day higher thanks to a late rally on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0756, down  
from $1.0771 late Wednesday. The dollar also was quoted at 114.30 
Japanese yen, up slightly from 114.29. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trading day, the dollar dipped against both  
currencies on renewed concerns that the Fed may raise interest 
rates when it meets on Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Two economic reports Thursday increased worries about a rate  
increase. One showed a slowing of worker productivity in the 
April-June quarter, and another showed a sharp rise in a key gauge 
of labor costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Both suggested higher rates could be on the way, which could  
hurt U.S. stock and bond markets. The dollar often suffers as 
foreign investors pull their funds out of American investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4878 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4844, and 1.4962 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4902. The British 
pound fell to $1.6129 from $1.6223. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8185 German 
marks, up from 1.8159; and 6.0976 French francs, up from 6.0901. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
