<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 30-Year Mortgages Rise to 7.89 Pct. / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages rose to 7.89 percent this week, reaching the 
highest level in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The average was up from 7.70 percent last week, according to a  
weekly survey released Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage 
company. This week's average rate on 30-year mortgages was the 
highest since the end of May 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortgages rates have been on an upward climb. So far this year,  
average rates on a 30-year mortgage have hit a low of 6.74 percent 
set at the end of January and a new high set this week. The 
previous high for this year of 7.71 percent was set the week ending 
July 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 7.45 percent this week, up from the average of 7.29 
percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 6.09 percent this week, also up from 5.99 
percent the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bond market has been very volatile in the past week, not  
sure whether inflation would remain subdued or if it would increase 
slightly, thus causing the Federal Reserve to tighten credit,'' 
said Robert Van Order, Freddie Mac's chief economist. ``That 
uncertainty pushed all interest rates higher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Mortgage Bankers Association reported Wednesday  
that mortgage loan applications for the week ending July 30 were 
down 20.8 percent compared to the same week last year. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
