<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Adopts Station Ownership Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission adopted  
rules today that partially relax existing restrictions on the 
number of local stations a single broadcasting company can control. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission voted 4-1 to loosen an existing rule that forbids  
a single company from owning more than one local TV station in a 
given market. Under the changes approved today, a company could own 
two TV stations in the same market if there were at least eight 
other competitors after the deal. The top four stations cannot 
combine. Common ownership could also be permitted if one of the 
stations was failing. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also voted 4-1 to alter a current rule that prohibits  
ownership of radio and TV stations in the same market. Under the 
changes, a company could own two TV stations and six radio stations 
are long as there are enough other media voices in that market. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also voted to provide some ``grandfather'' relief  
to companies that already have been granted waivers to own 
combinations of radio and TV stations. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC also clamped down on local marketing agreements -- which  
currently allow one TV station to operate another TV station in the 
same market, but not actually own it. Under today's rules, a TV 
station that provides more than 15 percent of weekly programming to 
another station could be considered the owner of that second 
station. 
</P>
<P>
	Stations that entered into such agreements before November 1996  
would also be grandfathered until 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate over broadcast ownership has pitted public interest  
advocates who fear that greater consolidation will mean less 
diversity of content against some industry groups who say stations 
must face certain financial realities to stay on the air. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of media ownership has been contentious at the  
commission and around Washington. A similar FCC proposal in the 
winter drew attacks from top telecommunications lawmakers, who said 
the measures did not give broadcasters enough regulatory relief. 
</P>
<P>
	The Media Access Project, a public-interest law firm, opposes  
permitting increased broadcast consolidation, saying that it 
reduces the diversity of ownership, and therefore, of content, 
available to audiences. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that there are many more stations out there is  
dwarfed by the fact that over the last 15 years the number of 
entities owning the stations has reduced,'' said Andy Schwartzman, 
president of the Media Access Project. He is concerned that without 
clear definitions of what constitutes ownership, companies are able 
to skirt federal restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who want to push the limits have been able to do  
essentially whatever they wanted,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
