<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holocaust Insurance Money Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence Eagleburger, chairman of a  
Holocaust-era insurance claims commission, has resolved a key 
dispute over the current value of policies held by Jewish victims 
of the Nazis. 
</P>
<P>
	This could clear the way for payment of claims beginning later  
in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a participant, Eagleburger decided to place a  
``real value'' of about 10 times the prewar face value on policies 
issued by the German insurance company Allianz. 
</P>
<P>
	Eagleburger, a former secretary of state, used a complex formula  
linked in part to long-term German bonds. A five-day period for 
registering objections ended Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	An aide to the commission vice chairman, Neal Sher, said some  
responses were received, but she did not know if they were 
objecting to Eagleburger's action. 
</P>
<P>
	Eagleburger stepped in when the commission could not agree on a  
formula that would have determined current values on policies taken 
out some six decades ago by factoring in inflation and interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Some European insurers have questioned the valuation formula and  
indicated they may pull out of the process. 
</P>
<P>
	``They could do whatever they want,'' Elan Steinberg, executive  
director of the World Jewish Congress, said in an interview. ``But 
the consumer and state insurance regulators would not look kindly 
to insurance companies reneging on their commitments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next step is a meeting of the commission at the end of the  
month in London to adopt a process for compiling lists of policy 
holders and communicating with the families of the victims of Nazi 
persecution. 
</P>
<P>
	The aim is to begin payments at the end of October.  
</P>
<P>
	The commission has representatives from five major European  
companies, Jewish groups and American regulators. Earlier, they 
agreed on a formula for payment on policies issued in Eastern 
European countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
