<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tennessee Man Claims Big Game Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- When Randy Kerfoot saw that the winning numbers  
for the $116 million Big Game jackpot matched the numbers on his 
ticket, he did a double take. He even went online to verify the 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took it a while to really sink in, and I don't think  
anybody took their eyes off that ticket all night,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It may still take Kerfoot a while get used to being an instant  
multi-millionaire. The East Ridge, Tenn., resident was the sole 
winner of Tuesday's drawing. By selecting the lump-sum option on 
his Quik Pik ticket, Kerfoot's winnings came to about $59 million, 
or $38.9 million after taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia Lottery Corp. officials said it was the largest payout  
to a single winner since the state lottery began in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerfoot worked as parts and service director for an Infiniti  
dealership in Chattanooga. Usually, he said goodbye to his boss 
every Friday with the words, ``I'll see you Monday unless I hit the 
lottery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he struck it big, he made good on his promise.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm out of here,'' he told his boss minutes before appearing  
at a news conference Wednesday to claim his prize. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerfoot intends to begin enjoying his leisure now that he is a  
wealthy man. His wife, Sandy, will continue working for a Toyota 
dealership, but only until she trains someone to replace her as 
controller and office manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The first major purchase for the couple may be two new cars,  
since both drive company-provided vehicles. A new house also may be 
in the offing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had just re-mortgaged our house so we could fix it up,''  
Mrs. Kerfoot said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the winnings also will go to charity, including the  
Ronald McDonald House, they said. The Kerfoots met as teen-agers 
working for a McDonald's restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	They have two daughters, ages 18 and 16, and a granddaughter.  
</P>
<P>
	The Big Game is played in seven states: Massachusetts, Georgia,  
Illinois, Maryland, Michigan, Virginia and New Jersey. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
