<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 09:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race Car Driver Waltrip To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Darrell Waltrip said today it's true -- he is  
retiring after next season. 
</P>
<P>
	In an emotion-choked announcement at Indianapolis Motor  
Speedway, one of stock car racing's legendary drivers confirmed 
what has been widely reported for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 52-year-old three-time Winston Cup champion is calling his  
final season a ``victory tour.'' Waltrip, who hasn't won since 1992 
and rarely misses a punchline, nailed this one on the nose. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be kind of a fake tour, kind of a farce if we didn't  
get at least one victory,'' Waltrip said. ``Winning a race now 
would be just as special as winning that first one in 1975.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In making his announcement before qualifying for the sixth  
Brickyard 400 at Indy, Waltrip broke down in tears and summoned his 
wife to the podium for support. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leaving this sport, hanging up my helmet, that's hard to talk  
about,'' said Waltrip, the man who stormed into racing and earned 
the nickname ``Jaws'' for his loud mouth now choking back sobs. 
``I've done this for 40 years. Ever since I was 12 years old, we'd 
get up, put on our racing gear and go to the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always thought about the future. What am I going to do  
next year? If I don't win this week, I'll get 'em next week. Well, 
I'm running out of next weeks. That's really the bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, a Kentucky native who lives in Franklin, Tenn., leads  
all active Winston Cup drivers with 84 career victories but has not 
won a race since Darlington in September 1992. He finished 25th in 
the most recent series race, the Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono 
Raceway, and is 38th in the season points. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip sold his team last year after owning it for eight years,  
citing sponsor disputes and other financial reasons. At the time, 
he said the 1999 season would be his last. He changed his mind when 
asked by Travis Carter and Carl Haas to drive the No. 66 KMart Ford 
Taurus for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, who has frequently used the former champion's  
provisional to keep his career going, vowed to qualify consistently 
in the top 25 with a new car -- trimmed with flames instead of 
Waltrip's favorite chrome look -- that was unveiled today. 
</P>
<P>
	``There should be no excuse for me and this car to miss races,''  
Waltrip said. ``This car should not need a provisional.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
