<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12:40 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Three Killed in Alabama Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	PELHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Three people were shot to death this morning  
at two businesses in a suburb south of Birmingham and a former 
employee at one of the firms was arrested, police said. Police said 
the 34-year-old suspect, who was not immediately named, was 
arrested ``after a brief scuffle'' when officers approached after 
forcing his car to a shoulder of I-65 in nearby Chilton County. 

</P>
<P>
	House Nears Tax Cut Bill Vote  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Offering a multitude of tax breaks for average  
taxpayers and special interests, the Republican-controlled Congress 
opened debate today on the final version of a 10-year, $792 billion 
tax cut in defiance of repeated veto threats from President 
Clinton. The House plans to vote on the bill later today, with the 
Senate expected to follow later today or tomorrow. GOP leaders 
gained key support from a handful of Republican Senate moderates by 
inserting new items aimed at low-income workers, affordable housing 
and people paying for dependent care, officials said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Confirms Holbrooke to U.N.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today confirmed veteran diplomat  
Richard Holbrooke as U.N. ambassador, filling a post that has stood 
vacant through military conflicts in the Balkans and the Persian 
Gulf. The 81-16 vote ended a 14-month odyssey for Holbrooke, 58, 
the Clinton administrator's top international troubleshooter and 
the architect of the 1995 agreement that brought peace to Bosnia. 
In contrast to the long delay, the Senate debated the nomination 
for only 35 minutes. 

</P>
<P>
	Murrah Plaza Reopens in Oklahoma  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The plaza adjacent to where the Alfred P.  
Murrah Federal Building once stood reopened quietly today, a serene 
space for workers and visitors to stop amid the sounds of a 
cascading fountain. The plaza used to be a perfect lunchtime 
hangout, with workers eating from brown bags in the midday sun. 
That was before April 19, 1995, when a bomb ripped apart the 
building, killing 168 people and injuring hundreds of others. ``For 
some of us there's bad memories here, but it's a lot nicer now,'' 
said John Cresswell, who was a GSA maintenance mechanic at the 
Murrah building. 

</P>
<P>
	Report Calls Los Alamos Probe 'Flawed'  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI's espionage case against a Los Alamos  
weapons scientist was ``flawed from the outset'' because 
authorities identified a number of other suspects, but failed to 
investigate them, a congressional report revealed today. The report 
also disclosed that in a polygraph test in February when the 
scientist, Wen Ho Lee, was asked if he had passed nuclear secrets 
``to any unauthorized person,'' he failed the test. The report by 
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee outlines missteps over 
three years that prevented the FBI from establishing a strong case 
against the scientist. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Honors Former Presidents  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former President Jimmy Carter and his wife  
Rosalynn and former President Gerald Ford will receive the nation's 
highest civilian honor, the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the 
White House announced today. Carter and his wife will be honored 
Monday at a ceremony in Atlanta at the Carter Center. Ford and 
seven other people will receive their awards Wednesday at the White 
House. Other recipients include Lloyd M. Bentsen, Clinton's first 
Treasury secretary, and Edgar M. Bronfman Sr., president of the 
World Jewish Congress. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Wants To Appoint Khmer Judges  
</P>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- The United Nations, concerned about  
the fairness of Cambodia's judiciary, wants to appoint a majority 
of the judges for a proposed trial of Khmer Rouge leaders, a 
government official said today. A U.N. legal team will arrive in 
Cambodia later this month with a proposal for a tribunal of five or 
seven judges, a majority to be U.N.-appointed, said an official 
close to the negotiations. The proposed tribunal will try Khmer 
Rouge leaders blamed for the deaths of an estimated 1.7 million 
Cambodians during the group's rule in the late 1970s. 

</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales Top Expectations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales at the most of nation's biggest retailers  
rose to better-than-expected levels in July, with hot weather and 
the economy's continued strength giving Americans incentive to 
shop. Warmer-than-normal weather through much of the country sent 
consumers heading to the stores both to escape the heat and buy 
seasonal items such as air conditioners, inflatable pools and 
bathing suits. The strong July sales reported today followed big 
gains the prior two months. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Drops 25; Nasdaq Down 20  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 25.96 points at 10,648.81. Declining issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led advancers 1,991-731. The Nasdaq was down 20.22 
at 2,519.78. 

</P>
<P>
	Sharpe May Miss Game in Australia  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Denver Bronco's tight end Shannon Sharpe,  
already unhappy about traveling to Australia and dealing with its 
``rude'' people, sprained his ankle during today's practice in 
Sydney. The injury threatens to keep him out of Saturday's game in 
Sydney against the San Diego Chargers. Broncos doctors examined 
both his knee and ankle and concluded Sharpe had a sprained ankle. 
Broncos coach Mike Shanahan said he didn't think the injury would 
require a magnetic resonance imaging test. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
