<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Net IPOs See Turnaround </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Investors shrugged off the months-long slide  
in Internet stocks Thursday to give a warm welcome to initial 
public offerings by three Web-focused companies. 
</P>
<P>
	However, they were less enthusiastic to two other Internet  
companies, barely budging on one while sending the other below its 
opening price. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in the holding company Internet Capital Group and  
networking specialist Mission Critical Software both soared in 
their Nasdaq debuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet Capital more than doubled from its offering price of  
$12 to $24.43 3/4. Houston-based Mission Critical rose 58 percent from 
its $16 offering price to $25.43 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Considered almost invincible early this year, online stocks  
appear to have reached their peak in April, when the luster began 
to wear off for investors. The 40-stock Dow Jones Internet Index 
has shed more than 40 percent of its value since it hit an all-time 
high on April 13. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, however, the index rose 4 percent, while both the  
technology heavy Nasdaq composite and Dow Jones industrial average 
posted gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great day for Internet Capital and a validation for  
the business of e-commerce and the role it's going to play in our 
economy over the next five to 10 years,'' said Walter Buckley, 
chairman and chief executive for the Wayne, Pa.-based company. 
</P>
<P>
	The company holds interests in 35 Web-based companies. Proceeds  
from the stock sale will be used to increase those holdings and 
invest in new ventures, Buckley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Internet company, HomeStore.com, a Thousand Oaks,  
Calif.-based provider of online real estate listings, rose to 
$22.75 from its $20 offering price. 
</P>
<P>
	HomeStore had doubled its asking price on Wednesday, despite the  
recent bashing of Internet IPOs, on advice from chief underwriter 
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We raised a significant amount of capital. We're going to use  
that to keep growing,'' said HomeStores chairman and chief 
executive Stuart Wolff. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was less generous to two other companies that debuted  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Interactive Pictures Corp., a multimedia company based in Oak  
Ridge, Tenn., slid initially from its $18 asking price to $17.75 
before finishing at $19. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobalt Group opened at $9.87 1/2, below its $11 asking price.  
Shares closed at $8.31 1/4 for the Seattle-based company that designed 
and maintains Web sites for more than 3,000 auto dealerships 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet Capital's success may have resulted more from investor  
uncertainty than resurging confidence in the Web sector, said Brian 
G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. 
Because the company invests in a wide range of Internet stocks, 
investors don't face the risk of trying to pick a winner 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost like buying a basket or a mini-mutual fund.  
They're diversifying their risk,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mixed response to Thursday's five IPOs also suggests that  
investors have become more sophisticated in choosing Web stocks. 
That sophistication means the volatility is likely to continue in 
the near term as investors try to sort out winners from losers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a certain amount of bottom fishing that takes place  
in groups or sectors like this when they become oversold. The 
Internet sector is probably one that stands out this week as one 
that's been truly oversold,'' said Internet Capital's Buckley. 
``There's a certain constituency that's going to own these Internet 
stocks for the long haul. I think in stocks in general have proved 
their noteworthiness and their viability.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
