<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 5, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	House Seeks HMO Compromise  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats reached agreement with a group  
of breakaway Republicans today on legislation to strengthen the 
rights of patients dealing with HMOs, officials said. The measure 
is designed to lower barriers to medical care -- at emergency rooms, 
from specialists and elsewhere -- that are imposed by insurance 
companies. Patients would have the right to a review by an 
independent panel if they believed they were wrongly denied 
treatment. They would also be permitted to sue. 

</P>
<P>
	Swissair Offers To Settle in Crash  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Swissair offered today to take  
responsibility for last year's crash that killed 229 people off the 
coast of Nova Scotia and said it would settle with the victims' 
families if they agree not to pursue punitive damages. An attorney 
for Swissair told a judge that the airline would accept liability, 
as would two of the three other co-defendants -- Boeing and Delta 
Airlines. Swissair is facing claims totaling $16 billion from 
families of U.S. victims suing on grounds of gross negligence. 

</P>
<P>
	Republicans Push $792B Tax Cut  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A 10-year, $792 billion Republican tax cut,  
sure to be vetoed by President Clinton but embraced by the GOP as a 
bedrock political issue, hurtled toward final congressional passage 
today. The House passed the bill 221-206, and final Senate approval 
was expected by early evening. With little chance of becoming law, 
the bill will serve mainly as a defining issue between Republicans 
and Democrats in the 2000 struggle for control of Congress and the 
race for the White House. The bill would be the largest tax cut 
since 1981. 

</P>
<P>
	Los Alamos Probe Reported 'Flawed'  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI investigation of a Los Alamos weapons  
scientist was plagued by errors, poor judgment and delays that 
probably doomed the case, senators said today in a report into the 
alleged theft of nuclear secrets by China. The report said the 
scientist, Wen Ho Lee, had signed a waiver three years ago allowing 
his computer to be searched, but the FBI and government lawyers did 
not learn of it until this year. When the computer was finally 
examined, it was found that Lee had shifted thousands of 
super-secret weapons codes into an unsecured computer system. 

</P>
<P>
	Barton Victims Had Loaned Him Money  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Some of the people day trader Mark O. Barton shot  
had loaned him money to cover losses, and police said today he was 
deliberate with his shots -- at times he fired from point-blank 
range. Detective Steve Walden said it wasn't clear whether Barton 
had specific people in mind when he entered two brokerages last 
week and killed nine people and wounded 13, hours before killing 
himself. But Barton was able to shoot people at close range, 
including some under desks or at their chairs in the small offices, 
Walden said. 

</P>
<P>
	Kurd Rebels Agree To Leave Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Kurdish rebels accepted a cease-fire call  
by their imprisoned leader, saying today they would withdraw from 
the battlefields of southeast Turkey. Abdullah Ocalan, sentenced to 
death in June, urged his followers to unilaterally pull out of 
southeast Turkey by Sept. 1 to open the way for dialogue with the 
government. It would be the rebels' first retreat from their 
mountain hideouts in the 15-year battle between their Kurdistan 
Workers Party, or PKK, and Turkey's military. 

</P>
<P>
	GM Markets Warner Bros. Minivan  
</P>
<P>
	BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- Warner Bros. rolled out its latest  
production today, but it's coming to a car lot rather than a 
theater near you -- a General Motors minivan bearing Bugs Bunny and 
other logos owned by the big movie studio. The Chevy Venture Warner 
Bros. van is the first part of a four-year marketing partnership 
between GM and Warner, with the automaker using the studio's 
movies, TV shows and Looney Tunes cartoons as a carrot to help sell 
cars. It is believed to be the first big-ticket consumer item 
labeled with an entertainment logo. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Surges 119.05 to 10,793.82  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks managed their strongest rally in more  
than a week today as bargain-hunting investors stepped into a 
market driven down by fears of higher interest rates. At the close, 
the Dow industrials were up 119.05 at 10,793.82. Declining issues 
on the New York Stock Exchange outnumbered advancers 1,823-1,198. 
The Nasdaq was up 25.82 at 2,565.82. 

</P>
<P>
	Driver Waltrip To Retire in 2000  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- NASCAR stock car great Darrell Waltrip  
announced today that he's retiring after next season. With a finale 
that he's calling ``Victory Tour 2000,'' Waltrip will finish up one 
of the most remarkable, outspoken, fun-loving careers motorsports 
has ever seen. Waltrip, 52, has won three Winston Cup championships 
and leads active drivers with 84 victories, tied for third all-time 
with Bobby Allison. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  



  	   	
