<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Passes Tax Cut Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defying repeated veto threats from President  
Clinton, the House today passed a Republican 10-year, $792 billion 
tax cut offering a multitude of tax breaks for average taxpayers 
and special interests. The vote was 221-206 to send the bill to the 
Senate, where expected final passage is scheduled for this evening. 
Clinton, addressing a Democratic rally at the Capitol before the 
vote, responded: ``We say first things first,'' urging any budget 
surplus go first for preserving Social Security and Medicare and 
reducing government debt. 

</P>
<P>
	Three Killed in Ala. Office Shootings  
</P>
<P>
	PELHAM, Ala. (AP) -- A man shot three people to death this  
morning in two industrial businesses on an Alabama highway, a week 
after a Mark O. Barton killed nine people in a shooting spree at 
offices in Atlanta. Police in this Birmingham suburb said the 
34-year-old suspect was arrested after officers forced his car to a 
shoulder of Interstate 65. Police said the suspect worked at 
Ferguson Enterprises, where two of the victims were shot inside the 
company, and was a former employee of Post Airgas, where another 
victim was shot to death a short time later. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Attacks Clinton-Gore Policy  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Bill Bradley told black activists today that poor  
children have suffered from the inattention of the Clinton-Gore 
administration. ``After the first two-term Democratic president 
since Franklin Roosevelt the number of children in poverty in 
America has barely blipped down,'' said Bradley. Vice President Al 
Gore's only competition for the Democratic presidential nomination 
spoke to the annual convention of Jesse Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH 
Coalition. Gore will address the convention Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	Montenegro: Abolish Yugoslav Federation  
</P>
<P>
	PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a possible prelude to a bid for  
independence, Montenegro said today it wants to abolish the 
Yugoslav federation in favor of a loose partnership with Serbia 
that would allow the two republics to go their own ways. The 
proposal is a direct challenge to Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic, who moved federal troops into Montenegro in an attempt 
to stifle its autonomy ambitions during the recent Kosovo crisis. 
Milosevic is believed to be almost certain to reject the proposal, 
in which case Montenegro says it would call a referendum on full 
independence. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Confirms Holbrooke to U.N.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an 81-16 vote, the Senate today confirmed  
veteran diplomat Richard Holbrooke as U.N. ambassador, filling a 
post that has stood vacant through military conflicts in the 
Balkans and the Persian Gulf. Holbrooke is the architect of the 
1995 agreement that brought peace to Bosnia. The Cabinet-level post 
at the U.N. headquarters in New York has been vacant since Bill 
Richardson left in September to become energy secretary. 

</P>
<P>
	Robert Downey Jr. Sentenced to Jail  
</P>
<P>
	MALIBU, Calif. (AP) -- Actor Robert Downey Jr. was sentenced to  
three years in prison today for violating probation from a 1996 
drug conviction. Municipal Court Judge Lawrence Mira, who presided 
over Downey's original case in 1996, said he had given the 
Oscar-nominated actor many chances to rehabilitate himself. But, he 
said, the actor has manipulated doctors and psychiatrists who have 
examined his progress. 

</P>
<P>
	Skin Cancer Defense Explored  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sun-damaged skin cells that could become  
cancerous are killed by a special protein produced in sunburned 
tissue, according to a new study. Researchers at the University of 
Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center report in the journal Science 
that sunburned skin cells make a cell-killing protein called Fas 
that guards the body against skin cancer by killing genetically 
flawed skin cells. Skin cancer is the most common form of cancer. 
About 1 million cases are diagnosed annually in the United States. 

</P>
