<HEADLINE> FBI Director Admits Agency Mistakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The head of the FBI has admitted the agency's  
Boston operation made ``significant mistakes'' in its past dealings 
with organized crime informants. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot of mistakes to account for,'' FBI Director Louis  
Freeh said Wednesday. ``We are not an agency that makes excuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for alleged mobsters including Francis ``Cadillac  
Frank'' Salemme and Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi have asked a 
federal judge to dismiss racketeering charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Cardinale, Salemme's attorney, said Freeh's admission  
sounded like an attempt to ward off bad publicity if the judge 
throws out the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're trying to put a shine on a sneaker,'' he said. ``It  
isn't going to be pretty for the FBI. I think they know they're 
about to get croaked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinale said a grand jury is investigating the roles played by  
at least two FBI agents. A spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorney's 
office, Samantha Martin, said she could not comment on grand jury 
investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeh also said the bureau would consider adding James  
``Whitey'' Bulger's name to the 10 Most Wanted List. Bulger, an 
alleged crime boss from Boston, has been on the lam since his 
indictment in January 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinale and other defense attorneys have argued that the  
charges should be dismissed because Bulger and Flemmi were given 
permission to commit crimes in exchange for information they gave 
the FBI on the mafia. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Mark Wolf has not yet ruled on the requests.  
</P>
<P>
	Freeh said the improper behavior was largely in the 1970s and  
'80s and said the FBI has since revamped its informant policies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
