<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BASF Reports Drop in Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUDWIGSHAFEN, Germany (AP) -- BASF AG, the world's second-largest  
chemicals concern after DuPont Co., suffered worse-than-expected 
declines in first-half profits and sales despite an upturn in the 
second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Profits slid 30 percent to 992 million euros, or about $1  
billion, compared with the same period last year, while group sales 
dropped 4.7 percent to 14 billion euros, or about $15 billion, the 
German company said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both figures failed to meet analyst forecasts. In Thursday's  
trading in Frankfurt, BASF's shares fell more than 4 percent after 
rising 5.3 percent Wednesday amid merger speculation sparked by Dow 
Chemical's agreement to acquire Union Carbide. The overall Xetra 
DAX stock index was down 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	BASF said an upturn in second-quarter sales volumes meant  
revenues only declined 1.1 percent in that quarter compared with an 
8.2 percent decline in the first three months of the year. BASF's 
European operations bore the brunt of the overall sales decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings also were hurt by a fine of 210 million euros, or $225  
million, levied by the U.S. Justice Department for BASF's role in a 
vitamins price-fixing case. Further charges could arise from civil 
class-action lawsuits under way in the United States, BASF said. 
</P>
<P>
	BASF said it sees full-year group sales matching last year's  
27.6 billion euros, but said lower first-half profit margins will 
hurt full-year earnings. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
