<HEADLINE> 3 Bodies Returned From Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The remains of three U.S. Air Force officers  
killed in the Vietnam War have been identified and will be given to 
their families for burial in the United States, the Defense 
Department said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	They are Maj. Charles F. Morley of Warrensburg, Mo., Capt.  
Thomas C. Daffron of Pinckneyville, Ill., and a third officer whose 
name was not released by the Pentagon at the request of his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Morley and Daffron were flying a night strike mission over  
Khammouan Province in Laos on Feb. 18, 1970, when their F-4C 
Phantom jet was struck by enemy anti-aircraft fire and crashed. 
Teams of U.S. and Laotians investigating the crash site in 1995 
recovered human remains and items related to the crew. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Army Central Identification Laboratory in Hawaii  
confirmed the identification of the two men. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon released no details on the loss or recovery of the  
third officer, whose name was withheld. 
</P>
<P>
	There are now 2,057 Americans unaccounted for from the Vietnam  
War. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
