<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rejects Verdict Vs. Dow Jones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- A federal judge has dismissed a $22.7 million  
libel verdict against Dow Jones &AMP; Co. over a 1993 Wall Street 
Journal article and scheduled a new trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 22-page ruling last April, U.S. District Judge Ewing  
Werlein Jr. notified the parties in the case that he would dismiss 
the remainder of an original $222.7 million verdict won by Money 
Management Analytical Research Group Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	He formalized that decision Monday and also set a Nov. 5 trial  
date to hear claims that the now-defunct Houston investment firm 
was libeled. MMAR contends that, in an article chronicling the 
company's relationship with a pension fund, reporter Laura Jereski 
published false and defamatory statements that forced it out of 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	In the earlier ruling, Werlein said MMAR failed to disclose  
audiotapes that would have supported Dow Jones' defense at the 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1997, a federal jury returned the $222.7 million  
judgment, the largest libel verdict ever delivered by a jury. Two 
months later, the judge cut the verdict to $22.7 million after he 
heard arguments that MMAR routinely recorded clients' phone calls 
but could not produce one conversation that showed it lost a client 
because of the article. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones attorney David Donaldson has acknowledged inaccuracies  
in the story. But he said the punitive damages would be 
inappropriate unless Ms. Jereski and her editors knew they were 
false. He said they believed the story was accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Dow Jones responded to Werlein's dismissal with a  
motion seeking sanctions against the defendant for failing to make 
the information about the tapes available during discovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones is seeking an estimated $3.5 million in court costs as  
a result of the plaintiff's omission about the taped information. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that motion will be granted,'' Richard Tofel, a Dow  
Jones spokesman, said today. ``We think it's meritorious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to MMAR attorney Kenneth Morris was not immediately  
returned. He has said the firm intends to retry the case. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
