<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM May Build Cars in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will consider becoming the  
first American automaker to build vehicles in Japan since before 
World War II in an effort to boost sales there. 
</P>
<P>
	GM, the world's largest automaker, sold only about 53,000 cars  
and trucks in Japan last year, a small number in a market where 
more than 4 million vehicles are sold each year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't be successful in Asia without being successful in  
Japan,'' GM spokesman Henry Wong said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wong said GM's strategy would include ``establishing a  
manufacturing presence'' in Japan, along with building its dealer 
base, importing models, and relying on its ties to Japan's Isuzu 
Motors Ltd. and Suzuki Motor Corp. Wong declined to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	GM owns 49 percent of Isuzu and 10 percent of Suzuki. Isuzu has  
been working on truck designs for GM, while Suzuki is known as a 
small-car specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Anya Hayes, an industry analyst with AutoPacific, said Japanese  
consumers might find GM cars more appealing if they were made in 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Japanese consumers look on American cars as somewhat lesser in  
quality, and producing in Japan would change that,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayes also said it would make sense for GM to use an Isuzu or  
Suzuki plant as a base, rather than building a new plant in a 
country that already has too much auto-building capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though the cars they import are cost-effective there,  
they would still save more by producing them in Japan,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Japanese companies have built several assembly plants in  
the United States and other countries, no foreign company assembles 
vehicles in Japan. Ford Motor Co. built cars in Japan before World 
War II. 
</P>
<P>
	That's likely to change now that GM and other foreign companies  
own large stakes of Japanese automakers, Hayes said. Ford owns 33 
percent of Mazda Motor Corp., while French automaker Renault SA 
owns 36.8 percent of Nissan Motor Co. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
