<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Suns Trade for Hardaway Likely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Penny Hardaway is on the verge of joining the  
Phoenix Suns, a major acquisition for a team that has almost no 
money under the salary cap and not a lot to offer in a trade. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the end, the Orlando Magic had little choice but to  
accept the Suns' offer of Pat Garrity, Danny Manning and two 
first-round draft picks. It was the only offer that remained on the 
table. 
</P>
<P>
	An announcement that the trade was completed was likely to come  
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a done deal until we get the league office on the  
phone and we have the transaction take place,'' Suns president 
Jerry Colangelo said Wednesday night. ``And we have not had that 
take place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Colangelo gave every indication that the Magic were prepared  
to go through with the trade. Hardaway has told Colangelo that he 
wants to go to the Suns, and the Magic apparently have reluctantly 
gone along. 
</P>
<P>
	``They told us that we had a deal in that we've agreed to what  
we're going to give them in terms of compensation,'' Colangelo 
said. ``We took care of our end of the business. That's why I keep 
saying we're waiting for Orlando to pull the trigger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There have been indications that Orlando's management was trying  
mightily to salvage more out of the deal than the Suns were 
offering, either by persuading Hardaway to stay and play for new 
Magic coach Doc Rivers or by finding another interested trading 
partner. 
</P>
<P>
	Magic general manager John Gabriel went home Wednesday evening  
without publicly giving his approval to the trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a huge decision for us, obviously,'' Gabriel said. ``I  
was in here until midnight trying to work this out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make the trade happen, Hardaway would sign a seven-year, $86  
million contract with Orlando, the largest allowed for a player 
with his experience under the NBA's collective bargaining 
agreement. Then he would be traded to Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be a major boost to the Suns, who endured a lackluster  
season this year and are handicapped in any efforts to improve by 
the new salary cap. The team used its new $2 million exception 
Wednesday to sign free-agent forward Rodney Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	If Hardaway joins the Suns, he would team with Jason Kidd as one  
of the most formidable backcourts in the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway, 28, has averaged 19 points in six NBA seasons, making  
the All-Star game four times. Nagging injuries have plagued him the 
last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Magic might be tempted to thwart Hardaway by refusing to  
sign him and allowing him to enter the free-agent market, where he 
could only sign a six-year deal for significantly less money. Only 
Chicago, the Los Angeles Clippers and Toronto appear to have the 
salary cap room to meet his demands. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Gabriel said such a scenario probably won't happen,  
leaving as the only alternatives the nearly impossible task of 
persuading Hardaway to stay in Orlando, or letting him go to 
Arizona. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
