<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Linda Alma    	
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Linda Alma, a high-kicking dancer who  
worked with leading Greek and French artists during her 30-year 
career, died Monday of cancer. She was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Alma was born Eleni Malioufa in Athens in 1926. She assumed  
a stage name and rose to fame as the partner of dancer Yannis 
Flery, with whom she moved to Paris in the late 1940s to work with 
French singing legends Edith Piaf, Yves Montand and Charles 
Aznavour. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Alma was best known to Greek audiences for her appearances  
in dance sequences in Greek movies, styled on 1950s Hollywood 
musicals, and her 1979 marriage to actor Manos Katrakis, who died 
in 1984. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Rudy Burckhardt    	
</P>
<P>
	SEARSMONT, Maine (AP) -- Rudy Burckhardt, a photographer,  
filmmaker and writer known for his portrayals of city life in New 
York, died Sunday at his summer home in Maine. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss-born Burckhardt, who emigrated to New York in 1935 and  
lived the rest of his life in Manhattan, drowned Sunday in a pond 
near his home. The death was ruled a suicide by Maine's chief 
medical examiner. 
</P>
<P>
	The World War II veteran earned a reputation for his photographs  
of street subjects from the late 1930s to the 1950s. His camera 
captured people on subways and images of the city's vast skyline. 
</P>
<P>
	His photographs are in permanent collections of the Museum of  
Modern Art and The Metropolitan Museum of Art. A film retrospective 
at the Museum of Modern Art honored him in 1987 for his 90-odd 
films using 16-millimeter film. 
</P>
<P>
	Some were comedies, but many were what his widow, Yvonne  
Jacquette, calls ``film poems,'' with poems used as subtitles. Some 
featured New York dancers mixed in with shots of Maine, where he 
spent his summers painting. 
</P>
<P>
	His memoirs include ``Mobile Homes'' in 1979 and ``Talking  
Pictures: The Photography of Rudy Burckhardt'' in 1994. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Mohammed Hadid    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Mohammed Hadid, an economist and politician who  
devoted his life to advocating democracy in Iraq, died in London on 
Tuesday. He was 92 and was admitted to a London hospital four days 
ago after an asthma attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Hadid, a graduate of the London School of Economics in the  
1920s, became Iraq's finance minister in 1949 when the country was 
ruled by the monarchy. He resigned after less than two months when 
the government failed to hold free elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Hadid was one of the founders of the opposition National  
Democratic Party in the early 1930s. He was instrumental in the 
July 14, 1958 revolution that toppled the monarchy and established 
the first republic in Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	Hadid served as the republic's first finance minister in the  
government of Abdel Karim Qassem. He resigned from the government 
and the National Democratic Party in 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterwards, Hadid established the National Progressive Party. He  
led it until 1963, when the Arab Baath Socialist Party pulled off a 
bloody coup and ruled Iraq for nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Baathists killed Qassem and detained Hadid without trial for  
a year until 1964, when he was acquitted by a military tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	Hadid later quit political life and went back into business. His  
negotiations with British oil companies led to the nationalization 
of most of Iraq's oil industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The government of Saddam Hussein barred him from leaving Iraq  
until four years ago, when he went to London to join his family. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Richard Olney    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Richard Olney, an American author of classic books  
about French cooking and wines, has died. He was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Olney, who is believed to have died several days ago, wrote more  
than 30 books on all aspects of French cooking and wines, as well 
as the culinary traditions of Provence, the sun-drenched region on 
the Mediterranean where many of the greatest lovers of French food 
have perfected their taste. 
</P>
<P>
	Olney is best known for two books: ``Simple French Food'' that  
was first published in 1974 and ``The French Menu Cookbook.'' He 
also wrote about some of France's greatest wines. 
</P>
<P>
	He received the National Tastemakers Award and his books are  
considered cooking classics. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Lynette Ricketson    	
</P>
<P>
	LAKE CITY, Fla. (AP) -- Lynette Ricketson, a newspaper publisher  
who didn't miss an edition despite a fire that destroyed the 
century-old offices of the Suwannee Democrat, died of cancer 
Saturday. She was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ricketson was president of Lake City-based Ricketson  
Newspapers Inc., which includes the Suwannee Democrat, the Branford 
News, the Jasper News and the Mayo Free Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include husband J. Thomas Ricketson; daughters Sherry  
Lynn Hamilton and Lucinda J. Harrison; and her mother, Lucille 
``Shug'' Shore. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Henry W. Sawyer III    	
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Henry W. Sawyer III, a civil liberties  
lawyer who won two landmark U.S. Supreme Court cases, died Saturday 
of lung cancer. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Sawyer, was a champion of liberal causes, a civil rights  
activist and an advocate for political outcasts. But he is best 
remembered for local lawsuits dealing with the separation of church 
and state. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1962, the Supreme Court ruled in Schempp vs. the Abington  
School District that the ceremonial reading of the Bible and prayer 
in public schools is unconstitutional. In 1971, the court ruled in 
Lemon vs. Kurtzman that public aid to parochial schools is 
unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	He was an at-large member of the Philadelphia City Council from  
1956 to 1959 and got a local law passed requiring that 1 percent of 
a building's construction budget be spent on public art. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965, he spent the summer in Mississippi, defending blacks'  
right to vote in court. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the former president of the local chapter of the American  
Civil Liberties Union and a former chairman of the local chapter of 
Americans for Democratic Action. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Zohara Schatz    	
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Zohara Schatz, an artist who designed the  
emblem of Israel's Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial, died Wednesday 
after a long illness. She was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Schatz, whose father founded Jerusalem's prestigious Bezalel  
art institute, was a fixture in the Jerusalem art scene. She 
designed numerous sculptures and decorative works throughout the 
city, including the six-branched menorah, or candelabra, that 
stands at the entrance to Yad Vashem. 
</P>
<P>
	The sculpture became the museum's emblem, commemorating the six  
million Jews who died in the Holocaust. It is lit once a year on 
Holocaust Remembrance Day. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1954, Ms. Schatz won the Israel Prize, an honor conferred by  
Israel's president on distinguished scholars, writers, artists and 
public figures. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Bernard Simon    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dr. Bernard Simon, who treated women disfigured  
by the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and helped lay the foundation 
for plastic surgery in Japan, died Sunday. He was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon passed away at The Mount Sinai Hospital, where he had  
worked before retiring in 1992. He had been chief of the Division 
of Plastic Surgery from 1965 to 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1955, Simon took part in the ``Hiroshima Project,'' where  
reconstructive surgery was done on a group of women who had been 
injured when the United States dropped an atomic bomb on Hiroshima 
in August 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	The project also trained Japanese surgeons, and set the stage  
for plastic surgery in Japan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
