<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bradley Urges Gore on Profiling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Bill Bradley said Thursday that if Vice President  
Al Gore is serious about stopping police departments from using 
racial profiling he should act now, rather than wait for the next 
millennium. ``I say, Why wait?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Gore said he would make the end of racial profiling,  
the police practice of singling out minorities for questioning at 
airports, on highways and on streets, ``the first civil rights act 
of the new century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to the annual convention of Jesse Jackson's  
Rainbow-PUSH Coalition, Bradley responded, ``Why doesn't he walk 
down the hall, put the executive order in front of the president 
and ask him to sign it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, Gore's only opponent for the Democratic presidential  
nomination, took pains to draw distinctions between his vision and 
the Clinton-Gore administration's civil rights record. But even as 
he did, he saluted the administration for its commitment to race 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	His speech and one by Gore on Saturday amount to separate  
auditions for an endorsement by Jackson and his army of grass-roots 
Democratic mobilizers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here's the man who's gotten millions and millions of votes for  
president himself. He's also probably registered more Democratic 
voters than anyone in history. It would be foolhardy to ignore 
him,'' said Paul Begala, Clinton's former political strategist. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson said no endorsement would be coming soon, calling this  
stage of the presidential campaign ``the exhibition season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a former New Jersey senator, said he is basing his  
presidential campaign on a theme of racial unity and, as president, 
would like to build a multiracial coalition to tackle economic 
disparities, poverty, gun control and health-care reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm staking my presidential campaign on the belief that over  
50 to 60 percent of Americans, including white Americans, want to 
have racial unity,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said the administration had not done enough to end  
poverty, especially among children. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the first two-term Democratic president since Franklin  
Roosevelt, the number of children in poverty in America has barely 
blipped down,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reducing the number of children in poverty in America should  
be the North Star for our society,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Roger Salazar said the administration had created  
``unprecedented'' prosperity, but that more remains to be done. 
</P>
<P>
	``The past 6 1/2 years have been just a start,'' Salazar said.  
</P>
<P>
	Minority advocates say racial profiling can prove fatal, citing  
the killings of young blacks by police in New York, Pittsburgh and 
Riverside, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton ordered federal officers -- only a fraction of  
the nation's police -- to collect data on the race and gender of 
those they arrest and then develop a plan to stop racial profiling. 
</P>
<P>
	David Bositis, a policy analyst at the Joint Center for  
Political and Economic Studies who has studied Jackson's popularity 
and the racial dynamic of national politics, said Bradley can 
barely hope to overcome Gore's popularity with black voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a dime's worth of difference between Al Gore and  
Bill Bradley,'' said Bositis. ``But I've got news for Bill Bradley: 
Bill Clinton is the most popular person among black America and Al 
Gore is right there next to him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
