<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am Games Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- No nerve-fraying penalty kicks or  
shirt-ripping celebrations this time. This was another women's 
soccer team from the United States, doing things its own way and 
enjoying it just as much. 
</P>
<P>
	And now the U.S. 18-and-under team has something in common with  
its sisters from the World Cup: a championship. In fact, a gold 
medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Catherine Reddick went solo, scoring after a series of  
magnificent moves in the first half, and goalie Hope Solo had an 
act of her own Thursday as the United States edged Mexico 1-0 in 
the Pan American Games final. 
</P>
<P>
	``The World Cup team was pressing on for the gold and they got  
it. You set your standards so high to be like them,'' Reddick said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully the World Cup is in my future. It's my goal right  
now. The Pan Ams is the biggest game of all of our lives right now. 
It's so special, right after the World Cup to live up to what they 
did. It's such a great experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reddick, a 17-year-old high school senior from Birmingham, Ala.,  
chest-trapped the ball near midfield, dribbled about 40 yards, 
juked two defenders in front of the penalty area and then drove a 
right-footed shot high over Mexican goalie Linny Quinones in the 
26th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw I had a shot and said, `Please go in.' And it went in,''  
Reddick said. 
</P>
<P>
	Solo and the Americans' defense made it last. Solo, who plays at  
the University of Washington, was unscored upon in the three 
matches she started. Her fully extended block of a shot by Iris 
Mora in the 53rd minute and her diving stop of a shot in the 
penalty area by Fatima Leyva in the 87th preserved the U.S. lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had our own expectations, because we are a different  
team,'' Solo said. ``We are not the USA team, not the World Cup 
team. So we had to establish our own expectations and distinguish 
ourselves. And it wasn't just because they won. 
</P>
<P>
	``But they intrigued us and they inspired us.''  
</P>
<P>
	Two American boxers put on inspired efforts, with mixed results  
</P>
<P>
	Super heavyweight Davin King moved into the final against Cuba's  
Alexis Rubalcaba by shutting out Argentina's Manuel Azar 4-0, 
staying outside and fighting defensively after building an early 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Darnell Wilson of Chicago lost 9-8 to Cuban star Jorge  
Gutierrez. The bout was tied 7-7, then Wilson took a one-point 
lead. Gutierrez tied it and scored a winning punch in the final 20 
seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``This shows me how far I have come,'' said Wilson, who gets a  
bronze medal. ``There are a lot of boxers leaving here with 
nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women's basketball team played Cuba in the semifinals.  
Americans Paul Goldstein and Cecil Mamiit played for the men's 
singles title in tennis, while teammate Tara Snyder took on Maria 
Vento of Venezuela for the women's crown. 
</P>
<P>
	The American soccer team bowed in a chorus line after its  
victory and took a lap around the field after getting the gold 
medals. The United States, tied by Mexico 1-1 in the preliminary 
round for its only blemish, outscored its opponents 22-2 in the 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico's best first-half scoring chance was foiled as Solo came  
to the front of the goal area to block a shot. The Mexicans got the 
rebound, but defender Karyn Hall cleared a shot off the goal line, 
giving Solo time to regain her feet. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. defender Nandy Pryce left in the first half when she took a  
rebound of her own clearing attempt in the face. And Becky Myers 
was forced out in the 80th minute after suffering a probable broken 
nose as she tried to head the ball and collided with Solo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We needed to show we belonged in this game,'' Mexican coach  
Leonardo Cuellar said. ``I feel we have a long way to go. We had a 
group here who came to give a good show. We have to respect the 
U.S. They are still 20 years ahead of us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
