<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise Amid Turmoil / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds rose for a second straight session  
Thursday, as turmoil in other fixed- rate investments led investors 
to seek the security of U.S. Treasurys. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 23/32  
point, or $7.18 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, a key 
influence on long-term borrowing costs, fell to 6.04 percent from 
6.09 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors sought the safety of government debt in uneven trading  
on an abrupt drop in the value of derivatives known as swaps and 
corporate bonds relative to the value of Treasurys. 
</P>
<P>
	The nongovernment debt markets declined amid vague rumors of  
financial problems at swap dealers, investment banks and other 
financial institutions. As a result, investors closed out positions 
involving those products and bought back Treasurys. 
</P>
<P>
	Derivatives are securities whose value is tied to, or derived  
from, an underlying asset, such as bonds. In the case of swaps, 
corporate treasurers try to protect their businesses from rising 
interest costs by trading in sophisticated securities that provide 
one party with a fixed return and the other with an interest rate 
that floats. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, when interest rates were rising rapidly, bad bets on  
interest rate derivatives caused significant losses for some 
companies and led to the bankruptcy of Orange County, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Also boosting the appeal of the safety of Treasurys were fears  
of building tensions between China and Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market's advance came despite a report that U.S.  
productivity growth decelerated in the second quarter to a 1.3 
percent annual rate -- its smallest increase since the second 
quarter of 1998. Productivity growth has been viewed as a major 
reason that the strong the U.S. economy has not resulted in a 
rebound in inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising inflation reduces the value of fixed-income investments  
like bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
rose 1/8 point to 5/32 point, while intermediate-term Treasurys rose 
5/16 to 15/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
fell to 4.71 percent while the discount fell to 4.59 percent, down 
0.04 percentage point from Wednesday's levels. Yields on six-month 
Treasurys fell to 4.93 percent as the discount fell to 4.74 
percent, down 0.04 percentage point. One-year yields fell to 5.01 
percent as the discount fell to 4.77 percent, down 0.05 percentage 
point. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.06 1/4 percent from Wednesday's 4.87 1/2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 3/16 point to 117 1/16. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.61 percent from 5.60 percent on 
Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
