<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 5, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Tech Stocks Keep Sinking  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The big selloff in Internet stocks that began  
quietly during the spring is suddenly accelerating, decimating the 
phenomenal gains achieved this year by many high-profile online 
companies. Considered almost invincible early this year, online 
stocks dragged down the technology-laden Nasdaq composite index for 
a fifth straight day yesterday, leaving it a painful 11.3 percent 
lower than the all-time high it reached July 16. The 40-stock Dow 
Jones Internet Index has shed more than 40 percent of its value 
since it hit an all-time high on April 13. Amazon.com is at 88 7/16 
after hitting a high of 221 1/4 in April. America Online is at 87 7/16 
compared to a 52-week high of 175 1/2. eBay's 52-week high was 234. 
It's now at 75 3/4. Marketwatch.com is off from 129 to 27 5/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq Down 11 Percent Since Peak  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The sell-off of tech stocks continues. The  
Nasdaq Composite Index has fallen 11.3 percent since its July 16 
record high close of 2,864.48. Traditionally, Wall Street considers 
a drop of at least 10 percent a correction, a milestone symbolizing 
weakness in markets. Yesterday, Internet bookseller Amazon.com fell 
6 7/16 to 88 7/16, while online auctioneer eBay dropped 8 5/8 to 75 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Loses 2.54; Nasdaq Falls 47.99  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks collapsed in the final  
half-hour of trading yesterday, deflating a rally fueled by a $9.3 
billion merger of Dow Chemical and Union Carbide. The broader 
market, plagued by fears of inflation, declined much more steeply. 
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 2.54 points to close at 
10,674.77. The Dow, following what is becoming a familiar pattern, 
gave up nearly all its gains late in the day and wiped out what had 
been a 152-point gain. Other market indicators fared worse. The 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 16.85 to 1,305.33, and the Nasdaq 
composite index fell 47.99 to 2,540.00. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Industrials Now Have Vacancy  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Speculation has begun on who will fill a vacancy  
in one of the world's most exclusive clubs -- the 30 stocks that 
make up the Dow Jones industrial average -- following the 
acquisition of Union Carbide Corp. by Dow Chemical Co. The $9.3 
billion deal announced yesterday would create the world's 
second-largest chemical business behind DuPont Co. and a lucrative 
opening in the Dow. Inclusion in Wall Street's best-known indicator 
establishes a company as a leader in its own industry and in the 
economy at large. And investment funds tied to the Dow index 
performance are bound by their charter to buy shares of the 
components. 

</P>
<P>
	Most Asian Markets Decline  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stocks closed sharply lower today,  
following a sharp overnight fall on Wall Street. In Tokyo, the 
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 327.19 points, or 1.85 percent, 
to 17,358.19. On Wednesday, the average fell 1.58 percent. In Hong 
Kong, shares plunged 2.5 percent after four straight sessions of 
gains. The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 336.68 points to close at 
13,254.34. The Taiwan Weighted Price Index fell 151.07 points, or 
2.1 percent, to 6,959.73. 

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Rise by 4,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits inched up last week after hitting their 
lowest level in two years the week before. The Labor Department 
reported today that 279,000 Americans filed new claims for jobless 
benefits for the week ending July 31, up by 4,000 from the previous 
week. Last week's level was the highest since July 17, when claims 
were at 315,000. Jobless claims had plunged by 40,000 to 275,000, 
the lowest level in two years, for the week ending July 24. The 
Labor Department will announce second-quarter productivity numbers 
at 10 a.m. EDT. 

</P>
