<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe: Dog Chewed Plane's Wires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Dog bites man is commonplace. Man bites dog, a  
little weird. But dog bites plane? 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities at Logan Airport said an Irish wolfhound freed  
itself from a kennel during a United Airlines flight to San 
Francisco and chewed up the cargo area. 
</P>
<P>
	The dog, whose name was not released, managed to gnaw into wires  
for the Boeing 767's landing gear, its cockpit warning lights and 
others that slowed the plane upon landing by extending its wing 
flaps. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline officials said the pilot was able to land the plane  
safely in San Francisco, albeit at a slightly faster speed than 
normal because of the impaired flaps. The July 24 flight was 
carrying 159 passengers and a crew of nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Aviation Administration officials say dogs have damaged  
airplanes before, but this is the first time a dog is believed to 
have caused service difficulties for a plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline is still investigating how the dog got loose.  
Luggage handlers reported that when they opened the cargo door, 
they found the dog wagging his tail, apparently eager to disembark. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
