<HEADLINE> Clinton Names Marshall's Son to Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will nominate a son of  
Thurgood Marshall to head the U.S. Marshals Service, the White 
House said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	John Marshall would succeed Eduardo Gonzales, who left this  
spring as director of the nation's oldest law enforcement agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Marshall has been U.S. Marshal at the federal courthouse in  
Alexandria, Va., since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	His father, the first black Supreme Court justice, died in 1993.  
Marshall's brother, Thurgood Marshall Jr., is an assistant to the 
president for Cabinet affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marshals Service, founded in 1789, provides security at  
federal courthouses, protects endangered federal witnesses and 
pursues federal fugitives. 
  	   	
