<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Protects Rights of Unborn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unborn children would be protected by federal  
criminal law for the first time under a bill a House subcommittee 
has approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law does not now treat unborn children the same as the  
living. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said the bill was overdue. Opponents claimed it was  
an attempt to undermine Roe vs. Wade, the Supreme Court decision 
that legalized abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Right to Life Committee, which supports the measure  
and helped draft it, said the legislation was the first of its kind 
at the federal level. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Judiciary Committee's constitution subcommittee voted  
5-2 for the bill Wednesday, sending it to the full committee for 
consideration. The full House and Senate also must act on it before 
it can go to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, anyone who intentionally or unintentionally  
injured or killed an unborn child while committing a federal crime, 
such as a kidnapping or bank robbery, would be charged with an 
additional federal offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would amend federal criminal law and the Uniform  
Code of Military Justice. It would not apply to an abortion that a 
pregnant woman agreed to have, or to acts by such a woman that 
could affect her unborn. 
</P>
<P>
	It defines an unborn child as a ``member of the species homo  
sapiens, at any stage of development, who is carried in the womb.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven states already have similar laws.  
</P>
<P>
	``What this bill seeks to do is face up to the reality that an  
unborn child is not a nothing,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., a 
staunch abortion opponent who is chairman of the Judiciary 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents criticized the effort to distinguish between a woman  
and her fetus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such separation is merely the first step toward eroding a  
woman's right to determine the fate of her own pregnancy and to 
direct the course of her own health care,'' the American Civil 
Liberties Union said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., a prime sponsor of the bill,  
said it would not prohibit abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're focusing on criminal misconduct directed toward a  
pregnant woman and her unborn child,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other prime sponsors are Republican Reps. Charles Canady of  
Florida and Christopher Smith of New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 2436.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
