<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 10:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TV Calls In the Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- My patience is wearing thin. How come nobody  
calls? 
</P>
<P>
	Listen up, CNN, MSNBC and Fox News Channel, ``Dateline,''  
``Nightline'' and ``Today'': I want my shot at stardom! I want my 
15 minutes as an on-air expert! 
</P>
<P>
	After all, what I've got, TV news can't get enough of: opinions  
and verbosity. EXPERT opinions and verbosity, that is, from people 
cast by TV news in guest-starring roles as experts in whatever they 
do in real life. 
</P>
<P>
	Actual breaking news can carry TV only so far in covering a  
story, especially a big one. Solid information comes in fits and 
starts. Relevant video may be limited. How's a big story without a 
commensurate bounty of show-and-tell supposed to span endless hours 
of airtime? 
</P>
<P>
	No wonder experts are needed. They're as important to TV news as  
a snowmaking machine is to a ski resort. You can't count on Nature 
for favorable conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	With that in mind, I stand ready to join TV's know-it-alls. I'm  
happy to weigh in on pennies, sun block, Kosovo, Woodstock, women's 
soccer, potty training or Talk magazine. And I can do it with crisp 
authority or indignant bluster -- you make the call. Put me on the 
left. Put me on the right. Just put me on the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Heck, I'd even go on MSNBC's ``Watch It! With Laura Ingraham,''  
and she scares me to death. Anything is better than being ignored 
by TV time after time, news event after news event. 
</P>
<P>
	And anything is better than living with my father's reproach:  
``When are ya gonna get on TV like that Jonathan Alter character (a 
Newsweek editor who lately has popped up more often than those 
'Power for Living' commercials)? Why do you think your mother and I 
made so many sacrifices?'' 
</P>
<P>
	What can I say? ``Gosh, Dad, the news channels take people in  
alphabetical order''? 
</P>
<P>
	I'm not getting any younger! I want to log some face time before  
I need a facelift. I want to establish myself as a brand that I can 
leverage into a franchise, then use to launch my own talk show, Web 
site, self-help books and chain of theme restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the way being an on-air expert works, as New York Times  
columnist Frank Rich suggested a few days ago. Rich wrote of the 
``fast friends'' of John F. Kennedy Jr. who, after his fatal plane 
crash, came on TV to prattle self-servingly about the man they 
claimed to know. 
</P>
<P>
	After checking around, Rich labeled as impostors or  
grandstanders ``almost all of those who passed themselves off as 
Kennedy chums.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, it's never too late to forge a friendship,  
even posthumously -- especially if it certifies one's status as a 
TV-worthy expert. 
</P>
<P>
	So what do I have to do to certify mine? That's what I was  
wondering last month, sitting by the phone, watching nonstop 
coverage of the Kennedy-Bessette tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Didn't you know? I was a friend of John's!  
</P>
<P>
	I used to party with him.  
</P>
<P>
	Well, I went to a party with him.  
</P>
<P>
	Well, it was more like a reception. Last winter. I was there. So  
was he. I didn't talk to him. He was busy talking with Tom Brokaw 
and Harrison Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	But while I stood in line for the finger food, I remember  
concluding, ``John's a simple man. Yet complicated.'' I definitely 
think he would have run for office. Unless he chose not to. I 
remember thinking that, too. 
</P>
<P>
	And don't forget, my expertise extends beyond the Kennedys.  
</P>
<P>
	For example, TV coverage of last week's tragic shootings in  
Atlanta could have used my expert input. 
</P>
<P>
	I know almost as much about day trading as I do about crazed  
killers, and years ago I lived less than a mile down Piedmont Road 
from the Buckhead brokerages where the massacre took place. I could 
have told a TV audience about Atlanta's dogwoods in spring and all 
the nights I spent in a nearby bar playing Pac-Man. I could have 
even explained where the name ``Buckhead'' came from. 
</P>
<P>
	And while I'm on the subject of Atlanta, I'd like to mention  
that I went to the same Atlanta high school that President Carter's 
daughter Amy later attended. After graduation, she went to Brown 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, of course, is the alma mater of JFK Jr.  
</P>
<P>
	Did I mention that John and I used to be friends?  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`MILLER' TO WRAP: Veteran comic Red Buttons will discuss ``Aging  
Gracefully'' when ``Dennis Miller Live'' wraps its latest season 
Friday at 11:30 p.m. EDT on HBO. As always, the weekly program 
gives Miller a showcase for his freewheeling commentaries in an 
opening monologue and rant about the week's topic, followed by a 
chat with that week's guest, viewer call-ins and a wrap-up of 
current events. Previous guests this season have included Ben 
Affleck, Kathy Bates, Sheryl Crow, Eddie Izzard, Rob Lowe, Norm 
Macdonald, Camryn Manheim, Roseanne, Jon Voight and Noah Wyle. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ''at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
