<DOCNO> APW19990805.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Slave Suit Urged Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- On behalf of Ford Motor Co., former  
Secretary of State Warren Christopher argued Thursday that a 
class-action lawsuit against the auto maker by slave laborers at 
its German plant during the Nazi era should be dismissed because 
courts cannot decide questions of war reparations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reparations have been, and must be handled, by the political  
branches of government,'' Christopher told a federal judge. 
</P>
<P>
	He was joined by another Clinton administration veteran, Walter  
Dellinger, once acting solicitor general, who said the lawsuit, 
filed in March 1998, should also be dismissed because postwar 
treaties decided that claims by individuals would be handled by 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers, assisted by lawyers who helped reach a $1.25  
billion settlement between Holocaust victims and Swiss banks, are 
seeking whatever profits Ford and its German subsidiary, Ford Werke 
AG, made from their unpaid labor, and compensation for brutal 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 10,000 people -- men, women and children -- were pressed  
into laboring at Ford Werke during the war years. 
</P>
<P>
	Arguing for the workers, New York University law professor Burt  
Neuborne asserted that later postwar treaties anticipated 
individual reparations claims. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Joseph A. Greenaway Jr. said he could rule  
on the dismissal request in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford maintains that its plant in Cologne was seized, along with  
other American interests, after Germany declared war on the United 
States, and that Ford lost contact with the plant until the war 
ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Nazi government's exploitation of civilians during World  
War II was abhorrent and inexcusable,'' Ford spokesman Jim Vella 
said in a statement issued Thursday from company headquarters in 
Dearborn, Mich. ``But whatever occurred at the Cologne plant during 
WWII was and is the responsibility of the German government, as 
successor to the Nazi regime.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
