<HEADLINE> Chevron Starts Thai Field Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The U.S. oil company Chevron announced  
that oil and gas production has begun in an offshore Thai field it 
acquired earlier this year from Rutherford Moran Oil Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release posted Thursday on the Internet, the company  
said its Benchamas field 125 miles offshore in the Gulf of Thailand 
had initial production of 35 million cubic feet of natural gas and 
2,200 barrels of oil per day. 
</P>
<P>
	Production is expected to increase to 75 million cubic feet of  
gas and 25,000 barrels of oil a day by October, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gas is sold under contract to the Petroleum Authority of  
Thailand, the country's state oil company, and the oil is exported 
via a nearby floating terminal. 
</P>
<P>
	Benchamas is the second of three known fields in the B8/32 block  
to enter production, Chevron said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron holds a 51.66 percent interest in the block and will  
become, pending government approval, operator of the concession on 
Oct. 1. Chevron's partners in the block include Thaipo, a 
subsidiary of Pogo Producing Co., with a 46.34 percent share, and 
Palang Sophon, with 2 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
