<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 23:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Markets Warner Bros. Minivan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- General Motors is not changing its name  
to the Acme Car Co., after the fictional firm in Warner Bros. 
cartoons, but it is using the Looney Tunes brand to pitch a new 
line of minivans. 
</P>
<P>
	GM and Warner on Thursday introduced the Chevy Venture Warner  
Bros. van, which bears labels featuring Bugs Bunny and the studio 
logo as a marketing carrot to lure family buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest instance of cross-marketing between Hollywood and  
manufacturing, GM plans to build 20,000 of the vans. It's believed 
to be the first big-ticket consumer item labeled with an 
entertainment logo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel so strongly about the viability of this vehicle, we  
placed our most important asset, our corporate logo, on it,'' said 
Dan Romanelli, president of Warner consumer products. 
</P>
<P>
	GM unveiled the van at the Warner studio, with actors in Bugs  
Bunny, Daffy Duck and other Looney Tunes costumes on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	The vehicle is the first step in a four-year marketing  
partnership that will give GM access to Warner's studio identity 
along with its films, TV shows and other productions. The companies 
said they have not settled on details of future marketing plans. 
</P>
<P>
	GM will pay royalties to Warner for use of the studio logo on  
its vans. The vehicle's list price will be just under $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The minivan, a variation of GM's Chevy Venture model, has two  
small Warner logos on each front door and the rear door. The logo 
also appears on a videocassette screen over the back seat. 
</P>
<P>
	The van, expected to be on dealer lots by late August or early  
September, also carries bonuses for buyers, such as free Warner 
videos and compact discs, discounts at the studio's retail stores 
and passes to sneak previews of movies. 
</P>
<P>
	GM executives said they hope the long family identity of Warner  
-- with its movies and cartoons -- will attract car-buyers who have 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Entertainment has an increasing emotional connection with our  
customers,'' said Phil Guarascio, GM vice president for advertising 
and corporate marketing. ``We're here to have Warner Bros. leverage 
that and help us understand it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the videocassette player, the van has other special  
features that include a built-in child-safety seat and a sound 
system that allows passengers to listen to different audio sources. 
</P>
<P>
	GM has used Looney Tunes characters such as Wile E. Coyote and  
the Tasmanian Devil in car ads before. The marketing deal also will 
give the automaker first rights to place its vehicles in Warner 
productions, as it did with cars in the studio's ``Lethal Weapon'' 
movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Product placement in films and television shows is common, as is  
marketing of movies on small items such as ``Star Wars'' and 
``Inspector Gadget'' toys at fast-food restaurants. BMW has been 
introducing new sports-car models in James Bond movies. 
</P>
<P>
	But branding something as big as a vehicle with a studio logo is  
new. 
</P>
<P>
	A Warner-branded minivan might appeal to hard-core Looney Tunes  
fans, but the main benefit to the companies will be simple 
advertising, said Mike Kamins, a marketing professor at the 
University of Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like those big billboards that drive around all  
day, only this is a little billboard,'' Kamins said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 13:00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coors May Not Use 'NFL' in Promo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coors Brewing Co. cannot use the National Football League's  
trademark initials in its new beer promotion, a judge has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden, Colo.-based brewer had worked out a deal with  
Players Inc., the licensing arm of the NFL Players Association, to 
call their product the ``Official Beer of NFL Players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the NFL and NFL Properties fought the plan and U.S. District  
Court Judge Denise L. Cote on Wednesday granted a preliminary 
injunction against the planned promotion. The ruling was issued in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Coors spokesman Dave Taylor said the real conflict is between  
the NFL and Players Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Coors still plans to launch the promotion in mid-August as  
planned and run it through the Labor Day weekend, Taylor said. But 
he was not sure if the promotion would use the phrase ``Official 
Beer of Players, Inc.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Gertzog, NFL senior vice president of business affairs and  
general counsel, said the injunction proves the NFL has sole rights 
to its trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL and NFL Properties are seeking to make the injunction  
permanent. A date for a trial on that request will be set in a 
hearing in New York on Aug. 18, Gertzog said. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of Players Inc. could not be reached immediately  
for comment. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
