<DOCNO> APW19990805.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar, Gold Move Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against most other major  
currencies in European trading Thursday. Gold prices also fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0803 in late European trading, up from  
$1.0767 Wednesday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0796. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,  
included 114.08 Japanese yen, down from 114.23; 1.4800 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.4846; 1.4908 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.4922. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6169, down from $1.6228.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 113.98 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6165. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8105 German marks, down from 1.8165; 
6.0720 French francs, down from 6.0923; 2.0399 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0467; 1,792.34 Italian lire, down from 1,798.34. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $255.00 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$255.10 on Wednesday. In Zurich the bid price was $254.75, down 
from $254.95. Gold fell 10 cents in Hong Kong to $256.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.42 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.43. 
  	   	
</P>
