<HEADLINE> GM To Offer New Pickup Truck Bed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will offer a  
composite plastic cargo bed as an option on its 2001 Chevrolet 
Silverado full-size pickup, which the automaker said is more 
durable than conventional pressed steel. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Burns, GM's vice president of research and development,  
told an industry conference Thursday that the plastic bed also will 
improve fuel economy, reduce maintenance and repair costs, increase 
resale value and is recyclable. 
</P>
<P>
	The new 6 1/2-foot cargo bed, also called a box in the industry,  
will be offered starting in fall 2000 on the extended-cab version 
of the 1500-series Fleetside Silverado. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers offer plastic bed liners to protect their steel cargo  
beds, but GM said this is the first that's made completely of 
composite plastics. The bed also features a stronger, 
easier-to-open tailgate, will not rust or dent and is highly 
scratch-resistant, Burns said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bed will reduce the truck's weight by 50 pounds, which will  
help boost fuel economy and increase load capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	GM has been a leader in the use of plastics for vehicle bodies  
for decades. Its Saturn line of cars, the Chevrolet Corvette, 
Camaro and Pontiac Firebird use composite body panels. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
