<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak Forms Business Strategy Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastman Kodak Co. promoted Jesse J.  
Greene Jr. to a new post charged with shaping the photography 
company's business strategy, but didn't name him chief financial 
officer as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, currently the acting chief financial officer, will be  
the highest-ranking black executive in Kodak's 118-year history in 
his role as senior vice president of business strategy and 
information technology. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the 54-year-old executive had been widely expected to  
succeed Harry Kavetas as CFO after Kavetas died of a heart attack 
in May at age 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene will develop Kodak's overall strategic direction --  
handling mergers, acquisitions, partnerships and new investments -- 
while the new chief financial officer will handle operational 
finance, Kodak said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene will act as CFO until that post is filled, and his new  
job includes some of the CFO's duties, Kodak said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I can be every bit as effective and maybe even more  
effective toward the future direction of the company from this 
position as I would be from the CFO (post),'' Greene said. ``I view 
it as a great opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	``My only complaint now,'' he added with a chuckle, ``is I have  
to continue to do the acting CFO role for another few months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Greene and the eventual CFO will report to Dan Carp, who is  
replacing George Fisher in January as chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Ellmann, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co., suspects Carp  
``felt the functions that Kavetas was performing were sufficiently 
important and wide-ranging that one guy couldn't do them all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``One's cynical inference is Greene's been kicked upstairs. That  
thought did flicker across my mind but I think that's the wrong 
call. It's really a function of a new guy coming in, having a 
somewhat different view of the manpower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene downplayed the significance of becoming one of corporate  
America's highest-ranking minority executives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I view it as important for me to contribute to the performance  
of this company,'' he said, adding that it's ``obviously important 
for Eastman Kodak Co. to continue its diversity efforts as it is 
for most American companies today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene joined Kodak in 1994 as treasurer following 23 years at  
International Business Machines. Kodak credits him with leading the 
effort to reduce debt and improve the company's balance sheet. 
Kodak promoted him in 1998 to vice president of finance. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of New York City, Greene earned a law degree and  
master's degree in business administration at Columbia University 
and a master's in mechanical engineering at New York University. He 
is married and has two grown sons. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
