<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stocks closed sharply lower  
Thursday, following a sharp overnight fall on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell  
327.19 points, or 1.85 percent, to 17,358.19. On Wednesday, the 
average fell 1.58 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo shares were dragged down by sharp losses in U.S. Internet  
and high technology stocks, which pushed the Nasdaq Composite Index 
in New York down 1.85 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese stocks also fell on the stronger Japanese yen, which  
rose against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.62 yen in late trading, down 0.48 yen from  
its level of 115.10 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its late 
New York level of 114.29 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said the yen rose after comments by U.S. Treasury  
Secretary Lawrence Summers late Wednesday failed to indicate that 
the two countries would intervene in currency markets to prop up 
the greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen makes the products of Japanese exporters more  
expensive and therefore less competitive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares plunged 2.5 percent after four straight  
sessions of gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 336.68 points to close at  
13,254.34. On Wednesday, the index rose 0.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Hong Kong shares, which are technically weak on  
fundamentals, have become overpriced as liquidity rushed into the 
market in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a time for the liquidity-driven rally to come to an  
end,'' said Joseph Yu of Pacific Challenge Securities Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taiwan, shares also fell amid heightened tensions with China.  
</P>
<P>
	The Weighted Price Index fell 151.07 points, or 2.1 percent, to  
6,959.73. 
</P>
<P>
	Continued media reports of increased sorties over the Taiwan  
Strait by both mainland and Taiwanese fighter jets eroded investor 
confidence and pressured share prices lower. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares fell on losses in banking and finance  
shares. The SET index fell 4.34 points, or 0.9 percent, to 447.09. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares fell amid renewed fears over a  
possible U.S. interest rates hike. The JSX Composite index fell 
8.125 points, or 1.3 percent, to 606.270. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares fell on continued selling by  
foreign funds. The KLSE Composite Index fell 13.54 points, or 1.9 
percent, to 705.98. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares fell on renewed fears over the  
stability of the peso and the direction of domestic interest rates. 
The PSE Index fell 23.81 points, or 1 percent, to 2,348.24. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares rose on buying in mineral resources  
and gold shares. The All Ordinaries Index rose 13.2 points, or 0.4 
percent, to 3,018.9. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares plunged 3.7 percent on continued  
worries over financial troubles of Daewoo Group, one of the 
country's largest conglomerates. The Kospi fell 36.38 points to 
939.07. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Singapore shares fell on lingering concerns of a  
possible U.S. interest rate hike. The STI fell 61.87 points, or 2.9 
percent, to 2,082.13. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on gains by market leaders Carter Holt  
Harvey and Telecom Corp. The NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 11.43 
points, or 0.52 percent, to 2,189.86. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
