<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Slaying Evidence Parked for 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Every month for eight years, Dennis  
Field scraped together $40 to keep a 1978 Lincoln Continental in 
storage in Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	But he wasn't trying to protect a classic. He was trying to  
protect himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say the part-time telemarketer, who bounced from one  
$4-a-day hotel room to another, stole the car from his landlady in 
1991 -- just after he shot her to death. 
</P>
<P>
	``He placed it in storage and never touched it again,'' Palm  
Beach County Sheriff's Detective Wayne Robinson said Wednesday. 
``It was a really good way to keep it out of circulation -- a little 
expensive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation into the death of Barbara McConnell, 58, of  
Palm Beach Gardens went cold shortly after she was shot in January 
1991. Police issued a warrant for Field for the theft of her car, 
but there wasn't enough evidence to charge him with her death. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, there was no sign of either Field or the car.  
</P>
<P>
	That was until last month, when Field, who had lung cancer, was  
hospitalized in San Diego. He was registered under the name William 
Mahan, the identity he apparently had been using since he moved to 
California shortly after the slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	While in the hospital, he called his boss, Brian Mitchell, and  
asked Mitchell to get a briefcase, gun and money from his hotel 
room. 
</P>
<P>
	Curiosity apparently got the best of Mitchell, and he rifled  
through the briefcase. In it, he found papers and photographs 
indicating the man he knew as William Mahan actually was Dennis 
Field. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Mitchell's friends turned to the Internet for answers and  
found that Field's name was listed on the FBI Web site, from the 
1991 warrant for the stolen car. Mitchell called police. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson flew to California, where he and other detectives found  
that Field had kept the .38-caliber gun believed to have been used 
in McConnell's shooting and a box of bullets with two missing. The 
bullets, bought in Sarasota, Fla., appeared to have corroded with 
age. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson also found a business card from a nearby storage area,  
where surprisingly, Field had parked McConnell's 1978 Continental, 
its windows open, its seats full of mud and rainwater. It had been 
spray-painted red. 
</P>
<P>
	``The possibility of him having the weapon and the box of  
bullets and the victim's car -- I was a bit dumbfounded by that,'' 
Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	When police questioned Field, he admitted his true identity but  
said nothing about the slaying. Robinson told Field that police had 
discovered the gun, the bullets and the car. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never one time denied anything. He just shook his head  
`yes,''' Robinson said. ``I really believe he wanted to resolve 
everything, but he was afraid to say anything without an attorney, 
and I had to respect that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On July 25, Field was brought before a judge and was told he  
would be sent back to Florida to face a murder charge. 
</P>
<P>
	But he'll never stand trial.  
</P>
<P>
	About 10 minutes after Field was returned to his jail cell, he  
dropped dead, apparently of a heart attack. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 09:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Asks for Help on Youth Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite highly publicized school shootings,  
youth violence has declined and Congress now has the opportunity to 
encourage the reduction, Attorney General Janet Reno said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Congress has a major task in the days ahead. The conferees  
on the juvenile justice bill, who begin meeting this afternoon, 
have an opportunity to finalize legislation, which can 
significantly contribute to the reduction in youth violence,'' Reno 
said at her weekly news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	She opened the session by noting the decline in youth violence  
reported Tuesday by the federal Centers for Disease Control and 
Prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	The CDC researchers reported that in 1991, 42.5 percent of high  
school students said they had been in a fight in the previous year, 
but the figure fell to 36.6 percent in 1997. And in 1991, 26.1 
percent said they had carried a weapon in the previous month, but 
the rate dropped to 18.3 percent in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	These figures show ``we're on the right track, we can make a  
difference with respect to youth violence and a balanced approach 
of enforcement and prevention,'' Reno said. 
</P>
<P>
	The House and Senate have approved differing versions of the  
juvenile justice bill and the conference committee must work out a 
compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno urged that the final bill include a significant investment  
in prevention and in mental health services. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wherever I go, people are talking about the need for mental  
health services to provide assistance and support for youngsters 
who are grappling with the issues so many teen-agers face today,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it had initially rejected tougher gun-control  
restrictions supported by the Senate, the House last week approved 
a nonbinding measure endorsing background checks on all firearms 
sales at gun shows. Under current law, background checks are 
required only on sales by licensed dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution also calls for including measures to prevent  
violence in schools and ensuring that the legislation does not 
weaken existing gun regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill, in addition to requiring background checks on  
all firearms buyers at gun shows, would require dealers to provide 
safety devices with all handguns, ban importation of certain 
high-capacity firearms clips and impose a lifetime prohibition of 
gun ownership on anyone convicted as a juvenile of a serious 
felony. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
