<DOCNO> APW19990805.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 07:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diet Supplement Crackdown Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional investigators dealt a blow to  
the Food and Drug Administration's planned crackdown on 
ephedrine-laced dietary supplements Wednesday, saying the agency 
used sloppy science to justify some of the proposed rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA in 1997 proposed mandating warning labels and a dramatic  
slashing of the dose of ephedrine in herbal supplements, citing 
reports of 17 deaths and 800 illnesses linked to products that 
promise to help people lose weight, build muscle and heighten 
sexual awareness. 
</P>
<P>
	Ephedrine, an amphetamine-like stimulant, has long been  
controversial. Florida and New York banned ephedrine supplements 
after pills with such names as Herbal Ecstacy and Ultimate Xphoria 
promised a ``natural high.'' The bans came when a 20-year-old 
college student died after taking Ultimate Xphoria during spring 
break in 1996; the manufacturer ultimately settled with the 
student's parents for $2.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FDA's proposal sparked a storm of protest, and Congress'  
General Accounting Office investigated. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the GAO concluded that while health officials were  
right to probe ephedrine, they used sloppy science in deciding 
supplements should contain no more than 8 milligrams of ephedrine 
per serving. 
</P>
<P>
	Studies suggest 20 milligrams may be the dose at which certain  
people suffer side effects, the GAO said, while the FDA focused on 
a mere 13 reports of injured patients -- some that were inaccurate -- 
to propose the much lower dose. 
</P>
<P>
	``The available scientific information suggests that the use of  
products containing synthetic ephedrine alkaloids can result in 
adverse experiences for some individuals,'' says the GAO report. 
However, the report adds, studies ``did not provide information 
relating to adverse events below the 20 mg level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``For the FDA -- one of the most important regulatory agencies in  
government -- to use such poor science for a dietary supplement 
raises warning flags for other products the agency regulates,'' 
said House Science Committee Chairman F. James Sensenbrenner, 
R-Wis., who requested the GAO probe. 
</P>
<P>
	FDA officials told the GAO they were looking for additional data  
before making a final decision on ephedrine regulation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
