<DOCNO> APW19990805.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Beats US Women Basketball Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- The U.S. women's basketball team made  
a big turnaround against Cuba in the Pan American Games. It just 
wasn't big enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba dominated the inside play in the second half and beat the  
Americans 87-78 Thursday night to advance to the gold medal game 
against Canada, which upset Brazil 56-54. 
</P>
<P>
	The best the United States can hope for Saturday night is the  
bronze. But the Americans responded well after losing to Cuba 95-64 
last Saturday, the worst loss ever for a U.S. women's team in the 
Pan Am Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've come a million miles,'' U.S. coach Nell Fortner said  
of her team, which was put together just two weeks before the 
games. ``I just wish we could have hit a few more shots against 
that zone defense and maybe it's a different outcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Led by Edwina Brown's 15 points and four steals, the United  
States led 36-34 at halftime and went ahead 49-48 with 13:22 
remaining when Brown's fifth steal produced a layup for Michelle 
Marciniak. 
</P>
<P>
	But long-armed center Yamilet Martinez, who gave the United  
States problems all night, scored on a strong spin move inside to 
start a 7-0 run and the Cubans never trailed again, though the 
Americans stayed within striking distance the whole time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess we all reached down individually within ourselves and  
we brought to the table everything we had,'' said Brown, who 
finished with 18 points. ``Maybe we were holding back in the 
beginning. Maybe we just didn't quite understand the capability we 
had. But it came out tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba, which still has most of the players from its 1996 Olympic  
team, opened a 77-64 lead with four minutes left and another 
blowout was looming. Except the United States didn't let it happen 
this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Beth Cunningham hit a 3-pointer and the Americans followed with  
six more points to cut the lead to 77-73 with 1:59 to play. But 
that's as close as it got. Cuba continued attacking inside and held 
on. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew Cuba's great at making good, hard runs at you,''  
Fortner said. ``When they do, you cannot panic. You've got to stop 
it and then you've got to turn around and get one of your own. And 
that's what they did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Pride had 15 points for the United States, while Marciniak  
and Sylvia Crawley each scored 10. Martinez had 22 points on 
9-for-12 shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first meeting, Cuba jumped to a 14-3 lead and led by 20 a  
little more than 13 minutes into the game. But fired up by 
Crawley's pregame dunks, the Americans started strong and matched 
the Cubans run for run until the very end. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was willing to do whatever it took to get my teammates  
excited,'' Crawley said. ``Slam dunking got the crowd into it, the 
crowd on our side. We were really intense at the beginning of the 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said she was certain the team would take that intensity  
into the bronze medal game as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a disappointment to me individually because I hate  
losing,'' she said. ``But then for the USA, they don't deserve a 
bronze medal, they deserve a gold. We were unable to give it to 
them and get it for ourselves. So we've got to go out and get 
something.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo May Talk Investment With GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's troubled Daewoo Group  
may soon hold serious investment talks with General Motors Corp. of 
the United States, company officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Desperate for cash, Daewoo has publicly said it wanted General  
Motors to buy part of Daewoo Motors Co., its main subsidiary and 
South Korea's second largest car maker. 
</P>
<P>
	Local news media, quoting unidentified Daewoo officials,  
reported that a memorandum of understanding will be signed as early 
as Friday, committing both sides to discussing details of possible 
GM investment in Daewoo Motors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have any comment to make now, but we can say that we  
have made progress,'' said Daewoo Motors spokesman Kim Seung-hee. 
</P>
<P>
	This is not the first time Daewoo and GM discussed partnership.  
General Motors owned half of Daewoo Motors from 1978 to 1992 in a 
deal that allowed Daewoo to sell cars overseas using GM brand 
names. Their rocky marriage ended with Daewoo buying out GM's 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo, South Korea's second-largest conglomerate, narrowly  
escaped becoming South Korea's largest-ever bankruptcy in July when 
domestic creditors, mostly under government control, agreed to 
delay repayment of $5.8 billion in short-term debt for six months 
and extend $3.3 billion in new loans. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Daewoo promised to cut its debt drastically by  
selling or spinning off most of its 40 subsidiaries and attracting 
foreign investment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 10:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Ridicules GOP Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton staged a unity rally with  
Democrats on Capitol Hill today to poke fun at Republican tax cuts 
and boast that his economic program has brought America prosperity. 
``We should not abandon it,'' he declared. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton gathered with House and Senate Democrats a day before  
Congress leaves town for a monthlong summer recess. He challenged 
Republicans to keep House and Senate negotiators at work to produce 
gun-control legislation that ``keeps guns out of the hands of 
criminals and children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a wish list of legislation, he also urged Congress to  
increase the minimum wage, strengthen the rights of patients in 
managed-care health plans and enact long-stalled campaign finance 
reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The president attacked the Republicans' $792 billion tax cut,  
saying the money from huge projected budget surpluses should be 
used first to solve the nation's social needs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now what they have said is, `Let's pass this big tax cut  
first, make everybody happy tomorrow and then we'll talk about 
these long-term challenges.' And normally that's better politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Clinton said, ``We should not be doing this until we  
figure out how we're going to save Medicare, save Social Security 
and pay the debt off. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ought to figure out: What is it we have to spend to educate  
these kids here, to provide for the national defense, to invest in 
medical research, to do the basic thing,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then we ought to ask ourselves how much is left, and whatever  
it is, we ought to give it back to the American people in a tax 
cut,'' the president said. ``That's the way we ought to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said his economic strategy -- rather than the  
Republicans' -- has been a success. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have to debate this anymore,'' Clinton said. ``Now we  
have 6 1/2 years of evidence. We have the longest peacetime expansion 
in history, we've turned the biggest deficit into the biggest 
surplus, we've got 19 million new jobs, the highest home ownership 
in history, the lowest minority unemployment in history, a 30-year 
low in the welfare rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing more to argue about,'' he said. ``This  
economic strategy works and we should not abandon it in this 
moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warming up the crowd for the president, House Minority Leader  
Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said, ``This Congress should not be measured 
on how many billions of dollars in tax cuts it provides to the 
wealthiest, most secure members of our society. It should be 
measured by its attempts to stop violence against the most 
vulnerable people in our society ... our children. Let's pass gun 
safety now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said the Republican  
plan ``doesn't devote one dime of the surplus to Medicare and it 
doesn't include one nickel for prescription drug benefits. The 
truth about their plan is it doesn't protect Social Security. It 
raids the trust fund to pay for more tax breaks for wealthiest 
Americans.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 10:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
