<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 08:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Camp Investigating Racism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- The Marine Corps has begun  
investigating a Young Marines camp after Washington-area black 
youths said they were the targets of racial hostility. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. James Rich, a spokesman for the Camp Lejeune Marine Corps  
base, said today that the base inspector has begun investigating a 
Washington Post report that racial epithets were scrawled on the 
lockers of youths attending the Young Marines camp here. Their 
belongings also were vandalized, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The camp ended two weeks ago, Rich said, but Camp Lejeune  
officials learned of the alleged incidents only through the 
newspaper report. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one brought this up with the leadership at Camp Lejeune  
when they left,'' Rich said today. ``That's why we're only looking 
at the matter now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the perpetrators apparently were other youths attending  
the camp, but he had no details. The Young Marines is an 
organization for youths between the ages of 8 and 18 supported by 
but not part of the Marine Corps, Rich said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nation's Capitol Young Marines group said one member's  
mattress was ripped, his military boots stolen and his wooden 
locker covered with racial epithets scribbled in toothpaste. 
</P>
<P>
	Another camper returned to his barracks to find a picture of his  
dead parents torn and scattered on the floor, money and uniforms 
missing and the smell of stale urine, the youths said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I saw wasn't teasing, and that bothers me a lot,'' said  
Michael Kessler, the incoming national executive director of Young 
Marines. Kessler has launched an investigation to find those 
responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	``Incidents like that are certainly contrary to everything we  
believe in,'' Maj. Dave Lapan, a Marine Corps spokesman, told the 
Post. ``We support the Young Marines' taking disciplinary action 
against those found accountable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the black youths attending, 15-year-old Joseph Hall from  
Oxon Hill, Md., said he couldn't believe the incidents happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``It left me feeling so violated,'' Hall said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
