<P>
	``When the book is written about NASCAR racing, he will  
certainly have a chapter in it,'' Michael Waltrip said. ``One of 
the things that I most admire about him is that he's been able to 
do it on his own terms, and that hasn't always made everybody 
happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip got his first victory at his home track in Nashville,  
Tenn., in 1975. He won 22 races from 1975-79, then captured the 
Winston Cup championship in 1981, '82 and '85. 
</P>
<P>
	His popularity soared once he learned to use his gift for gab  
wisely. 
</P>
<P>
	Once in the 1980s, Waltrip was asked what he thought of  
Chevrolet's new Lumina. Without hesitation, Waltrip said he'd 
received letters from fans who wanted to know, ``Why are they 
switching to those 'luminum cars? What's wrong with steel?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, a future TV commentator who says he also might go into  
politics after racing, still has plenty of one-liners left in the 
tank. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just haven't decided what state I want to be governor of  
yet,'' Waltrip said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like racing, politics probably would never be the same.  
</P>
<P>
	``DW ain't told all the stories he knows,'' Waltrip said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Wants Subpoena Thrown Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush asked a judge Thursday  
to dismiss a subpoena for his testimony in a whistle-blower lawsuit 
by the fired executive director of the Texas Funeral Service 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the Republican presidential front-runner, said he knows  
nothing about the February firing of Eliza May. She had been 
leading the agency's investigation into the embalming practices of 
Houston's Service Corporation International, owner of 3,700 funeral 
homes worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no personal knowledge of relevant facts of the  
investigation nor do I have any personal knowledge of relevant 
facts concerning any dispute arising from this investigation,'' 
Bush said in an affidavit. He also said he had no conversations 
with commission officials or the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May's suit alleges that SCI, whose political action  
committee gave Bush $35,000 in 1996 and 1997, worked with Bush's 
staff to interfere with the investigation. The defendants are the 
funeral commission, SCI and Robert Waltrip, the company's founder 
and chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has said the fight is between Ms. May and the state,  
and believes its inclusion in the suit is a ``publicity stunt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state attorney filed the motion to throw out the subpoena. A  
hearing is set for Aug. 30 in Travis County district court, Bush 
spokeswoman Linda Edwards said. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for Ms. May, Derek Howard, said he expects the judge to  
allow him to question Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's investigation led to a recommended fine of  
$445,000, which SCI is fighting. The company contends the funeral 
agency misinterpreted state embalming law. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May was hired in 1996 by the nine-member funeral commission,  
which included six Bush appointees. She also was treasurer of the 
Texas Democratic Party until last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit says Ms. May was dismissed nine months after she was  
called into the office of Joe Allbaugh, Bush's executive assistant, 
and asked to explain inspections on April 10, 1998, at SCI 
affiliates in Dallas and Hurst. Among those present during the 
meeting were Waltrip and an SCI attorney, according to the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's office has said Allbaugh's role was simply that of  
listener and that his presence had nothing to do with SCI 
contributing to Bush's gubernatorial campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Allbaugh now is managing Bush's presidential campaign.  
</P>
<P>
	The fines were assessed against SCI for allegedly using  
unlicensed embalming companies, allowing unsupervised apprentices 
to embalm bodies, failing to inform families how much SCI paid 
third-party embalmers and refusing to comply with funeral 
commission subpoenas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
