<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 21; Nasdaq Loses 40 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were lower in early trading today as the  
investors awaited the latest indications of whether inflationary 
pressures will encourage the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 21.21 at 10,653.56. On Wednesday, the blue-chip index gave up 
a gain of 152 points to finish 2.54 lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also fell today. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 9.03 at 1,296.30, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was down 40.37 at 2,499.63, continuing its string of losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell as traders awaited and then received the Labor  
Department's 10 a.m. report on productivity and labor costs. The 
department said American workers' productivity slowed significantly 
in the spring, rising at an annual rate of just 1.3 percent, while 
labor costs surged at an annual rate of 3.8 percent, the worst 
showing for this measurement since the end of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, increased productivity has enabled U.S.  
businesses to counteract rising labor costs. But Fed Chairman Alan 
Greenspan has cautioned that investors have been too confident that 
strong gains in productivity would continue. 
</P>
<P>
	If productivity levels off and labor costs rise, that could  
persuade the Fed to raise rates, hoping to slow down economic 
growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The market remained nervous as it also anticipated Friday's  
unemployment report, another widely watched barometer of U.S. 
economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online was among the biggest decliners on the New York  
Stock Exchange, falling 7 15/16 to 79 1/2. While the entire Internet 
sector has been suffering in recent sessions, AOL is also being 
hampered by battles over its instant-messaging technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-4 margin on the  
NYSE, where volume came to 97.97 million shares, ahead of 
Wednesday's early pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 2.56 at 611.90, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.16 at 774.79. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas indexes were mostly lower, held down by the weakness in  
U.S. markets. Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.85 percent. In 
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.1 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 1.6 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 1.4 percent. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
