<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Honors Former Presidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former President Jimmy Carter and his wife  
Rosalynn and former President Gerald Ford will receive the nation's 
highest civilian honor, the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the 
White House announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter and his wife will be honored Monday at a ceremony in  
Atlanta at the Carter Center. Ford and seven other people will 
receive their awards Wednesday at the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, the nation's 38th president, will be recognized for ``his  
honesty and integrity'' and his efforts to restore confidence in 
government and the presidency after the Watergate scandal that 
forced the resignation of Richard M. Nixon. ``As president, he 
brought the Vietnam war to a close,'' a White House tribute said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter, the 39th president, will be recognized for brokering the  
Camp David peace accords, signing the Panama Canal treaty and 
re-establishing normal diplomatic relations with China. With his 
wife, he created the Carter Center to promote peace, democracy and 
improved health throughout the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a statesman, President Carter has been a successful  
diplomat in hot spots around the world,'' the White House said. 
``Mrs. Carter is a longtime advocate of improved mental health 
care, widespread childhood immunization, women's equality and 
enhanced care for seniors. Each year, the Carters help to build 
homes for the needy through Habitat for Humanity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other recipients will be:  
</P>
<P>
	--Lloyd M. Bentsen, Clinton's first Treasury secretary and a  
22-year veteran of the Senate and six years in the House. He was 
the Democratic Party's vice presidential nominee in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	--Edgar M. Bronfman Sr., president of the World Jewish Congress.  
He has ``worked to insure basic rights for Jews around the world 
and to fight anti-Semitism and has spearheaded the effort to 
retrieve the assets of Holocaust victims and their families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Evy Dubrow, an advocate for more than 50 years of laws to  
improve domestic labor conditions. ``A representative for the 
International Ladies Garment Workers Union and for the Union of 
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employes, she has been 
influential in numerous causes, including broadening laws against 
discrimination and protecting American industry from unfair foreign 
competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Sister M. Isolina Ferre, founder of community service centers,  
clinics and programs to empower the poor in Puerto Rico, New York 
and Appalachia. She gained international recognition in the late 
1950s and 1960s for her mediation efforts with youth gangs in 
Brooklyn. 
</P>
<P>
	--Oliver White Hill, civil rights lawer. He is best known for  
litigating one of the school desegregation cases that became the 
landmark Brown v. Board of Education case. 
</P>
<P>
	--Max Kampelman, lawyer, diplomat and negotiator in Democratic  
and Republican administrations. ``In those roles, he emphasized 
human rights in East-West diplomacy and prepared the foundation for 
long-term arms reductions between the United States and the Soviet 
Union.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Edgar Wayburn, five time president and a member of the board of  
directors of the Sierra Club for almost 40 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
