<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Race Car Driver Mahoney Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- Chuck Mahoney, a driver who excelled  
in the early years of NASCAR four decades ago, has died at the age 
of 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahoney, who ranked seventh in total points on the Grand  
National circuit in 1959, the second year of what would become 
Winston Cup racing, died July 20 after a heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Mahoney, whose hard-driving style earned him the nicknames  
``Three Wheels'' and ``Wild Man,'' finished fifth in the first 
Darlington 500. He made a name for himself while competing against 
the likes of Lee Petty and Fireball Roberts, and was named NASCAR 
driver of the month in November 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no one better than Chuck,'' said 79-year-old Cliff  
Kotary, who raced against Mahoney. ``I think a lot of people may 
have forgotten about him, but when racing first got started he was 
the big name. If you could beat Chuck Mahoney, that was something 
special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mahoney, who introduced stock car racing on ice on Oneida Lake,  
also promoted racing at two tracks in upstate New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
