<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> INS Looking at IOC Member's Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- American immigration officials are  
examining whether John Kim, the son of a South Korean International 
Olympic Committee member, set up a sham job with a Utah company to 
get United States residency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the process of looking at the information that's  
developed and surfaced ... with relationship to the allegations of 
fraud in obtaining a green card,'' Russ Bergeron, a spokesman for 
the Immigration and Naturalization Service, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations surfaced in court Tuesday, when David E.  
Simmons, head of the now-defunct Keystone Communications, pleaded 
guilty to misdemeanor tax evasion, the first criminal case in the 
investigations of vote-buying to help Salt Lake City win the 2002 
Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons admitted he had hired the son of IOC vice president Kim  
Un-yong at the request of the Salt Lake bid committee, then claimed 
as a business expense the money funneled to him to pay the younger 
Kim's salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Court documents say that in 1990, a bid committee official  
Simmons later identified as Tom Welch ``told Simmons that he wanted 
Simmons to assist (Kim) in attaining lawful permanent resident 
status in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, who had been laid off from NBC's sports marketing division,  
had a temporary work permit but needed full-time salaried work to 
get residency. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons said he hired Kim as a marketing manager for Asia with a  
salary that started at $50,000, based on Welch's pledge to 
reimburse Keystone if Kim didn't work out. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Welch funneled more than $130,000 in bid  
committee money to the company through bogus consulting contracts 
and other means. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kim family spokesman Bill Schechter insists neither Kim  
Un-yong nor his son knew about the Salt Lake deal and John Kim had 
other job prospects while living in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't have to take the job with Keystone,'' Schechter said  
Thursday. ``It was just kind of unfortunate that they were doing 
some back-room deals. He was totally unaware of what may have been 
going on back in Utah.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schechter also said the Kim family had not been contacted by the  
INS or the FBI, despite news reports to the contrary. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergeron said he wouldn't discuss such particulars as long as an  
inquiry was under way. He also wouldn't say whether Welch or 
Simmons is under scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons' federal plea agreement stipulates he can only be  
prosecuted for the tax evasion charge, as long as it holds firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, as federal officials spread the net of their  
investigation, U.S. Olympic Committee leaders feared the Simmons 
case could scare off even more skittish sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, this won't refuel it,'' USOC Executive Director  
Dick Schultz said. The Salt Lake Organizing Committee is about $187 
million behind in fundraising needed to meet its budget. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
