<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Urges Parents on TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TONAWANDA, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton urged parents  
Thursday to consider boycotting sponsors of violent television 
shows and to refuse to buy violent video games ``no matter how much 
your child begs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There is an opportunity for more parents to act as  
consumers,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``Let people know you're not going 
to buy products that support shows and things you don't believe 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, eyeing a run for the Senate from New York, said  
parents must take more control over their children. 
</P>
<P>
	``This may sound hopelessly old-fashioned, but I believe  
children want limits,'' she said during a discussion with more than 
75 Buffalo-area residents on school violence and youth problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't buy those video games, no matter how much your child  
begs,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Television came in for its share of criticism from the first  
lady. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is just no doubt that our children are exposed to an  
overwhelming amount of violence and mayhem -- not only violent acts, 
but violent language -- from the moment they are put in front of a 
television set,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most parents would never allow a screaming, violent person into  
their homes and would probably call the police if such a person 
showed up at their door, Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we invite those people into our living rooms and even  
worse than that, we put televisions into the bedrooms of our 
children so they're all alone when they're watching that,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	For Mrs. Clinton, who has been characterized by some Republican  
critics as being too liberal, the event allowed her to strike a 
conservative note when it came to parental involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	A Senate reported released Thursday also called for parents to  
do more to shield their children from media violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, requested by Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and prepared  
by the Republican staff of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which he 
chairs, concluded that the media dominate children's lives, that 
they are exceedingly violent and that the images lead to real world 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	It called for a ban on advertising for adult programming at  
times when children are most likely to be watching television or 
listening to the radio, and said the television, motion picture, 
music and video game industries should be encouraged to rate their 
products using a similar rating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Arriving at an elementary school for the latest stop of her  
``listening tour'' of New York, Mrs. Clinton was greeted by more 
than 100 fans and a handful of placard-carrying critics. One sign 
read: ``Hillary, go back to Arkansas on the jackass you rode in 
on.'' A small picture of President Clinton appeared next to the 
word ``jackass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inside, the first lady blasted Congress for considering taking a  
vacation without having completed work on tough gun-control 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress should get back to work before our children go back  
to school ... This is too important an issue to be put on the back 
burner,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the day came word of another fatal shooting with three  
people reported dead in Alabama and a suspect taken into custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's criticism came as she continued her summer-long  
``listening tour'' across New York. The first lady, who has never 
lived or worked in New York, is eyeing the Senate seat being 
vacated by fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. On the 
Republican side, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and two Long 
Island congressmen, Rick Lazio and Peter King, are considering the 
race. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 07:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sotomayor Angry About Loss of Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Cuban high jump great Javier Sotomayor, angry over  
being stripped of his Pan American gold medal when cocaine was 
detected in his urine, said he never knowingly took the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have only seen that substance in the movies,'' Sotomayor  
told the Communist Party daily Granma in an interview published 
today. ``I don't need any kind of trick to jump 2.30'' meters (7 
feet, 6 1/2 inches). 
</P>
<P>
	He said he doesn't even take vitamins.  
</P>
<P>
	In the interview granted in his home in Havana's fashionable  
Miramar neighborhood, Sotomayor said he had undergone countless 
drug tests both for various athletic competitions and by doctors 
who work for Cuba's sports program and no traces had ever been 
found before. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am a victim,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	So far, Sotomayor has talked only to Cuba's  
government-controlled media, which stands behind his claims of 
innocence and insists that he was the victim of a ``manipulation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign reporters arriving at his light blue stucco one-story  
home have been turned away by his family. 
</P>
<P>
	He was spotted by reporters briefly Wednesday night when he  
drove into his garage in his red Mercedes before someone closed the 
garage door behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	Recreational drug use remains rare in Cuba, and is frowned upon  
by Fidel Castro's government, which considers it just another 
negative byproduct of capitalism. 
</P>
<P>
	Such use has grown in recent years, however, with an increase of  
tourism to the island nation. Worried about narcotics use among 
youth who befriend visiting tourists, the government shut down many 
of Havana's nightclubs for several weeks early this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba To Fight Sotomayor Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Cuba's Olympic committee president  
accused ``enemies of Cuba'' with trying to discredit high jumper 
Javier Sotomayor, a national hero who tested positive for cocaine 
at the Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Ramon Fernandez, a vice president of the Cuban Council of  
Ministers, made some veiled references Thursday to the United 
States during a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``My conviction is that there are foreign interests set out to  
harm us,'' Fernandez said. ``They denied before the plots to 
assassinate, to sabotage ... What is the hairy, ugly, powerful hand 
behind this? We do not know yet. ... With technology and power, 
certain agencies can do anything, even things we can't think of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba will fight Sotomayor's expected two-year suspension from  
international competition that will force him out of this month's 
world championships and next year's Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports minister Humberto Rodriguez couldn't say on what grounds  
they might appeal or offer any explanation for the presence of 
cocaine in two urine samples taken from the world champion and 
four-time Pan Ams gold medalist. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is something I do not have to explain,'' he said while  
offering a lecture on the value of sport to Cuba and the honor and 
unimpeachable integrity of Cuban athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our athletes have had to compete under an atmosphere of  
hostility, exaggerated provocation and unlimited intolerance. We 
have been subject to such pressure in training centers . . . phone 
calls, personal messages in direct and indirect provocations,'' he 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Roriguez singled out Joe Cubas, a sports agent who has arranged  
for the defection of many Cuban athletes, including, last week, 
pitcher Danys Baez. 
</P>
<P>
	``That mercenary was walking the streets at night, enticing and  
provoking not only our athletes, but also our journalists,'' 
Rodriguez said. ``But of course our country, our land, our people 
are beyond anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez emphasized he was not accusing games doctors of  
anything. Instead, he claimed ``this is a maneuver against Cuba 
through Sotomayor by enemies of Cuba.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban officials said Sotomayor never took cocaine and charged  
the substance was planted in something he ate or drank. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is such a gentleman. To us, it is almost impossible he  
would take this substance,'' said professor Rodrigo Alvarez Cambra, 
director of the orthopedic complex of Cuba. ``He has told us he has 
not taken this substance and we believe his word. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is why we know this is a manipulation in the case of  
Javier Sotomayor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
