<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Defends Campaign Finance Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno denied Thursday  
that investigations of alleged Democratic campaign finance abuses 
have been kept alive to block Republicans in Congress from pursuing 
their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is certainly not true'' that investigations appearing to be  
dormant are kept on an active list to thwart congressional 
investigators, who are unable to question people targeted by the 
Justice Department, Reno said at her weekly briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of any basis for concluding that at all,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the investigations are more than a year old. Reno said  
she could not comment on any pending matters. 
</P>
<P>
	The attorney general was responding to questions about a column  
by Robert Novak of the Chicago Sun-Times. He reported earlier this 
week that an internal status report of the Justice Department's 
campaign finance task force listed as ``ongoing'' several 
investigations of Democratic fund raisers and donors that appear to 
have made little progress. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Government and Reform Committee has pursued its own  
investigation of the donors. Its chairman, Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., 
has complained bitterly that the committee's work has been stymied 
by the Justice Department and accused Reno of protecting President 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton's committee has been wanting to question Democratic fund  
raiser John Huang, who is accused of making illegal campaign 
contributions. As a chief fund raiser for the Asian-American 
community in 1996, Huang brought in $1.6 million in questionable 
donations that later were returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang cooperated with the Justice Department's task force and  
arranged a plea bargain. Last month Burton asked the judge in the 
case to postpone Huang's sentencing hearing until Huang agrees to 
testify before the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday the Justice Department's task force filed court  
papers saying that under the plea agreement Huang does not have to 
testify before his hearing, scheduled for Aug. 12. Huang will go 
before the committee after he has been sentenced and assert his 
Fifth Amendment rights, the documents said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Wednesday Burton's committee subpoenaed task force  
records on several aspects of the campaign finance investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said she would try to work with the committee, but noted  
potential conflicts in turning over documents. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are matters relating to pending investigations and  
pending prosecutions in which if we provide information and if it's 
made public can have a dramatic impact on the pending 
investigation,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno also said prosecutions are a function of the executive  
branch, and ``for Congress to be involved in the management of an 
investigation or a prosecution produces questions about is it being 
handled the right way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
