<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears Trying To Revive Pass Rush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLATTEVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- Richard Dent. Steve McMichael. Dan  
Hampton. Trace Armstrong. Alonzo Spellman. 
</P>
<P>
	For 10 years, the Chicago Bears had one of the most feared pass  
rushes in the NFL. Just the sight of a big, bruising lineman could 
be enough to make a quarterback bobble the ball or dump it off. 
</P>
<P>
	But the last few years, to put it nicely, the Bears' pass rush  
isn't what it used to be. No offense to Jim Flanigan, but when a 
tackle leads a team in sacks, that's usually not a good sign. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are questions that we've talked about through the whole  
off-season,'' coach Dick Jauron said. ``We've got to get production 
from the quarterback position, regardless of who it is. We've got 
to have an effective running game in order to be successful. And 
we've got to have a pass rush and we've got to find it from the 
defensive end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consistency at defensive end has been Chicago's biggest problem.  
While Dent was a fixture at right end from 1984 to 1993 and 
Armstrong at left end from 1989 to 1994, the roster from the last 
four seasons reads like a guest list. Spellman at left end one 
year, right end the next. John Thierry switching sides. Albert 
Fontenot, Carl Reeves, Shawn Lee, Mark Thomas and Bryan Robinson -- 
they all got a try at one time or another. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterbacks, meanwhile, got away practically unscathed. The  
Bears had 28 sacks last season, tied for last in the NFL with 
Cincinnati and way behind the league average of 40.3. Flanigan led 
the team with 8 1/2 sacks. He and linebacker Barry Minter shared the 
team lead in 1997 with six sacks. 
</P>
<P>
	So when Jauron took over as coach in late January, one of his  
first moves was to shore up defensive end. He recruited Clyde 
Simmons -- 10th on the NFL's all-time sack list and a two-time Pro 
Bowler -- to be a pass-rush specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know Clyde Simmons. Everybody in the league knows Clyde  
Simmons,'' Jauron said. ``He's a proven pass-rusher and he's a 
force at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears also signed Jamal Duff, who had three sacks and a  
career-high 38 tackles with Washington last season. They continued 
their conversion of Robinson, who played the last five games of the 
season at left end. 
</P>
<P>
	They also used their second-round pick on Russell Davis, who  
played end as a freshman and sophomore at North Carolina and has 
been compared to the Green Bay Packers' Vonnie Holliday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm real rusty and I feel kind of sloppy out there. But each  
day, I think I'm progressing,'' said Davis, who played tackle his 
last two seasons at Carolina. ``I don't feel any pressure on me to 
be the savior. Clyde's here, Bryan Robinson's here. Those guys are 
veterans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Progress is slow, though. Duff has drawn a lot more attention  
this week, and the rest of the ends seemed to have made more 
progress in the last couple of days, too. 
</P>
<P>
	But they're still nowhere near where Jauron and the rest of his  
staff want them to be. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're getting good play out of them at times. We're not  
getting the consistent play we need or want,'' Jauron said. ``But 
in fact, at this point in camp, we're probably not getting as 
consistent of play anywhere as we wanted. So we'll just have to 
wait and see that one.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
