<DOCNO> APW19990805.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Young's Comeback Still in Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stockton, Calif (AP) -- Bryant Young walks and runs easily now,  
and that's saying a lot considering the gruesome injury that ended 
his season last November. 
</P>
<P>
	A star defensive tackle for the San Francisco 49ers, Young has  
made remarkable progress since breaking both bones in his lower 
right leg in a freak collision with a teammate. 
</P>
<P>
	There's even a good chance, according to coach Steve Mariucci,  
that Young could be ready for the Sept. 12 regular season opener at 
Jacksonville, a prospect once regarded as unthinkable because of 
the severity of the injury. At one time, the 49ers forecast a 
midseason return. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, Young's comeback is a work in progress and will  
remain so even after he resumes playing. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I get back on the field, it doesn't stop there. That's  
where it starts,'' Young said. ``I've been feeling pretty good 
about how things have been going so far. It can only get better as 
long as I keep working at it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very serious injury and I've been very careful and  
tried to be as honest with myself as possible, listening to my body 
and I think I've done a pretty good job. Really, I feel I have a 
bright outlook.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young has indeed come a long way in the eight months since  
suffering the devastating injury. The tibia and fibula snapped when 
linebacker Ken Norton Jr.'s helmet struck Young's leg as he braced 
to tackle New York Giants quarterback Kent Graham last Nov. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Young was lifted from the soggy turf in his uniform, placed on a  
gurney and wheeled to an ambulance that transported him to Stanford 
Hospital, where he spent the next two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	He underwent three operations, including the insertion of a  
titanium rod in the tibia to stabilize the weight-bearing bone. His 
leg swelled badly after surgery and doctors had to slice 6-inch 
openings on both sides of his calf to drain fluids and relieve 
inflammation. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it happened, you think, `Wow, is my career over?''' said  
Young, who also underwent skin graft surgery to repair the wounds 
on his calf. ``And you never know where it's going to end up at, 
but with prayer and the support of my family, friends, the 
organization, and my teammates, they've all helped me along. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, there were some tough times but once I was able to  
start walking and then gradually going to a light jog, and then 
sprinting, I knew in my heart I would be able to come back from 
this injury. It does stay with you because of the way it happened. 
But I think it's healthy to think about it. It can only help you to 
deal with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deep scars on his calf are about the only visible sign of  
the injury. The metal rod will remain in his leg for the 
foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's feeling pretty good,'' Young said. ``But if it was  
bothering me, and I wasn't able to do the things I've been doing, I 
would have had to make a decision to have it taken out. It feels 
very natural. It's a light piece of metal so I'm able to work and 
run like I was before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the club's training camp, the 27-year-old Young is still  
working apart from the team, engaged in daily rapid-fire 
rehabilitation and conditioning drills under the supervision of 
physical development coordinator Jerry Attaway. 
</P>
<P>
	What quickly becomes clear is that Young is as powerfully built  
as ever -- he can bench press 500 pounds. He still possesses an 
explosive burst off the ball and continues to showcase in his 
workouts the intense, determined style that epitomized his play and 
made him such a defensive force. 
</P>
<P>
	Young is expected to be activated from the physically unable to  
perform list by the middle of next week, allowing him to start 
practicing with the team on a limited basis. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll start off slowly,'' said Mariucci, adding that in all  
likelihood Young will prepare for the season without playing in any 
of the team's four exhibitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got to be able to go through all the drills that we do  
without having any pain, without favoring it, without having any 
problem. He's got to be able to go 1-on-1 pass rush. He's got to go 
1-on-1 against offensive lineman in the run game and be able to 
hold up. Then he's got to be able to take on some double-team 
blocks. He's got to be able to defeat the trap block coming from 
the side, but we can do that in a controlled environment. You're 
not going to have nine bodies flying around in piles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young said he's confident he can regain his past form.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty confident I can be the same player if not better,''  
he said. ``Once I decide to step on the field and see how things 
go, that will really tell me where I'm at.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
