<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Opposes 'Claritin Bill' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The sick, poor and elderly who need  
prescriptions would suffer from a bill that would extend patents on 
seven drugs, a former senator who represents consumer groups said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Metzenbaum of the Consumer Federation of American said  
the legislation would block manufacturers of generic drugs from 
making cheaper versions of brand-name medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill is essentially a tax on the uninsured, the poor, the  
sick and the elderly,'' Metzenbaum, a former Democratic senator 
from Ohio, told the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``I strongly urge 
you to reject it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, sponsored by Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., and Reps.  
Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., and Jim McDermott, D-Wash., would allow the 
companies that make seven prescription drugs to ask the U.S. Patent 
and Trademark Office for three years of patent protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The protection would extend that afforded under a 1984 law that  
gave the companies making Claritin and six other drugs only 
two-year patent extensions rather than the five years given other 
pharmaceuticals. 
</P>
<P>
	When a patent expires, generic drug makers can manufacture  
cheaper versions, which could give makers of name-brand medicines 
less incentive to develop new drugs. Supporters of the legislation 
say Congress has a constitutional duty to foster the research and 
development of new medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	``A fair patent process will help consumers in the short term  
with affordable drugs and in the long term by supporting the 
research that produces new medicines,'' Torricelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue has become an expensive legislative fight in Congress  
involving some of Capitol Hill's top lobbyists. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough Corp., which makes Claritin, has brought in some  
big names to push legislation that could extend the patent on its 
popular anti-allergy drug by three years. The patent is set to 
expire in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without fair patent protection, we simply could not generate  
the necessary capital that allows us to make these risky and large 
investments,'' Richard Jay Kogan, chairman and CEO of 
Schering-Plough Corp., told the committee. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers' Harper Set for Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- San Diego Chargers cornerback Dwayne  
Harper has steel in his eyes to match the steel in his neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Harper will play his first game Sunday in almost a year, coming  
back after neck surgery which would have prompted many 33 year olds 
to give up football. 
</P>
<P>
	A collision with teammate Rodney Harrison and Buffalo receiver  
Andre Reed left Harper with a fractured bone in his neck. Surgery, 
faith and a metal plate in his neck have Harper ready to challenge 
for his starting job again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just taking the same approach as before,'' Harper said  
Thursday, ahead of Sunday's exhibition match against the Denver 
Broncos at Stadium Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to worry about what happened last year with my  
neck I'm just going to go out there and do whatever I can to help 
my team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harper missed 15 games last season, and, with other injuries, he  
has been restricted to just 29 games in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	His starting place went to another 33-year-old, Charles Dimry,  
one of the few NFL players to face a more harrowing time than 
Harper in 1998. Dimry lost his wife Francine to leukemia five 
months ago and was honored as San Diego's most inspirational 
player. Despite his wife's illness, Dimry had an explosive season 
with 63 tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	While injured players are usually given a clear ride back into  
the starting lineup, Dimry did enough to hold onto the position. 
</P>
<P>
	Harper, who says he feels like he's lining up for his rookie  
season, is pressuring Dimry, saying his decision to continue 
``wasn't too hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have very strong faith in the man above, God, and support  
from my family and friends and a doctor who made me feel very 
confident about the surgery,'' Harper said. ``It's taken a long 
time just thinking about whether or not I was going to come out and 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He says the long time on the sideline has evaporated any fears  
he might have had. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think if I go out there with fear, something bad could  
happen,'' Harper said. ``You've just got to go out there with your 
natural self.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harper admits some players would have retired.  
</P>
<P>
	``It'd be nice if I play two or three more years,'' said Harper.  
``I've had a good career and I'll just go out and play as many as I 
can until my body says no more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I have to prove to anyone that I can still play  
the game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 00:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought May Deter Leef Peepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GUILFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Each autumn, millions of people flock to  
New England for a glimpse of the brilliant red, orange and yellow 
leaves. 
</P>
<P>
	But with a summer drought already causing maples, elms and  
poplars to dry up, merchants and innkeepers who rely on tourism to 
sustain their quaint towns fear tourists won't have much to look at 
this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very concerned about the whole area because the drought  
is terrible and it is drying up the grass and affecting the 
trees,'' said Terry Kinsman, 73, who owns the Felshaw Tavern, a 
pre-Revolutionary War bed and breakfast in Putnam, with her husband 
Herb. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trees are not as robust as they should be, though their  
roots are very deep. I pray they will be all right,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the East Coast has been stuck for weeks in a devastating  
drought, by some accounts one of the worst this century. Foresters 
across New England predict that if the drought continues, the 
leaves will begin to change color in late September instead of 
mid-October. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathryn Vreeland, a climatologist at the Northeast Regional  
Climate Center at Cornell University, said the drought is taking a 
toll. 
</P>
<P>
	``Already I'm noticing leaves on the ground in upstate New  
York,'' she said. ``Some trees are brown. I think it's a mechanism 
where the trees kind of go into shutdown mode so they might have a 
chance at living if they get through this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut state forester Donald Smith said some birches and  
red maples already have begun to turn color, but the damage has 
been limited. For the most part, the trees are holding their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some trees are wilting and may be losing some leaves, but  
there's no statewide problem,'' he said. ``It will vary with the 
region of the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brent Teillon, chief of forest protection for the Vermont  
Department of Forests and Parks, said he and his colleagues are 
concerned about the possibility of forest fires. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we need is more rain and we need it now,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	If the region gets significant rainfall soon, the foliage season  
could be saved, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has a great chance of recovery. Trees are tremendous in  
their ability to bounce back, but the next couple of weeks are 
going to be important,'' Teillon said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Hampshire, the state director of forests and lands  
doesn't think tourists and others will be able to see the trees 
through the forest. Philip Bryce said individual trees are 
suffering, but ``as you look out over the landscape, we're not 
really going to see anything much different in terms of the fall 
colors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't believe folks are going to be able to tell much of  
difference,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Isaac Shepard House, a 1740 Colonial-style bed and  
breakfast in Plainfield, 79-year-old Elizabeth Kemp is using a 
garden hose to fight for the hollies, pines and locust trees 
growing on her five acres. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm lucky in the fact that my 200-year-old maples are  
probably pretty well protected. Their roots are pretty deep,'' she 
said. ``It may be that some of my new trees will die, but I think 
it's too early to tell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some bed and breakfast owners worry about the financial  
repercussions of a poor foliage season, Wilhelmina Smith, owner of 
the Highland Lodge in Greensboro, Vt., isn't worried. Travelers 
have already booked every weekend of leaf-peeping season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Foliage is so subjective, you can't measure whether it was  
great or not,'' she said. ``I never predict foliage in advance.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 07:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Voting on Tax Compromise Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Offering a multitude of tax breaks for average  
taxpayers and special interests, Republicans readied a 10-year, 
$792 billion tax cut for final congressional approval in defiance 
of repeated veto threats from President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The House planned to vote on a compromise version of the bill  
today, with the Senate expected to follow later in the day or 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders will not send the bill to the White House until  
September, hoping to build public support during the August recess 
and avoid an immediate veto. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. President, listen,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,  
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. ``Listen to the 
American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton and most Democrats on Capitol Hill don't believe  
people are clamoring for tax cuts and prefer that projected budget 
surpluses be used to first safeguard Social Security and Medicare, 
pay down public debt and ensure adequate levels of government 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're to make the most of this prosperity, we simply have  
to put first things first,'' Clinton said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Clinton has said he would sign a modest tax cut of  
perhaps $300 billion, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said in an 
interview that he saw no signs of compromise with the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any indication that he's serious at all,'' said  
Lott, R-Miss. ``I'm hopeful, because I want it very badly. But the 
president has shown no inclination to engage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in a signal that the GOP doesn't expect the bill to ever  
become law, many of the major provisions would expire after 2008. 
That means current law would return into force unless the cuts were 
renewed by a future Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Republicans said the projected $2.9 trillion surplus over  
the next decade was enough to meet Clinton's priorities and still 
enact the largest tax cut since 1981, mainly by delaying full 
impact of the breaks until well into the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the big-ticket item in the 10-year package would  
trim all income tax rates by 1 percentage point: First, the bottom 
15 percent rate would drop to 14 percent by 2003, followed by all 
the others in 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, repeal of the estate tax would take place in small  
increments beginning in 2003, with the full impact delayed until 
2009. Relief from the ``marriage penalty'' that hits many 
two-income couples would phase in beginning in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the tax cut for 2000 would total only $5.2 billion and  
only $156.2 billion over its first five years, said Lindy Paull, 
staff director for the Joint Committee on Taxation, which makes 
official tax estimates for Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the partisan gridlock, Republicans made sure their tax  
bill was chock full of items that would please many GOP 
constituencies, ranging from pro-family conservative groups to 
international and domestic business. 
</P>
<P>
	The Family Research Council, for example, joined GOP lawmakers  
at a Capitol Hill news conference to hail the marriage penalty 
provisions, which have been beefed up from an original House 
measure that caused some grumbling among conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide tax breaks for education, long-term  
health care and health insurance premiums, repeal the alternative 
minimum tax for individuals and cut top capital gains tax rates for 
most taxpayers from 20 percent to 18 percent retroactive to Jan. 1, 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	It also contained some special targets: a repeal of a 10 percent  
excise tax on certain kinds of fishing tackle boxes; an increase in 
tax breaks for reforestation expenses incurred by timber companies; 
breaks for purchasers of nuclear plants aimed at the costs of 
cleaning up reactor sites; and a credit for electricity produced 
from poultry waste. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would extend the research and development tax  
credit sought by high-tech businesses by five years, instead of the 
permanent extension they want. That brought a retort from 
Democrats, who are competing fiercely for support from those same 
companies and sought a permanent extension in their tax plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We listened and we delivered in our plan,'' said Sen. Harry  
Reid, D-Nev. ``The Republicans have done nothing more than talk.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
