<HEADLINE> Mexico Soccer Celebration Kills Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A 10-year-old girl and a teen-age boy were  
killed in separate accidents during late-night festivities 
celebrating Mexico's victory in the Confederations Cup tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Fatima Sheila Torres Rodriguez died when she was struck by a car  
about 2:15 Thursday morning in downtown Mexico City, the government 
news agency Notimex reported. Two women were injured in the same 
accident and taken to hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen-year-old Luis Alberto Monrreal Ibarra was electrocuted  
shortly after leaving Azteca Stadium where Mexico's national team 
beat Brazil 4-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ibarra and a friend came in contact with power cables while  
crossing a pedestrian bridge, the report said. The friend was 
hospitalized with burns. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Mexicans took to the streets late Thursday to  
celebrate the nation's first victory in a major international 
soccer tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	A celebration at Mexico's Angel of Independence monument turned  
violent when fans began throwing cans at police, Notimex said. 
Twenty people were arrested and about 10 injured. 
  	   	
</P>
