<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Die, 6 Missing, on Bering Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- A flotilla of skiffs carrying Russian  
Eskimos home from a visit to Alaska ran into a storm that flipped 
and sank one boat, drowning two people. Three more boats and six 
people remained missing today. 
</P>
<P>
	The group of 37 people had set out in 14 small boats Tuesday  
morning for the 65-mile trip from the Alaska village of Gambell on 
St. Lawrence Island to the coastal town of Provideniya, Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	They were returning from a visit to friends and relatives when  
they got caught in a storm with 35 mph winds and eight- to 10-foot 
seas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard was called out just before midnight Tuesday  
after two skiffs reached Provideniya and those on board told 
authorities of the dozen boats, which were 12 to 16 feet long, 
still trying to make the crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the boats overturned and a father and son drowned. Others  
aboard, including an American photographer, were rescued. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight more boats ultimately reached Provideniya. Three boats and  
six people were still missing today. 
</P>
<P>
	Many residents of Russia's Chukotsk Peninsula, where Provideniya  
is located, share the same Siberian Yupik Eskimo ancestry and 
language with residents of Alaska's St. Lawrence Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidi Bradner, a free-lance photographer who grew up in Alaska,  
was briefly hospitalized on arrival in Provideniya after spending 
time in the cold water. Bradner was working on a magazine story 
about the renewal of relations between native people on the two 
sides of the border. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard resumed the search today. A C-130 and two Coast  
Guard helicopters searched the U.S. side Wednesday evening while 
Russian rescue craft looked on their side of the area. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
