<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Push $792B Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A 10-year, $792 billion Republican tax cut,  
sure to be vetoed by President Clinton but embraced by the GOP as a 
bedrock political issue, hurtled toward final congressional passage 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed the bill 221-206, and final Senate approval was  
expected by early evening. 
</P>
<P>
	With little chance of becoming law, the bill will serve mainly  
as a defining issue between Republicans and Democrats in the 2000 
struggle for control of Congress and the race for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a dramatic difference between Democrats and  
Republicans in this capital city, and this is the dividing line,'' 
said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and 
Means Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders will not send the bill to Clinton until September,  
to prevent a veto while Congress is away for its August recess. Top 
Republicans intend to fan out across the country in an effort to 
sell the public on the wisdom of the tax cut -- and demonstrate 
their political priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a good deal for the American people,'' said House  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. ``It's a fair, responsible and 
balanced tax relief bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, which would be the largest tax cut since 1981, would  
trim the bottom 15 percent income tax rate to 14 percent in 2003 
and reduce the other rates by 1 percentage point in 2005. Relief 
from the ``marriage penalty'' that affects millions of two-income 
couples would begin in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The estate tax would be repealed gradually starting in 2003, and  
capital gains taxes would be cut from 20 percent to 18 percent for 
most investors retroactive to Jan. 1, 1999. There are breaks for 
education and health care, expanded IRAs and pensions and a legion 
of breaks for businesses large and small. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats portrayed the package as primarily favoring the  
wealthy and business and conservative groups. They said it unwisely 
uses a third of the next decade's projected $2.9 trillion budget 
surplus at the expense of safeguarding Social Security and 
Medicare, repaying the national debt and preventing deep cuts in 
government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is radical, it is risky and it is reckless,'' said Sen.  
Kent Conrad, D-N.D. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Capitol Hill rally, Clinton again promised to veto the bill  
and said he would only consider a modest tax cut aimed at the 
middle class once those other priorities are met. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ought to ask ourselves how much is left, and whatever it  
is, we ought to give it back to the American people in a tax cut,'' 
the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading Republican presidential candidate, Texas Gov. George  
W. Bush, said during an appearance in West Des Moines, Iowa, that 
he would strongly support the tax bill and urged Clinton to 
reconsider. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my judgment, we ought to pass back the money to the people  
who pay the taxes,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most polls show the public considers tax cuts a lower surplus  
priority than ensuring Social Security is ready for baby boomer 
retirements. One reason could be that nearly half the public thinks 
wealthy people would benefit most from the tax cuts, according to 
an ABC News poll of 1,012 adults taken July 28-Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	That poll, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 3  
percentage points, indicated that about a fourth of the people 
think the cuts would benefit everyone equally, while 14 percent 
said it would benefit middle-income people most, and 6 percent said 
the poor would benefit most. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said such polls only demonstrated that they are  
acting on principle by returning some of the surplus with tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know it may not be the single most popular thing, but it's  
the right thing to do,'' said Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, however, found a far different reason for many of the  
breaks: an effort by the GOP to please business and conservative 
political supporters. ``A wish list so that every contributor ... 
will get a promise,'' Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., called it. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the legislation is crammed with dozens of items sought  
by business lobbyists. Some examples: 
</P>
<P>
	--The National Federation of Independent Business, National  
Restaurant Association and others got an increase in the deduction 
for business meals from 50 percent to 60 percent, costing $3.8 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--For global energy companies, a $1.6 billion repeal of the limit  
on foreign tax credits for oil and gas produced overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	--For defense contractors, repeal of a limit on the benefits  
companies receive to compensate for the cost of selling military 
products abroad, worth $1.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--For Silicon Valley firms, the National Association of  
Manufacturers and others, a five year extension of the research and 
development tax credit, worth $13.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--For chicken farmers, a new credit for electricity produced from  
poultry waste, along with a four-year extension of a biomass and 
wind electricity credits, about $534 million. 
</P>
<P>
	This last item produced one of the more lighthearted moments of  
Thursday's debate, when Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, held up a 
large photo of a plucked chicken and compared it to the fleecing of 
key government programs through tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a chicken this is,'' Doggett said. ``They've given new  
meaning to chicken deluxe.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
