<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 0.63; Nasdaq Off 49.`9 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today as a government report on  
rising labor costs increased fears that the Federal Reserve will 
raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 0.63 at 10,674.14. Earlier in the session, the Dow had fallen 
108 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also fell today. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 8.66 at 1,296.67, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was off 49.19 at 2,490.90, continuing its steep decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell as traders awaited and then received the Labor  
Department's report on productivity and labor costs. The department 
said American workers' productivity slowed significantly in the 
spring, rising at an annual rate of just 1.3 percent, while labor 
costs surged at an annual rate of 3.8 percent, the worst showing 
for this measurement since the end of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, increased productivity has enabled U.S.  
businesses to counteract rising labor costs. But Fed Chairman Alan 
Greenspan has cautioned that investors have been too confident that 
strong productivity gains would continue. 
</P>
<P>
	If productivity levels off and labor costs rise, that could  
persuade the Fed to raise rates in an effort to slow down economic 
growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The market remained nervous as it also anticipated Friday's  
unemployment report, another widely watched barometer of U.S. 
economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online was among the biggest decliners on the New York  
Stock Exchange, falling 8 3/16 to 79 1/4. While the entire Internet 
sector has been suffering in recent sessions, AOL is also being 
hampered by battles over its instant-messaging technology. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's biggest retailers reported that sales rose to  
better-than-expected levels in July. Shares of Saks Inc., the 
parent company for luxury retailer Saks Fifth Avenue, rose 1 1/8 to 21 
15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-4 margin on the  
NYSE, where volume came to 289.54 million shares, ahead of 
Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 3.78 at 610.68, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 7.56 at 769.39. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.95 to 422.75.  

</P>
</TEXT>
