<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gwynn Still One Short of Milestone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Tony Gwynn was only an observer Thursday night  
as one of baseball's most cherished milestones was reached. 
</P>
<P>
	His shining moment will have to wait for another day in another  
city. 
</P>
<P>
	Never before had two players entered a game with a chance to  
each grab a big piece of history. Mark McGwire got his, and then 
some, hitting his 500th and 501st career homers for St. Louis in a 
10-3 loss to San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn needed two hits to become the 22nd player to get 3,000,  
but the Padres star didn't quite make it. He flied out in the 
first, walked in the second, flied out again in the fifth, grounded 
to second in the seventh, then lined a two-run double down the 
right-field line in the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like I swung the bat pretty good tonight, but I fell  
one hit short,'' Gwynn said. ``I'll move on to the next stop, which 
is Montreal, and hopefully I can get it there tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres open a four-game series against the Expos on Friday  
night. Dan Smith starts for Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire became the 16th player to hit 500 homers, connecting  
against Andy Ashby in the third inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn, stationed in right field, removed the glove from his  
right hand, tucked it under his arm, and clapped as McGwire rounded 
the bases. He stood and watched as fireworks exploded, streamers 
littered the field and the sellout crowd stood and cheered the 
hometown hero for three minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough, because the 500th home run tied the game,''  
Gwynn said. ``I'm standing out in right field wondering, `Should I 
clap like everybody else, or try to be a professional?' But 500 
only comes around a few times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire did it again in the eighth, when he hit his second homer  
of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals fans were rooting hard for Gwynn, recalling how crowds  
around the NL embraced McGwire on his way to 70 home runs last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those cheering on Gwynn was Lou Brock, the Cardinals Hall  
of Famer and the last NL player to get 3,000 hits. He reached the 
milestone 20 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd have loved to have seen him get it here,'' said Brock, who  
said he will not travel to Montreal to see Gwynn continue his 
pursuit. 
</P>
<P>
	After his ninth-inning hit, Gwynn doffed his helmet from second  
base as the St. Louis fans gave him a standing ovation. He was 
greeted with another loud ovation as he left the field after the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once again, it is amazing to me as a visiting player to be  
treated like I've been treated here,'' Gwynn said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
