<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 5, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Congress Passes $792B Tax Cut Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans overcame Democratic opposition  
today to narrowly win final passage of a 10-year, $792 billion tax 
cut the GOP calls a deserving return of budget surpluses to wage 
earners and businesses. President Clinton denounced the bill and 
promised a veto. The Senate voted 50-49 for the final package a few 
hours after the House passed it 221-206. With little chance of 
becoming law, the bill will serve mainly as a defining issue 
between Republicans and Democrats in the 2000 struggle for control 
of Congress and the race for the White House. 

</P>
<P>
	House Compromises on HMO Legislation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats and breakaway Republicans  
announced an agreement today on legislation that strengthens the 
rights of patients dealing with managed care plans and lowers their 
barriers to medical care. The bill would ease access for the 
insured to medical care in emergency rooms, from specialists in 
clinical trials and elsewhere. It also would establish an outside 
review process for patients who believe they unfairly were denied 
care. Companies obeying an independent panel's ruling still could 
be sued in state courts, but would not be liable for punitive 
damages. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL To Feature After-Hours Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America Online will feature a new section  
devoted to after-hours stock trading, inviting the Web's biggest 
mainstream audience into a market dominated by elite investors. The 
new service, scheduled for a November launch, will provide AOL's 17 
million subscribers with stock quotes and related information on 
the often volatile dealings that take place outside the regular 
hours on traditional markets like the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Charged in Alabama Shootings  
</P>
<P>
	PELHAM, Ala. (AP) -- A man allegedly shot two co-workers to death  
at their office today, then killed a third person at a company 
where he used to work, in a burst of workplace violence just one 
week after the Atlanta office massacre. Alan Eugene Miller, 34, was 
arrested shortly after the shootings when police spotted him on 
nearby Interstate 65 and forced him to pull over. He briefly 
scuffled with officers, and a gun was found in his car. Miller was 
charged with three counts of capital murder. The motive was 
unclear. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Convicted in Alabama Gay Slaying  
</P>
<P>
	ROCKFORD, Ala. (AP) -- A man accused of helping kill a gay man  
because of an unwanted advance was convicted of capital murder and 
sentenced to life without parole today. Charles M. Butler Jr., 21, 
a boyish-looking former construction worker, was convicted in the 
slaying of Billy Jack Gaither, 39, whose throat was slashed and 
body burned on a pile of old tires. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Report Slams Media Violence  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Parents need to do more to shield children  
from violence in movies, TV shows, music and other media, according 
to a Senate report issued today. Senate Judiciary Committee 
Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, asked for the report after the April 
shooting at Colorado's Columbine High School, which left 15 people 
dead. It reached three conclusions: that the media dominate 
children's lives, that they are ``exceedingly violent'' and that 
the images lead to real world violence, Hatch said. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Fish Oil Reduces Heart Deaths  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- People who have suffered heart attacks can reduce  
their risk of heart-related death by 30 percent by taking a fish 
oil capsule every day, a new study suggests. The Italian study is 
the most rigorous to date investigating the oil's potential 
heart-healthy properties. The study, published in this week's issue 
of The Lancet, also looked at the benefits of vitamin E pills. But, 
unlike other studies, it did not find they offer heart attack 
survivors protection from further heart problems. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Surges, Nasdaq Rebounds  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks managed their strongest rally in more  
than a week today as the Dow industrials closed up 119.05 at 
10,793.82. Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange 
outnumbered advancers 1,823-1,198. The Nasdaq was up 25.83 at 
2,565.83. 

</P>
<P>
	Poof! Magic Deal Hardaway to Suns  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Orlando Magic traded unhappy star guard Penny  
Hardaway to the Phoenix Suns today, completing the breakup of a 
team that went to the NBA Finals four years ago. After a final day 
of reconsidering their options and trying to talk Hardaway into 
staying, the Magic finally made the trade and acquired Danny 
Manning, Pat Garrity and two first-round draft picks. Hardaway will 
be paid $86 million over the next seven years. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

  	   	
