<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rams Sign Marshall Faulk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Marshall Faulk never missed a day of training  
camp his first five NFL seasons, and he doesn't want to miss any 
more after ending a 12-day holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	After signing a seven-year, $45.15 million contract with the St.  
Louis Rams that makes him the highest-paid player in franchise 
history, Faulk said his stand was never about money or skipping 
part of the training camp grind. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he is in good enough shape to play at least a few  
plays in Saturday's preseason opener against Oakland. Faulk has 
been working out under the supervision of trainer Bobby Kersee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to say what I need to do,'' he said. ``If they  
say `Marshall, we want you to make a couple carries,' fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, he said nothing can prepare a player for  
going on the field in pads. Faulk planned to start practicing today 
and joked that he might ``pass out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes a while,'' he said. ``Football is a fast game and I  
can't say exactly how long it'll take. Before that last preseason 
game, I want to be up to speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk was the NFL's best all-purpose back last season, rushing  
for 1,319 yards and catching 86 passes for the Indianapolis Colts. 
His total of 2,227 yards rushing and receiving was the 
sixth-highest total in league history, and in five seasons he has 
rushed for 5,320 yards and earned three Pro Bowl invitations. 
</P>
<P>
	He fell out of favor with Colts management, and the Rams got him  
for second- and fifth-round picks two days before the NFL draft in 
April. But the Rams view him as the next Eric Dickerson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're really excited to have him, and his record proves the  
type of player he is,'' said executive vice president Jay Zygmunt, 
who negotiated the contract with Faulk's agent, Rocky Arceneaux of 
St. Louis. ``We really think he's a franchise back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk is guaranteed $9.6 million this year, with a $7 million  
signing bonus and $2.6 million base salary. He'll make $19 million 
in the first four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The sticking point in negotiations was the fifth year, in which  
Faulk will get a $7 million salary and a $5 million roster bonus. 
The deal was structured in that fashion to prevent the Rams from 
designating Faulk as a transition or franchise player. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll also make $7 million in the sixth and seventh years. In  
addition, Faulk can void the contract after four years and become 
an unrestricted free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he'll opt out,'' Arceneaux said. ``If he gets to  
year five of the contract, there's a big reward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams knew they'd have to rework the contract he signed out  
of San Diego State as the second player taken in the 1994 draft. 
Faulk had two years to go on a deal that was scheduled to pay him 
$2.2 million in base salary this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk attended an early minicamp, saying it was a show of good  
faith, but skipped the June minicamp when talks stalled. The 
signing comes three days after the Rams scrimmaged with the Colts 
in Champaign, Ill., and Faulk said he hated to miss that gathering. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why would I duck them?'' he said. ``I would love to scrimmage  
against those guys. Nothing against the players, the coaching staff 
or Jim Irsay, but there's some people there who felt I couldn't 
play the game at the level at which I was playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, Faulk donated $500,000 to his charitable  
organization for inner-city youth. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere around the NFL:  
</P>
<P>
                             *Vikings    	
</P>
<P>
	Dimitrius Underwood might have cost himself a job with Minnesota  
by failing to return to training camp as promised. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a first-round draft pick, went AWOL after his first  
pro practice on Monday, but apologetically called his agent 24 
hours later, saying he needed to tend to a family crisis and was on 
his way back to camp. 
</P>
<P>
	But Underwood, who signed a five-year, $5.3 million contract on  
Sunday, missed Wednesday's workouts, too, leaving coach Dennis 
Green stewed and general manager Tim Connolly stumped. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not talked to him at all,'' Green said. ``We've got a  
football camp here. He knows where it's at and he knows where his 
room is. He is not here.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *Cowboys    	
</P>
<P>
	Raghib Ismail's debut with the Dallas Cowboys is on hold after  
the receiver slightly separated his left shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're calling it day-to-day, but it looks like it'll be closer  
to a week before we actually get him back on any type of full-time 
basis,'' coach Chan Gailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gailey said Ismail definitely will not play Monday night in the  
team's exhibition opener, the Hall of Fame game against the 
Cleveland Browns in Canton, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Ismail was injured while trying to catch a pass in a morning  
workout. 
</P>
<P>
	Ismail joined the Cowboys as a free agent in April. The former  
Oakland Raiders and Carolina Panthers player cashed in on the two 
best seasons of his career by signing a $21.5 million, seven-year 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	Dixon Edwards, a veteran of 18 playoff games and two Super  
Bowls, left the Dolphins on Wednesday and might sit out the season 
because of an irregular heartbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old linebacker was aware of the problem last year,  
when he started 14 games for the Minnesota Vikings. He participated 
in Miami's first three training camp workouts last week, then 
underwent further tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive coordinator George Hill said Edwards' return is a long  
shot. The Dolphins released him and terminated his contract, and 
Edwards returned the $350,000 signing bonus he received for joining 
Miami in June as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
                               *Jets    	
</P>
<P>
	After five straight days of two-a-day workouts, Eric Green was  
excused for the second straight day from training-camp sessions 
with a sore left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Eric Green can't play, we're going to have big problems,''  
coach Bill Parcells said. ``It would impact us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time Pro Bowler, who signed a four-year, $7.5 million  
free-agent contract with the Jets during the offseason, is being 
counted on to fill the void created when Kyle Brady signed with 
Jacksonville in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the Jets nor Green would reveal the exact nature of the  
problem. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Lions    	
</P>
<P>
	Detroit released ex-Notre Dame star Ron Powlus to make room for  
newcomer Donald Hollas, a former quarterback for the Oakland 
Raiders. 
</P>
<P>
	Powlus joined the Lions as a free agent, but was let go in a  
move Lions coach Bobby Ross called ``a tough thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to take a good look at Powlus,'' Ross said. ``I  
don't want five QBs out here. I wanted four, so we had to make that 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that we have Don Hollas in, he has to do a lot of catching  
up,'' Ross said of the newcomer who spent his first day in 
Detroit's camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lions corps of quarterbacks also includes starter Charlie  
Batch, Gus Frerotte and Corey Sauter. 
  	   	
</P>
