<HEADLINE> Winnie The Pooh Piano Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 200,000 toy pianos were recalled  
Thursday because a small part may pose a choking risk to children. 
</P>
<P>
	After testing the piano, the Consumer Product Safety Commission  
determined pieces on a microphone attached to the Tiger Electronics 
Pooh Poppin' Pianos may break off and create a hazard for young 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	No choking incidences or injuries have been reported, said Russ  
Rader, commission spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The lime green, eight-key piano has figures from ``Winnie the  
Pooh,'' including Pooh, Tigger and Roo. Only toys with serial 
numbers starting with ``WT'' or ``CO15D'' have the defective 
microphone. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiger Electronics of Vernon Hills, Ill., sold the toys from  
August 1997 until this month for about $20. Consumers should call 
1-888-748-2860 to find out how to receive a safe replacement toy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
