<DOCNO> APW19990805.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DeLay: Farm Aid Adds Complications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican plans to leave Social Security  
surpluses alone this year have been thrown into disarray by Senate 
passage of $7.4 billion in emergency farm aid, House Majority Whip 
Tom DeLay said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay, R-Texas, said GOP leaders still intend to pass  
tax-cutting and spending bills that don't touch the billions in 
surpluses the massive pension program is building up. By the end of 
Congress' August recess, he said, top House Republicans hope to 
decide how to do that and still move their own farm aid package 
through the chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a discussion with reporters about his party's budget  
tactics, the No. 3 House Republican said Senate approval of farm 
aid Wednesday night had complicated things. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the atomic bomb that blows up the whole strategy,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trent tried to hold off the mules and wagons, and he was  
rolled,'' Delay said, referring to Senate Majority Leader Trent 
Lott, R-Miss., ``And we'll get rolled over here if we try to stop 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay's remarks spotlighted the difficult time GOP leaders are  
having hewing to their pledge to leave Social Security surpluses 
undisturbed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congressional Budget Office has estimated there will be a  
$14 billion budget surplus next year without counting Social 
Security's surplus. DeLay said it has been the GOP's intent ``from 
the get go'' to use that money for tax cuts and spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But so far, Republicans have committed $5.3 billion of it to  
their tax bill; $4.5 billion for paying for next year's census; 
plus the still undetermined costs of the farm aid bill, which could 
well grow to about the Senate's $7.4 billion figure. 
</P>
<P>
	That excludes the price tag for other emergencies that may  
occur. It also excludes money that Republicans want to use to shore 
up a huge spending bill for health and education that is currently 
about $15 billion below last year's levels. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay said President Clinton's expected veto of several of the  
13 annual spending bills for next year would demonstrate to the 
public that it was he -- not Republicans -- who wants to use Social 
Security money for extra spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll just have to go to the American people and convince them  
it's important,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Linda Ricci of the White House Office of Management  
countered, ``Their budget doesn't meet the responsibility test and 
it doesn't meet the reality test. It's a cynical plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay spoke as Congress sorted through spending business as it  
approached its August recess. The Senate adjourned Thursday evening 
until Sept. 8, and the House worked into the night planning to do 
the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiscal 2000 begins Oct. 1. So far, Congress has completed the  
final version of just one of the 13 annual spending bills for the 
new year. With lawmakers not returning until after Labor Day, the 
pressure will be on for Clinton and lawmakers to work out their 
differences. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 217-210 to approve a $37.7 billion measure  
financing the departments of Justice, Commerce and State for next 
year after refighting a familiar battle over U.S. abortion spending 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	By 221-206, the House rejected an effort by Rep. Tony Hall,  
D-Ohio, that would have allowed payment of $244 million of this 
country's U.N. back dues without linking them to limits on abortion 
funds. Conservatives would allow the payment of the dues only if 
U.S. funds are banned for groups that use their own money to lobby 
for liberalized overseas abortion laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate debated, but did not complete, a $14.1 billion  
measure financing the Interior Department and cultural programs. 
That measure has become a battleground over mining and other issues 
pitting industry against environmental concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	In a defeat for conservatives, the Senate voted 80-16 to reject  
an effort by Sen. Bob Smith, I-N.H., to kill the National Endowment 
for the Arts. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the House's Justice-Commerce-State bill and the Senate's  
Interior bill face veto threats from the Clinton administration 
because they provide less money for many programs than the White 
House favors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
