<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Jobless Rate Rises in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NUREMBERG, Germany (AP) -- The number of jobless persons in  
Germany edged above the politically sensitive 4 million mark again 
in July, pushing the unemployment rate to 10.3 percent from 10.1 
percent a month earlier, the Labor Office said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the increase was less than expected and largely the  
result of seasonal factors such as the end of the school year. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor Office president Bernhard Jagoda said conditions were  
picking up, especially in the west, where most German industry is 
located. Jagoda also noted there were fewer people in government 
job programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The unadjusted jobless tally rose 89,000 to 4.027 million, the  
Labor Office said. The 10.3 percent rate for the month was lower 
than the 10.7 percent registered in July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Adjusted for seasonal factors, the number of jobless rose only  
1,000 -- far below analysts' expectations of about 9,000 -- after a 
15,000 rise in June. The German jobless rate was expected to have 
risen to an unadjusted 10.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Western Germany's unadjusted unemployment rate was 8.6 percent  
in July, up from 8.4 percent in June. That compared with 17.4 
percent in formerly communist eastern Germany, up from 16.8 percent 
in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of unemployed Germans topped 4 million in 1997 and  
has stubbornly held near that level since, contributing to last 
year's defeat of long-serving conservative Chancellor Helmut Kohl. 
</P>
<P>
	New Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's government has pledged to  
reduce the level by at least 1 million by 2002, but has had little 
success so far. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
