<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Lowest in 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks on Thursday dropped to their  
lowest level since late March, with the hardest hit in 
telecommunications and technology shares and in media stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies fell 6.71  
points, or 2.2 percent, to close at 292.62. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications and technology were the worst-performing  
sectors, with both indexes dropping 3.8 percent. Media was nearly 
as hard-hit, with a 3.6 percent drop. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sell-off has accelerated,'' said Joe Hall, head of  
marketing for European equities at Deutsche Bank. ``There's been 
genuine heavy selling pressure in the more expensive companies such 
as mobile phone operators, which are more sensitive to rising 
interest rates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index fell 2.8  
percent to 4,978.45, the Paris CAC-40 index was 2.0 percent lower 
to 4,240.70, London's FTSE 100 index fell 2.1 percent to 6,101.60, 
Milan's MIBtel index fell 1.9 percent to 31,850 and Amsterdam's AEX 
index fell 2.2 percent to 529.02. 
</P>
<P>
	The German telecom and industrial conglomerate Mannesmann warned  
that net profit this year will fall below last year's level. The 
company's shares fell 7.5 percent , and Nokia, Orange and the 
German software company SAP, all registered declines. 
</P>
<P>
	``The weakness in the tech sector is intensifying,'' said Nick  
Stevenson, head of European equity strategy at Paribas. 
``Mannesmann's figures weren't good and more people are getting 
nervous. It's also interesting to see how the sell-off in techs in 
the U.S. is coming through to telecoms in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Anglo-Dutch publisher Reed International fell in  
London and Amsterdam after the group posted a 10 percent slide in 
pretax earnings. Reed International fell 41.25 pence (67 cents) to 
424 pence ($7.11) in London, and Elsevier dropped EUR1.10 ($1.19) 
to EUR10.50 ($11.34) in Amsterdam. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries joining the single currency, closed down 6.54 points at 
302.89. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index fell 77.98 points to 3,512.71,  
while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed down 83.25 points at 3,502.57. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
