<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Takes New Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- For decades, private foundations have focused  
on solving specific problems in the nation's poorest communities -- 
funding a job-training program here, an after-school program there 
-- but hundreds of urban communities remain poor. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s, researchers reconsidered the narrow approach. The  
best way to eliminate poverty, according to the growing consensus, 
is by simultaneously tackling all the problems confronting poor 
neighborhoods -- crime, bad schools, the lack of jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Experiments got under way in cities such as Seattle and Chicago.  
But no foundation launched a comprehensive community building 
program nationally. Until now. 
</P>
<P>
	The Annie E. Casey Foundation, the nation's 20th largest charity  
with assets of nearly $1.6 billion, is gearing up to launch its 
``Making Connections'' program in 22 cities. Foundation officials 
are prepared to spend up to $500 million over the next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we do only what others are doing well, the question is why  
bother?'' said Ralph Smith, a vice president of the Baltimore-based 
foundation. It was established in 1948 by United Parcel Service 
founder Jim Casey in his mother's memory. 
</P>
<P>
	Making Connections aims to help poverty-stricken families earn  
more, live healthier and feel safer so they can provide better 
lives for their children. The idea is stronger families will 
eventually result in stronger communities over time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are putting families back in the center of the action,''  
Smith said. ``The solution is going to require us to reconnect 
families to opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation wants to work with neighborhoods where grassroots  
groups, foundations and government agencies are already trying to 
solve problems. Casey doesn't want to supplant the existing work, 
just make it better, Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey representatives will bring together the residents, local  
businesses, faith groups, social service agencies, local 
governments, schools and the police so that the community can 
jointly figure out which problems are the most pressing and how to 
fix them. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the foundation will award grants, provide staff and other  
resources, and work to procure more aid and support, Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say Casey has the right idea.  
</P>
<P>
	Figuring out the neighborhood's needs is a crucial step in a  
``holistic'' approach to fighting poverty, said John McKnight, a 
Northwestern University professor who has done such work in 
Chicago. The next step is to find out what the community is doing 
right and expand that effort, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Will Making Connections work? No one is sure, and experts like  
Christopher Jencks at Harvard University are skeptical. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been a huge number of these kinds of discussions  
about what's the right strategy. We're going on 35 years of tearing 
our hair over this,'' Jencks said. ``I don't think we have any 
basis to say this kind of thing is better or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casey officials know they are taking on a tough job, said Gary  
Walker, president of Public/Private Ventures, a social policy 
research group in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know whether it's going to work, but you have to have  
some admiration for the fact that they're willing to try this,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Social-welfare groups, even those working within a neighborhood,  
don't always agree what the main problems are and how to solve 
them, causing turf battles. And the foundation's biggest challenge 
will be to get jobs and investment to move into blighted areas, 
Walker said. 
</P>
<P>
	One neighborhood that could benefit from Making Connections is  
Historic East Baltimore, a turn-of-the-century rowhouse community 
about a mile from the foundation's headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug dealers haunt the 144-square-block community. Homes are  
boarded up. Trash and liquor bottles litter the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago, 24 neighborhood associations, churches, and  
social service agencies formed the Historic East Baltimore 
Community Action Coalition to improve things from the ground up. 
But the progress has been agonizingly slow. 
</P>
<P>
	Casey gave the coalition several thousand dollars, and a  
foundation subsidiary, Casey Family Services, helped set up 
after-school programs, a men's center and the like. Casey officials 
said they haven't decided if they want to launch Making Connections 
in Historic East Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer David, a 45-year-old welfare mother of two, said things  
haven't gotten any better, a sentiment shared by several other 
residents. Many people living there would move in a second if they 
could only afford to, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the main problems here is the housing,'' she said.  
``The job situation is bad. ... It would be nice if they could get 
the drug dealers out of the park. Children can't even play in the 
park. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see it getting worse. I don't see any improvements.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
