<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bills' Johnson: `I'm Not a Backup' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- It was a freak play, and Rob Johnson  
winces at the cruel memory. 
</P>
<P>
	There's Johnson, crashing to the turf on Buffalo's first  
offensive series in Indianapolis last October. 
</P>
<P>
	There's Johnson, sandwiched between the point of the football  
and Colts tackle Larry Chester. 
</P>
<P>
	There's Johnson's job, taking a perfect bounce right into the  
eager and capable hands of scrambling Doug Flutie. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays showed a separation of his rib cartilage, and the Bills  
didn't know how long Johnson would be out. 
</P>
<P>
	He has yet to reclaim his status as starting quarterback for the  
Bills. Johnson acknowledged in training camp on Thursday that 
there's no question he's the backup to Flutie. 
</P>
<P>
	``He deserves it,'' Johnson said. ``He played well last year.  
You know who's going to be in there. You don't have to be a brain 
surgeon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson lost out to fate and Flutie last year. Now, he's ready  
to return the favor to Flutie. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got everyone in his corner, which is great,'' Johnson  
said. ``That's what the quarterback needs to do. My job is to be 
there in case something happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who was signed to a $25 million contract before last  
season after just one NFL start to his credit, wasn't happy about 
being sent to the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a backup, and I've proven that,'' Johnson said  
Thursday. ``I've played pretty well in every game I've been in. I 
just haven't been able to stay healthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting isn't something Johnson does well, although he has been  
gracious about it. He left USC as the school's career leader in 
completions, yards and touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	A classic drop-back passer with a great arm, Johnson has yet to  
really use his skills in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	For three seasons at Jacksonville, Mark Brunell was there.  
</P>
<P>
	Now Flutie.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty much his town and his team right now,'' Johnson  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Flutie, once cast off as too small to play in the NFL, helped  
carry the team to the playoffs last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Flutie made the Pro Bowl and was named comeback player of the  
year. In the offseason the Bills gave him a four-year, $22 million 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson bought a house on the water in Laguna Beach, Calif. His  
surfboard sat while Johnson worked out near his parents' home in 
Mission Viejo, Calif., with his friend and former USC teammate, 
Baltimore linebacker Jeff Kopp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ran a lot of stairs and hills, and lifted,'' said Johnson,  
who came to camp in the best shape of his life. ``There's a 
140-yard hill that's straight up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Upon his arrival at camp, Johnson discovered his name listed  
beside Flutie's on the depth chart. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice that they list us as co-starters and they think that  
much of me,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	After practice, while Flutie signs autographs, Johnson zips away  
in a golf cart with third-string quarterback Alex Van Pelt. Later, 
Johnson and Flutie face off in video hockey. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just push each other,'' Johnson said. ``Doug's very  
competitive and so am I. We're very different other than that. It's 
not like we're enemies. I wish him well and I'm sure he wishes me 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is trying to be patient, but he can hear the clock  
ticking. ``I want to play,'' he said. ``I'm 26. This is going to be 
my fifth year, and I've started six games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not my decision; it's their decision,'' he said. ``I like  
it here, I like the team. If they want to keep me, great. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know there's somewhere in the league for me. If this is  
going to be Doug's team for years, they'll probably trade me and 
try to get something for me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
