<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago, London Markets in Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Mercantile Exchange and the London  
International Financial Futures and Options Exchange have formed an 
alliance to give customers electronic access to each other's 
products, a move aimed at cutting traders' costs and improving 
their efficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	The connection will allow customers to trade futures contracts  
for securities pegged to short-term interest rates for both markets 
on one computer screen, officials for the two exchanges said in a 
joint news conference Thursday with participants in Chicago and 
London. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance is set to begin early next year and will provide  
the exchanges' customers access to both the Merc's Globex2 and 
LIFFE's CONNECT electronic trading systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials also announced plans for a for-profit joint venture to  
develop new products and services -- a plan which requires 
regulatory approval both in the United States and in England. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is a response to a growing number of alliances in  
electronic trading, including a recently approved deal between 
Eurex -- LIFFE's Swiss-German competitor -- and the Chicago Board of 
Trade, the Merc's rival. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today is truly a significant step for our two exchanges,''  
said Scott Gordon, chairman of the Merc's board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Partnerships like the one we are announcing today are the wave  
of the future,'' said Gordon, who began revamping the Merc after 
his election last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In years past, there has been resistance to electronic links  
between the world's exchanges from traders in U.S. commodity 
markets who rely on the ``open outcry'' method of yelling and 
gesturing to set prices on contracts for future delivery of 
everything from uncured bacon to sophisticated financial 
securities. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gordon said that has quickly changed -- adding that  
electronic trading is quickly becoming a complement to open outcry. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is not, however, as extensive as the Eurex alliance  
with the Chicago Board of Trade. That deal calls for the Board of 
Trade to acquire Eurex's electronic trading system. 
</P>
<P>
	But officials at the Merc and LIFFE say their alliance is unique  
because it is an ``open'' system that allows each exchange to set 
up more trading alliances. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not one exchange merging with or taking over another  
exchange. ... It is not for the benefit of both exchanges; it's a 
benefit to our customers,'' said Brian Williamson, LIFFE's 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, LIFFE officials turned down a proposed alliance that  
would have linked it with the Merc and French-based Matif. 
</P>
<P>
	Some say this latest alliance offers LIFFE a chance to  
rejuvenate itself -- now that Eurex controls trading in German 
government bond futures contracts that LIFFE developed more than a 
decade ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 02:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Free Computer Network Goes Offline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cleveland Free-Net, the nation's first free  
community computer network, is already a victim of the Year 2000 
bug. 
</P>
<P>
	The system, which started as an electronic bulletin board in  
1984 at Case Western Reserve University, is scheduled to go out of 
business on Oct. 1. Its operators said the system would 
self-destruct at year's end because the computer program written 
for it can't recognize the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Operators have decided to get out early.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's just sad to see it go,'' said David Bunsey, who has  
accessed Free-Net almost since its inception. ``It's an 
institution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Raymond Neff, vice president for information services at the  
university, said rewriting Free-Net's computer program would take 
too much time and personnel. And it still wouldn't have the 
``glamour of the Web,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As its name suggests, Free-Net is free service and is a tool for  
computer users to communicate. But does not offer flashy graphics 
or services offered by commercial Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	At one time, Free-Net had 10,000 users a day. Now there are  
about 7,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
