<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers 'Steel Action Plan' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration presented steel  
industry chiefs and labor leaders with a plan Thursday to bolster 
the weakened industry, including a pledge to oppose international 
loans that would further subsidize imports. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many steelworkers and communities are experiencing continuing  
hardship as a result of last year's sharp rise in steel imports,'' 
President Clinton said in a statement released by his press 
secretary. ``I am determined to continue taking forceful action to 
address the unfair trade practices that have contributed 
significantly to this crisis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labor leaders and executives from 10 steel companies who have  
clashed with the administration over how to react to low-priced 
steel flooding U.S. docks from Japan, South Korea and other 
countries emerged from the White House session pleased with the 
administration's promises to defend anti-dumping laws in upcoming 
trade talks and to hold an international conference on unfair trade 
practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're encouraged by the recognition of the crisis, the  
framework to resolve the problems in our industry,'' said Curtis H. 
Barnette, chairman and CEO of Bethlehem Steel Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Surging steel imports in recent years have driven down prices  
and forced at least three publicly traded American steel companies 
to declare bankruptcy. Administration officials have pointed to the 
fact that imports have begun to recede as evidence that continuing 
to enforce existing trade laws is the right course. 
</P>
<P>
	But labor and the industry continued to press for tougher  
action, and the issue has vexed Vice President Al Gore as his 
presidential campaign courts labor's support. Thursday's session 
was aimed at reassuring both labor and manufacturers that steel 
remained a priority. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are going to initiate legislative actions, administrative  
actions, to help deal with this,'' said United Steel Workers 
President George Becker. ``They're dealing with the important 
elements that we want done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others were less enthused about the plan. Rep. Ralph Regula,  
R-Ohio and chairman of the House steel caucus, called it ``a purely 
political document.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too little and too late,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The industry has filed trade complaints against several  
countries and won several cases, but manufacturers complain that as 
soon as one country reduces exports of a certain type of steel, 
another steps up its exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's ``steel action plan'' includes:  
</P>
<P>
	--A pledge to block World Bank and International Monetary Fund  
loans that would further subsidize foreign steel industries and 
ensure that the next round of World Trade Organization talks 
maintains strong sanctions against unfair trade. 
</P>
<P>
	--A comprehensive Commerce Department review of existing foreign  
government subsidies of industries and other ``market destroying 
trade barriers,'' such as the decline in production of iron ore and 
coke. 
</P>
<P>
	--A global forum on unfair trade practices that can lead to  
excess capacity in the steel market, deflating prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, administration officials said Clinton would sign a  
congressional package of $1.5 billion in loans for steel, oil and 
natural gas companies to help industries rocked by low prices. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
