<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meaning of National Debt Buyback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Treasury Department is considering buying  
back a portion of the $3.6 trillion national debt held by the 
public. What does that mean and what would it entail? 
</P>
<P>
	Basically, it means the government would have the option of  
buying back such things as Treasury bills, notes and bonds before 
they mature. No one would be forced to surrender their government 
securities. The process would be purely voluntary. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be done through a type of reverse auction in which the  
government would announce the type of securities it was interested 
in buying and accept the most competitive bids from holders of 
those securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Here, in question and answer form, is a look at the buyback  
program announced Wednesday by Treasury. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What is the significance of this for the government's  
long-term budget policies? 
</P>
<P>
	A: The Treasury Department's proposal sets the stage for  
completely eliminating debt held by the public by 2015, something 
that has happened only once before in the nation's history: in 1835 
when Andrew Jackson was president. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, interest on the public debt cost the government $364  
billion. Reducing the debt by buying back some securities would 
lower the government's interest payments. The savings could be used 
for other purposes, such as shoring up Social Security or Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said that even a tiny  
reduction in federal borrowing costs would save the government more 
than $1 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Reducing the debt also means less U.S. government reliance on  
overseas investors to finance American investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Why should the average consumer or business care about a  
buyback? 
</P>
<P>
	A: Reducing debt would lower interest rates and would lower  
borrowing costs to consumers and businesses. In theory, that should 
help reduce rates for home mortgages, car loans, credit cards and 
business loans. Businesses could invest the resulting savings in 
other ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: But what happens if the Federal Reserve becomes worried about  
the economy growing too quickly and starts to raise the short-term 
interest rates it controls? 
</P>
<P>
	A: That could happen. But the administration argues that no  
matter what the Fed does, the buyback plan for reducing the 
national debt will mean interest rates would be lower than they 
would be without the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Can any individual holder of government securities, such as  
Treasury bonds, sell them and get some quick cash? 
</P>
<P>
	A: Yes. But any individual holder of a government security can  
do that now by participating in what is known as the secondary 
market for Treasury securities, where billions of dollars in 
Treasury bills, notes and bonds change hands every day. Brokerage 
houses handle trades for small investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's buybacks will be handled by so-called primary  
dealers -- one of three dozen or so banks and investment houses that 
are authorized to buy and sell government securities. But the 
primary dealers will make their purchases from the secondary 
market, thus increasing the demand for securities being offered for 
sale by small investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What impact could this have on personal investment decisions?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Reduced debt tends to lower interest rates for bonds, which  
could make stocks seem like a more attractive return for investors. 
That would be similar to the forces that have helped in recent 
years to fuel the current long-running bull market in stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What is the likelihood that a buyback would happen soon?  
</P>
<P>
	A: It's hard to tell. The Treasury Department's proposal --  
laying out the rules that would guide buying back securities -- will 
soon be open to a 60-day comment period. At that time, members of 
the public and industry will have a chance to weigh in on the plan. 
The department, after digesting these comments, hopes to adopt a 
final set of rules by January. However, the department has not made 
a decision on when the buyback would occur after the rules are in 
place. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
