<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Will Vikings' AWOL Rookie Return? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood's agent said Thursday  
he still didn't know where the AWOL rookie was hiding out but held 
out hope that his troubled client would return to the Minnesota 
Vikings' training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Dennis Green, however, sounded as though the first-round  
pick might not be welcomed back. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once a guy walks out, I don't think you'll find another player  
on this team that can count on the guy regardless of what the 
situation was,'' Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a 6-foot-6, 276-pound defensive end from Michigan  
State and the 29th pick in the NFL draft, mysteriously vanished 
after his first pro practice Monday, walking out of his dorm and 
catching a cab out of town. 
</P>
<P>
	He apologetically called his Chicago-based agent, Craig Domann,  
24 hours later saying he'd needed to tend to a family crisis and 
was on his way back to camp to meet with Green, who would decide 
whether to take him back. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, who signed a five-year, $5.3 million contract on  
Sunday, hadn't returned by Thursday, and the team, which was able 
to freeze all but about $27,000 of the approximately $543,000 
after-taxes bonus wired to Underwood's bank account in Milwaukee, 
was contemplating its next move. 
</P>
<P>
	Domann faxed The Associated Press a statement on Thursday  
afternoon that said all attempts to locate Underwood had been 
fruitless. 
</P>
<P>
	``He deeply regretted not seeking permission from Coach Dennis  
Green and the Vikings before he left, but he felt the situation 
demanded immediate action,'' Underwood's statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I join everyone involved in this matter in emphasizing  
that the verification of Dimitrius' safety and well being is of 
utmost importance. Even though the specific reasons for his 
departure are not yet known, I can assure you that Dimitrius would 
never knowingly hurt his family, coaches and teammates by his 
unexcused absence. I remain hopeful that he is OK and I am 
confident that you will see Dimitrius in camp and ready to play 
soon,'' Domann added. 
</P>
<P>
	Domann said his client was eager to play for the Vikings, among  
the favorites for the Super Bowl this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dimitrius' dream is to play in the NFL. ... He has been  
looking forward to playing for Coach Green and he has been treated 
more than fairly by the entire Vikings organization,'' Domann said. 
``I ask that Coach Green and the Vikings continue to be patient and 
understanding with my client until such point when more facts 
become available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domann also added that ``all speculation that Dimitrius intended  
to simply take the Vikings money and not play football is totally 
inaccurate and erroneous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Domann negotiated a five-year, $5.3 million deal for Underwood  
on Sunday, including a partially deferred $1,725,000 signing bonus. 
Before taxes, Underwood got half the bonus, or $862,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Green said he still hadn't heard from Underwood on Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't worry about it once he left, to be honest with you,''  
Green said. ``I think other people kind of misinterpreted what our 
football team is about. I think everybody has been here long enough 
to understand that only a certain type of player can play on this 
football team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings were originally under the impression they had to  
make a decision on Underwood's status by Sunday. But the league 
says the team has many options. It could either cut its ties and 
recoup its money, leave him on the active-left squad list or place 
him on the reserve-left squad list. The Vikings also could keep him 
on their roster. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
