<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Advanced Air Bag Rules Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Department of Transportation says it will  
need six more months before issuing regulations on advanced air 
bags in new cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed rule, one of the most complex in the department's  
history, is intended to prevent deaths caused by air bags that 
inflate in low-speed crashes while saving hundreds more lives by 
improving the bag's performance in high-speed crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Issued last September, the proposed rule called for an array of  
new federal tests for air bags that included crash tests at 
different speeds and child and female dummies as well as the 
traditional male dummies. 
</P>
<P>
	The final regulation was due to be issued this September by the  
department's National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. But a 
transportation bill enacted last year allows the department an 
extra six months, until March 2000, if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater wrote Tuesday to Sen.  
John McCain, R-Ariz., author of the provision requiring the 
timetable, that he had ``determined that we must extend the date 
for issuing the final rule'' until March. The department released 
the letter Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater's letter also said the department would issue a  
``supplemental notice of proposed rulemaking,'' a document intended 
to either narrow the department's earlier broad proposal on air 
bags or clarify it. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers have criticized the proposal for being too ambitious,  
pushing the industry through a lot of new testing designed to get 
greater benefits from air bags while also trying to prevent deaths 
from the inflating devices. Automakers have argued the agency 
should concentrate first on eliminating deaths caused by air bags. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflating air bags have been blamed for 141 deaths since 1990 --  
mostly to child passengers or short female drivers in low-speed 
accidents they otherwise should have survived, according to NHTSA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
