<DOCNO> APW19990805.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Answers in BP Amoco Cancer Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAPERVILLE, Ill. (AP) -- Six workers at a BP Amoco research  
center probably got deadly brain cancer from their jobs, company 
officials said Thursday, citing a two-year study that dismissed any 
work connection to other ill employees and left many questions 
unanswered. 
</P>
<P>
	While the investigation will continue, officials acknowledged  
that the most intensive efforts to solve the decade-long medical 
mystery at the oil giant's suburban Chicago center have ended 
without identifying any specific cause for the malignant brain 
tumors. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we know today is that six of our colleagues have been  
affected with brain cancer and there's a pattern that appears to be 
work-related,'' said Jim Lowry, head of the company's health 
investigation task force. ``And we will continue to study; we will 
continue to look.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for former employees and surviving relatives who are  
suing the company said they hadn't yet received the report by 
investigators from the University of Alabama at Birmingham and 
Johns Hopkins University. But some expressed disappointment that 
the report didn't go further and suggested the company was dragging 
its feet because it is reluctant to admit responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they're concluding about the (brain cancer) cases is  
probably less strong than what my experts concluded a year ago,'' 
said attorney Marios Karayannis, whose father Nick was among the 
Amoco researchers killed by a malignant tumor. ``It becomes 
troubling that they took another year to come up with such a 
vanilla report.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten lawsuits have been filed against the company on behalf of 21  
people, some with malignant brain tumors, others with non-cancerous 
tumors in their heads and still others with different types of 
cancer. The lawsuits allege workers were exposed to numerous 
neurotoxins -- elements that poison the central nervous system -- 
because of inadequate ventilation and lax safety. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco has spent millions investigating and hiring experts to  
determine what, if anything, in the workplace caused the tumors. 
The research looked at more than 6,000 chemicals or agents used by 
researchers and made detailed comparisons of their work histories, 
but found no likely suspects for the cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the victims at the heart of the case had the same type of  
cancer, known as glioma, and were all longtime employees who 
``crossed paths'' at the center's chemical research complex in the 
mid-'70s and the early '80s. 
</P>
<P>
	``So there's a very strong pattern there,'' said Dr. Michael  
Wells, the company's chief epidemiologist. 
</P>
<P>
	Five of the men have died.  
</P>
<P>
	The research didn't find any work relation to employees with  
benign brain tumors, Wells said. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims' attorneys said they would press forward now with their  
lawsuits but held out the hope that the company might be ready to 
settle cases involving the glioma victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to go talk to those families and find out what  
they need,'' said Amoco spokeswoman Vicki J. Kastory. ``We are 
going to share their financial burden. What I don't know is what 
that means in terms of dollars and cents.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
