<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines, Pentagon Agree on Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Six major U.S. airlines and the Pentagon today  
signed an agreement under which the airlines will check the safety 
of foreign partners who help them fly American troops overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement, growing out of a 1985 charter crash in  
Newfoundland that killed 248 U.S. soldiers, should also help 
prevent commercial passengers from ending up on foreign carriers 
with substandard safety records. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. airlines plan to certify that they have processes for  
ensuring safety, that they have trained safety inspectors and that 
their flight crews get training through manuals that meet 
international flight safety standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from the airlines and the military announced the  
agreement during a news conference at the Air Transport 
Association, a trade group that represents the major U.S. airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a process that is really win-win,'' said Carol  
Hallett, president of the ATA. ``Win-Win for the government, for 
the employees of the U.S. government who travel on (foreign) 
partners, but for us as well to have the assurance that we can give 
to DoD (the Defense Department) of the quality of service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The safety of foreign carriers has become an issue for U.S.  
airlines because many of them now have partnerships with overseas 
airlines known as ``code-shares.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under such an arrangement, the carriers buy tickets on each  
other's planes and then sell them to passengers on connecting 
flights as if they were their own. Under those circumstances, a 
passenger with a United Airlines ticket, for example, may fly on a 
United plane to New York and then transfer for a flight to Europe 
with the airline's German partner, Lufthansa, even though the 
ticket still reads ``United'' and has a United flight number. 
</P>
<P>
	Both carriers have excellent safety records, and airlines favor  
such partnerships because it allows them to project the image of a 
larger route network. It also gives passengers the ability to make 
seamless connections between airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, however, Delta Air Lines halted it code-sharing  
arrangement with Korean Air after the Asian carrier suffered a 
cargo plane crash in China -- the latest in a series of fatal 
accidents or aircraft losses for Korean Air. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta had said previously that it would not team up with an  
airline it deemed unsafe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon has a travel budget of $1.2 billion per year, and  
has used its clout to push the airlines into taking visible steps 
to assure the safety of foreign partners who might carry U.S. 
troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The military has placed a renewed emphasis on troop safety since  
the 1985 crash, in which an Arrow Air DC-8 carrying soldiers from 
the 101st Airborne Division crashed on takeoff after a refueling 
stop in Gander, Newfoundland. The troops were returning to Fort 
Campbell, Ky., after a six-month peacekeeping mission in the Sinai 
Desert. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash was later blamed on wing icing, although some  
relatives suspect terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the Transportation Department, which must  
approve code-shares, is considering changing its policies so it can 
directly weigh the quality of the foreign airline partner. 
</P>
<P>
	Under existing rules, the department looks only at the safety  
standards of the country where the foreign carrier is based, not at 
the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's inspector general is also analyzing whether  
existing code-share policy adequately assesses foreign airline 
safety. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
