<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New England's Top Jockey Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The top jockey in New England underwent surgery  
Thursday after a career-threatening racing accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Rudy Baez, 49, did not move after falling from his horse shortly  
after the start of the second race Wednesday at Rockingham Park in 
Salem, N.H. He was taken to a hospital in Methuen, Mass., then 
airlifted to Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The result of Baez's surgery was not immediately known,  
according to Rockingham Park spokeswoman Lynne Snierson. Baez was 
listed in serious condition, Snierson said. His injuries are not 
believed to be life-threatening, the Boston Herald reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury occurred when Baez's horse, Gaitor Bait, clipped the  
heels of the horse in front of him as the field began to crowd 
shortly after coming out of the gate. The horse fell along the 
rail, sending Baez headlong onto the track. 
</P>
<P>
	No other riders or horses went down. Gaitor Bait was uninjured.  
</P>
<P>
	Track officials reviewed tapes of the race but there were no  
disqualifications. 
</P>
<P>
	Baez, a native of the Dominican Republic, lives in Wakefield  
with his wife and three children. He started riding when he was 13 
years old and has ridden in 28,000 races, winning more than 4,800. 
</P>
<P>
	He has won numerous jockey titles at both Rockingham and Suffolk  
Downs in Boston since the mid-1980s. Baez is ranked sixth in the 
nation based on the number of races won. On Sunday, he won the 
$100,000 Spicy Living Stakes in Rockingham, riding a horse named 
Lambana. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
