<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 04:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cross Burners Must Watch `Amistad' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDWARDSVILLE, Ill (AP) -- Four men who burned a cross in a black  
family's yard have been ordered to take racial sensitivity training 
that will include watching films like ``Schindler's List'' and 
``Amistad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Lawrence Keshner on Wednesday also ordered the men to  
participate in a special college program on cultural and social 
diversity and to write letters of apology to family they terrorized 
in June 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first reaction was to lock you up and throw the key away,''  
Keshner said during sentencing. But he said the men showed remorse 
and a willingness to be rehabilitated. ``It's time to heal,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The men -- Steven Horvath, 20, and Ryan Burns, 19, of  
Edwardsville; Darren Burgess, 30, of Glen Carbon; and Scott Davis, 
20, of St. Jacob -- have said they were drunk when they burned the 
cross on the front lawn of Keith Ellis' and Antonia Valentine's 
home. The couple and their two children have since moved away from 
the area in southwest Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of their sentence, the men must also pay $500 each into  
an educational trust fund for the couple's daughter, attend 
counseling and perform 100 hours of public service at an annual 
summer festival. 
</P>
<P>
	Keshner also sentenced each man to 2 1/2 years probation. They  
could face up to two years in prison if they fail to complete their 
tasks, the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	The four had been charged with, among other offenses, felony  
hate crimes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
