<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Says Patent Bill Harms Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Name-brand drug makers say it would help them  
invest in developing new medicines, but a consumer group says the 
poor, sick and elderly would be hurt by a bill that would extend 
patents on seven drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would delay generic drug manufacturers from  
making cheaper versions of the medications, Howard Metzenbaum, a 
former Democratic senator from Ohio who represents the Consumer 
Federation of America, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill is essentially a tax on the uninsured, the poor, the  
sick and the elderly,'' Metzenbaum told the Senate Judiciary 
Committee. ``I strongly urge you to reject it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But lawmakers of both parties are considering the bill, which  
would let the companies that make the anti-allergy drug Claritin 
and six other prescription drugs petition the U.S. Patent and 
Trademark Office for three years of additional patent protection. 
</P>
<P>
	It is sponsored in the House by Reps. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., and  
Jim McDermott, D-Wash., and in the Senate by Democratic Sen. Robert 
Torricelli of New Jersey, home to Schering-Plough Corp., which 
makes Claritin. 
</P>
<P>
	The opportunity to petition for three-year extensions goes  
beyond what was afforded under the Drug Price Competition and 
Patent Restoration Act of 1984. That law gave the companies making 
the seven drugs, which were in the pipeline at the time, only 
two-year patent extensions rather than the five years given other 
pharmaceuticals. 
</P>
<P>
	When a patent expires, generic drug makers can manufacture  
cheaper versions. Name-brand drug manufacturers say without 
reasonable patent protection, they don't have the revenues needed 
to invest in developing new drugs. Supporters of the legislation 
say Congress has a constitutional duty to foster the research and 
development of new medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	``A fair patent process will help consumers in the short term  
with affordable drugs and in the long term by supporting the 
research that produces new medicines,'' Torricelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue has become an expensive legislative fight in Congress  
involving some of Capitol Hill's top lobbyists. 
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough has brought in some big names to push  
legislation that could extend the patent on its drug by three 
years. The patent is set to expire in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without fair patent protection, we simply could not generate  
the necessary capital that allows us to make these risky and large 
investments,'' Richard Jay Kogan, chairman and CEO of 
Schering-Plough, told the committee. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
