<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Spreading in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Smoke from hundreds of dry-season  
fires burning in Indonesia was choking regional shipping traffic 
Thursday and has spread far enough to blanket Malaysia's capital in 
a mild haze. 
</P>
<P>
	In Indonesia's worst-hit Riau Province, visibility in the air  
ranged between 500 and 800 yards. Ground visibility was only 100 to 
200 yards, weather officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Flights to Riau's capital were diverted and residents in many  
areas were advised to stay indoors as much as possible and wear 
masks outdoors. Meanwhile, the haze was slowing shipping traffic 
through the busy Malacca Straits, which separates Singapore and 
Malaysia from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	For four months in 1997, severe smog caused by similar forest  
fires in Indonesia enveloped Southeast Asia, closing down airports 
and schools and leading thousands of people to seek treatment for 
respiratory disorders. 
</P>
<P>
	The haze badly hurt Malaysia's tourism industry that year. To  
avoid scaring away tourists this time, Malaysia will not release 
air pollution levels as it did in 1997 and 1998, a newspaper 
reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing alarming,'' Environment Minister Law Hieng  
Ding said in the Star newspaper. Publicizing the pollution index 
could drive away tourists, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the haze was spreading but the pollution index remained  
below 100. A reading above 100 is considered dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	A leading Indonesian environmental group is blaming timber  
industries for starting the new rash of fires. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have continued to conduct land clearing with burning  
method because it is cheap and fast,'' said Longgena Ginting, 
forestry program coordinator for the environmental group Walhi. 
</P>
<P>
	Walhi said at least 441 separate fires were burning on the  
Indonesian islands of Sumatra and Borneo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
