<DOCNO> APW19990805.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Defends Finance Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno today denied that  
the Justice Department has kept open campaign finance 
investigations involving Democrats to block Republicans in Congress 
from conducting their own. 
</P>
<P>
	A House committee investigating alleged fund-raising abuses in  
the 1996 presidential election is barred from questioning anyone 
who is a target of an active Justice Department investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said today it is ``certainly not true'' that the department  
has marked some probes as ``ongoing'' to thwart the committee's 
work, as was suggested this week in an article by Chicago Sun-Times 
columnist Robert Novak. 
</P>
<P>
	Novak cited an internal Justice Department memo dated June 4  
that said a number of long-dormant investigations involving 
Democratic fund-raisers and donors are marked ``ongoing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of any basis for concluding that'' the  
investigations are kept open to prevent other inquiries, Reno said. 
</P>
<P>
	She would not comment on why the investigations are still open  
and said the memo cited by Novak ``should not have gotten out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Government Reform  
Committee investigating campaign fund raising, has complained 
bitterly that Reno's Justice Department has frustrated his 
investigation in order to protect President Clinton and Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno was asked whether she planned to comply with a subpoena  
from Burton to turn over a large volume of Justice Department 
documents involving the fund-raising investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she would try to work with the committee, but noted  
potential conflicts in turning over documents. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are matters relating to pending investigations and  
pending prosecutions in which if we provide information and if it's 
made public can have a dramatic impact on the pending 
investigation,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno also said prosecutions are a function of the executive  
branch, and ``for Congress to be involved in the management of an 
investigation or a prosecution produces questions about is it being 
handled the right way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Powlus Rejoins Lions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIVERSITY CENTER, Mich. (AP) -- Ron Powlus will get another shot  
at becoming a Detroit Lions quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Notre Dame signal caller, released Wednesday when the  
Lions signed Donald Hollas, was called back to training camp 
Thursday night after Hollas, the former Oakland quarterback, left 
without speaking with coach Bobby Ross. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got to see him. He just said he's lost his desire,''  
Ross said Thursday of Hollas. ``He was in a meeting up until about 
11 o'clock (Thursday morning). At 11:05, he was calling our 
administration and telling them he just didn't have the heart for 
it anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Better to know now than when we line up.''  
</P>
<P>
	Ross said he had nothing against Powlus. He said his reason for  
cutting Powlus was that he had wanted the opportunity to look at 
another quarterback, and didn't want to keep five in camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ron's back with us, and he's in the hunt, in the  
competition,'' Ross said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, injuries continued to plague the Lions. Defensive  
tackle Henry Taylor had to be carted off the field Thursday after 
someone fell on his leg during a drill. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury was the Lions' third in two days. On Wednesday, wide  
receiver Herman Moore suffered a hip/groin strain and center Eric 
Beverly hurt his ankle. Both players were redshirted for Thursday's 
workout. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the three injuries are serious, and both Beverly and  
Taylor should be back in a couple of days, Ross said. Moore was 
kept out of Thursday's practice strictly as a precaution and could 
resume working out at any time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lions spent the early portion of practice Thursday working  
on their goal-line offense and defense, a drill cut short by 
Taylor's injury. Ross said he scheduled some goal-line scrimmaging 
Saturday, an area where the team could use improvement on both 
sides of the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to get better at that,'' Ross said. ``It's not going  
to be anything fancy. We're just going to line up and go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Thursday's goal-line drills, the Lions did some 11-on-11  
scrimmaging at midfield. Ross said he was pleased with the passing 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought our quarterbacks threw very well, particularly (Gus)  
Frerotte and Charlie (Batch),'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive tackle Aaron Gibson, one of Detroit's two first-round  
draft picks, will fly Monday to Birmingham, Ala., to get another 
opinion on his sore left shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback Kevin Abrams will continue to rehabilitate his ailing  
foot with a bone stimulator for about two more weeks, and defensive 
tackle Luther Elliss, who had surgery for an eye injury two weeks 
ago, is expected back in three weeks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 11:50:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PJs, Canterbury Win Animations Emmys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Fox Television series ``The PJ's,''  
created by Eddie Murphy, and HBO's ``Animated Epics: The Canterbury 
Tales'' won animation Emmys. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashley Potter and Les Mills won individual achievement awards as  
animators for the Animated Epics segment ``Leaving London.'' Joanna 
Quinn won for outstanding animator and production for the same 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	Ja'Net DuBois was honored in the voice-over performance category  
for her role as Mrs. Avery on ``The PJs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The awards were announced Wednesday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
