<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 11:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> London Stock Prices Fall Sharply / British Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Share prices fell sharply on the London Stock  
Exchange on Thursday as interest rate concerns on both sides of the 
Atlantic sparked a rush of selling in telecommunications, financial 
and pharmaceutical stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Times Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 133.8  
points, or 2.1 percent, to 6,101.6. Provisional volume was a shade 
over 1 billion shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The three big sectors in London displayed concern in thin and  
volatile conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are all highly rated stocks which have made a major  
contribution to the market's gains over the course of the year,'' 
James Dewhurst, senior salesman at CCF Charterhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	With the market's focus firmly on monetary policy, a British  
policy announcement that interest rates would remain at 5.00 
percent, offered a late morning diversion. Economists said a ``wait 
and see policy'' after four cuts this year seemed appropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. interest rates were a more pressing concern, with many  
commentators looking for a hike at the Federal Reserve's next 
policy meeting on Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Dewhurst said Thursday's drop in U.S. second-quarter  
productivity made people nervous, but a strong non-farm payrolls 
report Friday has the potential to cause a big scare. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
