<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- It was the 1970s, and the Rev. Robert Nugent  
wrote a note of commendation to a nun whose work with gay and 
lesbian Catholics he had read about. He ended with what he 
considered a throwaway pleasantry, to ``contact me if there was 
anything I could do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nugent says now, ``I've never said that again, because my life  
was changed radically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Jeannine Gramick did contact him, and it was the  
beginning of a joint ministry that continued for more than two 
decades, ending last month when the Vatican summoned the two to 
Rome and ordered an end to their work. 
</P>
<P>
	Vatican officials, reflecting traditional Judeo-Christian  
teaching that homosexual behavior is sinful, said Gramick and 
Nugent have ``caused confusion among the Catholic people and have 
harmed the community of the church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nugent, who at first issued a statement saying he accepted the  
decision with a heavy heart, later disputed the charge in an 
interview with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've tried to bring the experience of gays and lesbians to  
the rest of the church. We've been trying to build a positive 
understanding of homosexual orientation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramick took a month's leave from her church commitments to  
decide whether she will obey the Vatican. ``I am anguished and 
deeply troubled,'' she said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	While she said she is committed to Catholicism's ``core  
beliefs,'' she urged the church to stop focusing its attention on 
homosexual practice and instead to emphasize gay individuals' human 
dignity and Christ's urgings ``to liberate the oppressed and 
marginalized ... .'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was the idea behind New Ways Ministry, which Gramick and  
Nugent founded in Mount Rainier, Md., in 1977, six years after they 
met. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days after Nugent sent his ``contact me'' note, Gramick had  
called and asked him to come to a meeting of her Philadelphia 
group, telling him the men wanted to meet with a priest. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I found was people who loved the church very much. It was  
their family, their home. But they felt like the church didn't want 
them. There was a great love-hate relationship,'' Nugent recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	As the ministry developed, Nugent and Gramick traveled the  
country giving seminars. They wrote books and pamphlets on 
homosexuality and the church. 
</P>
<P>
	And their work attracted scrutiny from the church hierarchy.  
</P>
<P>
	There were several discussions in the early 1980s with Cardinal  
James A. Hickey, archbishop of Washington, D.C., the diocese where 
the independent New Ways Ministry is based. In 1988, Nugent and 
Gramick were told their case was being investigated by a 
commission, which in 1994 forwarded its recommendations to the 
Vatican's Congregation for the Doctrine of Faith. The panel sent 
several inquiries to Nugent and Gramick, probing their beliefs on 
homosexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	``They moved away from our teachings, our writings and our  
ministry and moved into an area of personal assent. They were 
trying to see if I internally accepted the teaching of the 
church,'' Nugent said. 
</P>
<P>
	In her statement, Gramick agreed: ``To intrude, uninvited, into  
the sanctuary of another's conscience is both disrespectful and 
wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hickey said earlier this month that the Vatican's decision was  
not made lightly and both Nugent and Gramick were ``given numerous 
opportunities over the past 20 years to clarify their beliefs and 
to assent to the church's full teaching on homosexuality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Gramick, Nugent said he doesn't dissent from the core  
teachings on homosexuality, but he does disagree with the church's 
language. 
</P>
<P>
	``I spent 25 years telling homosexuals that the church cares for  
you, that it wants you to have a part in it,'' Nugent said. ``How 
can I talk to them and convince them of that if I use language like 
`evil,' `depravity' and `disorder'?'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the New Ways Ministry, Nugent and Gramick focused on gays  
and lesbians as Catholics first, and homosexuals second. 
</P>
<P>
	For Nugent, the decision to obey the Vatican order was  
excruciating. But the stakes were too high. Disobedience would lead 
to dismissal from the Catholic community. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been a priest for almost 35 years, I've been happy as a  
priest and I don't think I could give that up, it's such a part of 
me. It's who I am,'' said Nugent, who is known as ``Father Bob'' to 
his parishioners at St. John the Baptist Church in New Freedom, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Nugent still thinks the time he and Gramick spent ministering to  
homosexuals was worthwhile. 
</P>
<P>
	``Homosexuals now have more of a sense of empowerment than they  
did in the 1970s,'' he said. ``The are willing to speak out, to 
say, 'I'm gay and I'm Catholic and I want to be both. I want to be 
gay in a healthy and mature way, and I want to be Catholic in a 
faithful way.''' 
</P>
<P>
	As Gramick weighs her decision, her statement expressed concern  
that the Vatican's order will anger gay and lesbian Catholics and 
their families. 
</P>
<P>
	``To them, I say: Use your anger creatively,'' she said. ``Don't  
leave the church. It is your spiritual home. The people of God ... 
are coming to see that the whole community is diminished when we 
exclude lesbian and gay persons from the table of the Eucharist and 
dialogue.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
