<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Immigration Ad Starts Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the nation's most ethnically diverse county,  
immigrants are getting a hard lesson in democracy: a sign saying 
America doesn't want them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over 80 percent of Americans support very little or no new  
immigration. Is anyone listening to us?'' proclaims the billboard 
in Sunnyside, a Queens neighborhood sprinkled with other signs in 
Greek, Korean and Hindi. 
</P>
<P>
	``We vehemently object to the message it sends to residents in a  
borough that is home to immigrants from more than 100 countries 
around the world,'' Queens Borough President Claire Shulman said 
Wednesday at a rally organized to protest the sign. 
</P>
<P>
	The billboard is the work of Craig Nelson, a Sunnyside resident  
who runs an anti-immigration campaign he calls ProjectUSA. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson, who once taught English in China, insists he's not  
saying that individual immigrants are bad: ``We're 
anti-immigration; we are not anti-immigrants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sign is just a block from the No. 7 train that is known for  
carrying immigrants to work in Manhattan. Last month, the White 
House chose the subway line as a ``National Millennium Trail'' -- a 
monument to its polyglot pastiche of riders helping build a new 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone getting off the No. 7 train is still greeted by a Chamber  
of Commerce sign that says: ``Sunnyside welcomes you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
