<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Tax Cut Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defying repeated veto threats from President  
Clinton, the House today passed a Republican 10-year, $792 billion 
tax cut offering a multitude of tax breaks for average taxpayers 
and special interests. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 221-206 to send the bill to the Senate, where  
expected final passage was scheduled for this evening. In the 
House, five Democrats joined most Republicans in support, while the 
GOP lost only four of its votes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a good deal for the American people,'' Speaker Dennis  
Hastert, R-Ill., said at a Capitol Hill rally. ``It's fair, 
responsible and balanced tax-relief bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would trim all income tax rates by 1 percentage point:  
first, the bottom 15 percent rate would drop to 14 percent by 2003; 
the other four would be reduced in 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	The estate tax would be repealed gradually beginning in 2003,  
ending it completely in 2009. Relief from the ``marriage penalty'' 
that hits many two-income couples would phase in beginning in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, addressing a Democratic rally at the Capitol before the  
vote, responded: ``We say first things first,'' urging any budget 
surplus go first for preserving Social Security and Medicare and 
reducing government debt. ``Figure out what it costs and give the 
rest back to the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., accused Republicans of bending to  
business lobbyists and producing a tax bill intended mainly for 
political consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got your Christmas list and you know it will never,  
never, never become law,'' Rangel said. 
</P>
<P>
	In West Des Moines, Iowa, Texas Gov. George W. Bush urged  
Clinton to sign the bill. ``In my judgment, we ought to pass back 
the money to the people who pay the taxes,'' said Bush, 
front-runner for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, GOP leaders gained key support from a handful of  
Republican Senate moderates by inserting new items aimed at 
low-income workers, affordable housing and people paying for 
dependent care, officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Senate vote was expected to be close, Republicans  
were confident they could pass the bill. GOP Sen. Mike Crapo of 
Idaho was absent for his daughter's wedding, but Sen. Arlen 
Specter, R-Pa., said he might not vote, which would reduce to 50 
the number needed for passage. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders will not send the bill -- negotiated from earlier  
House and Senate tax plans -- to the White House until September, 
hoping to build public support during the August recess and avoid 
an immediate veto. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. President, listen,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,  
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. ``Listen to the 
American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton and most Democrats don't believe people are  
clamoring for tax cuts and prefer that projected budget surpluses 
be used to first safeguard Social Security and Medicare, pay down 
public debt and ensure adequate levels of government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Clinton has said he would sign a modest tax cut of  
perhaps $300 billion, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said in an 
interview that he saw no signs of compromise with the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any indication that he's serious at all,'' said  
Lott, R-Miss. ``I'm hopeful, because I want it very badly. But the 
president has shown no inclination to engage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But in a signal that the GOP doesn't expect the bill to ever  
become law, many of the major provisions would expire after 2008. 
That means current law would return unless the cuts were renewed by 
a future Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Republicans said the projected $2.9 trillion surplus over  
the next decade was enough to meet Clinton's priorities and still 
enact the largest tax cut since 1981, mainly by delaying full 
impact of the breaks until well into the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the tax cut for 2000 would total only $5.2 billion and  
only $156.2 billion over its first five years, said Lindy Paull, 
staff director for the Joint Committee on Taxation, which makes 
official tax estimates for Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the partisan gridlock, Republicans made sure their tax  
bill was chock full of items that would please many GOP 
constituencies, ranging from pro-family conservative groups to 
international and domestic business. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide tax breaks for education, long-term  
health care and health insurance premiums, repeal the alternative 
minimum tax for individuals and cut top capital gains tax rates for 
most taxpayers from 20 percent to 18 percent retroactive to Jan. 1, 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	It also contained some special targets: repeal of a 10 percent  
excise tax on certain kinds of fishing tackle boxes; an increase in 
tax breaks for reforestation expenses incurred by timber companies; 
breaks for purchasers of nuclear plants aimed at the costs of 
cleaning up reactor sites; and a credit for electricity produced 
from poultry waste. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would extend the research and development tax  
credit sought by high-tech businesses by five years, instead of the 
permanent extension they want. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
