<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caddies Could Be in Shorts for PGA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Caddies will be allowed to wear shorts next  
week in the PGA Championship if the heat index is over 100 degrees, 
the first time the PGA of America has allowed shorts in its premier 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	The PGA of America generally follows the decorum set out by the  
PGA Tour. Spokesman Julius Mason said Thursday it is following the 
same guidelines the tour is using during a three-week test that 
concludes this week in the Buick Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years ago, the caddies for U.S. Open champion Steve Jones  
and British Open champion Tom Lehman wore shorts at Valhalla Golf 
Club during the PGA Championship. The PGA of America ordered them 
to change pants on the second tee in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	The USGA began allowing caddies to wear shorts in the U.S. Open  
a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Professional Caddies Association has commissioned  
a study by an Orlando, Fla., doctor on the effects of carrying a 
60-pound golf bag in 100-degree temperatures. That report is 
expected to be released later this month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
