<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 14:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Tax Cut Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Details of the 10-year, $792 billion Republican tax cut package.  

</P>
<P>
                            *INCOME TAX   	
</P>
<P>
	--A reduction of 1 percentage point in all marginal income tax  
rates between 2001 and 2005. The bottom 15 percent rate would fall 
to 14.5 percent in 2001 and 14 percent in 2003, followed by a 1 
percentage point reduction in all other rates in 2005. Cost: $283 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--To ease the ``marriage penalty'' paid by millions of two-income  
couples, the standard deduction would be gradually doubled over a 
five-year period, beginning in 2001, for those who do not itemize. 
Also, the income subject to the bottom tax bracket would rise for 
couples who file jointly in 2005. Cost: $119 billion. 

</P>
<P>
                           *CAPITAL GAINS   	
</P>
<P>
	--Reduce individual capital gains rates for most investments held  
at least one year from 20 percent to 18 percent, or from 10 percent 
to 8 percent for people paying the bottom income tax rate, 
effective retroactive to Jan. 1, 1999. Cost: $32 billion. 

</P>
<P>
                            *ESTATE TAX   	
</P>
<P>
	--Phase out and eventually repeal the taxes on inheritance and  
gifts beginning in 2003, with full repeal in 2009. Cost: $65 
billion. 

</P>
<P>
                      *EDUCATION and HEALTH CARE    	
</P>
<P>
	--Allow health insurance premiums to be fully deductible  
beginning in 2002 for those who pay more than 50 percent of those 
premiums. In 2000, create a new personal exemption (worth $2,750 in 
1999) for people who care for an elderly relative at home. Cost: 
$42.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase tax-exempt contribution limits to IRA-like education  
savings accounts from $500 to $2,000 and include elementary and 
secondary expenses. Interest on prepaid tuition accounts for public 
and private schools would be tax free. Cost: $15 billion. 

</P>
<P>
                            *RETIREMENT   	
</P>
<P>
	--Increase contribution limit to all individual retirement  
accounts from $2,000 to $5,000 a year, from 2001 to 2006. In 2002, 
raise the annual income limit from $150,000 to $200,000 for married 
couples to contribute to a Roth IRA and to convert a traditional 
IRA into a Roth IRA. Cost: $15 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow an unspecified deduction for the cost of prescription  
drug insurance for Medicare recipients, contingent upon passage of 
separate Medicare reform bill. No cost estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase contribution limits on 401(k) accounts from $10,000 to  
$15,000 and accelerate time for 100 percent vesting in 
employer-matched pension plans from 5 years to 3 years. Cost: $15 
billion. 

</P>
<P>
                            *URBAN ILLS   	
</P>
<P>
	--Create 20 ``renewal communities,'' including four in rural  
areas, where a variety of tax breaks would apply for businesses 
that create jobs, clean up former industrial sites and take other 
actions. Cost: up to $2 billion. 

</P>
<P>
                            *CORPORATE   	
</P>
<P>
	--Extend research and development tax credit for five years.  
Cost: $13.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Extend work opportunity and welfare-to-work tax credits for 2.5  
years. Cost: $1.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Extend wind and biomass electric credit and create new poultry  
waste credit, both for four years. Cost: $534 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow tax break for transfer of money set aside by nuclear  
plants for cleanups and other costs. Cost: $1.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Increase reforestation tax break for timber industry. Cost:  
$277 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--Repeal 10 percent excise tax on certain fishing tackle boxes.  
Cost: $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--Repeal 50 percent limit on corporation tax benefits for  
overseas sales of military equipment. Cost: $1.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Make a variety of international tax law changes, including  
elimination of 35 percent foreign tax credit limit for gas and oil 
extracted overseas. Cost: $1.6 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
