<DOCNO> APW19990805.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 06:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China's Retail Prices Fall Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's retail price index dropped in July for  
the 22nd straight month, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was evidence that the economy remains in the  
doldrums, enfeebled by weak consumer demand, excess industrial 
capacity and declining foreign investment and exports. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which cited the State Information Center, did not  
provide a specific figure, but said retail prices have fallen every 
month since October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The retail price index, the country's benchmark inflation  
indicator, fell 3.2 percent in the first half of the year compared 
with the same period in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The brief Xinhua report said prices remained in decline for more  
than 80 percent of all major commodities. It cited unnamed analysts 
as saying the price decline will continue in the second half of 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Information Center is a Beijing-based think-tank for  
China's State Development Planning Commission, a cabinet-level 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has sought to counter deflation by imposing  
controls on prices and embarking on a deficit-financed public works 
spending program, but economic growth has still faltered. 
</P>
<P>
	Four interest-rate cuts in 17 months have had a limited effect.  
Thanks to record unemployment caused by free-market reforms, 
consumers seem too worried about their jobs to spend some of the 
$700 billion they've stashed away in bank accounts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 07:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alarm raised over car industry, NATION </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	August 05, 1999  
</P>
<P>
	NATION   	
</P>
<P>
	THAILAND   	
</P>
<P>
	ENGLISH   	

</P>
<P>
	ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 209 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor  
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 COPYRIGHT 1999 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A 
JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE 
MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT 
ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC. 
</P>
<P>
		   THAILAND's automotive industry is likely to turn itself into a  
mere assembly centre if the government continues with its plan to 
revamp automotive taxes and lift local-content regulations, warned 
local auto-parts and modified pickup truck company Thai Rung Union 
Cars Plc. 
</P>
<P>
		   Thai Rung managing director Sompong Pa-ernchoke said the local  
automotive industry would follow the path of the electronics 
industry in offering low added value to the local economy, because 
the multinational companies that dominate the industry will import 
most of the parts and components they need for local production. 
</P>
<P>
		   According to Sompong, the government has a duty to make sure  
that its automotive tariffs policy will benefit the country, not 
foreign auto-makers. 
</P>
<P>
		   ''As more manufacturers turn to imported parts, especially  
semi-knocked-down kits, Thailand will become just an assembly 
keNpre where they just tighten the nuts ab Ybint the bodies. 
</P>
<P>
		   ''Local parts sourcing would only consist of products such as  
tyres and batteries$'$claimed Sompong. 
</P>
<P>
		   The Cabinet has approved the lifting of three decades-old  
local-content regulations from Jan 1, 2000, to abide by an earlier 
promise made several years ago to attract General Motors (GM) into 
establishing its auto plant in the country. 
</P>
<P>
		   The government has also announced a new auto-tariff structure to  
comply with the removal of the local content rule. 
</P>
<P>
		   Also, following lobbying by Ford and other foreign auto-makers,  
a senior Finance Ministry official was quoted as saying that the 
ministry would on Aug 15 introduce a new tax regulation on modified 
motor vehicles, to replace the current regime which discriminates 
against foreign producers. 
</P>
<P>
		   Despite decades of protection from the government, the Thai  
parts industry is still lagging behind foreign competitors in terms 
of quality and price. Sompong said that currently the parts 
industry had just completed the ''high school'' level, and needed 
to be nurtured further before being able to compete 
internationally. 
</P>
<P>
		   Citing Malaysia, which insists on having a local content  
regulation, the Thai Rung managing director said Thailand should 
not to follow GM's order to abandon the local content rule, since 
this would ''kill'' the local parts industry -- which employs 
24,000 workers and is worth more than Bt10 billion. 
</P>
<P>
		   After a two-year delay, GM said it would commence the commercial  
operation of its plant in Rayong around the middle of 2000, but at 
only half of its previously-announced production size. 
</P>
<P>
		   According to Thai Rung, the new automotive tariffs -- set to  
begin from next Jan 1, at the same time as the lifting of the local 
content rule -- will result in a lower gap of import duty rates 
between completely knocked-down (CKD) kits and completely built-up 
(CBU) units. 
</P>
<P>
		   The CBU-CKD gap for pickup trucks will be narrowed to 41.15 per  
cent from 50.93 per cent, for multi-purpose vehicles to 88.22 per 
cent from 105.48 per cent, blind vans to 39.99 per cent from 48.46 
per cent, glass vans to 17.99 per cent from 26.46 per cent, 
passenger cars to 124.62 per cent from 149.24 per cent, and trucks 
(with cabs) to 17.99 per cent from 26.46 per cent. (See table.) 
Thai Rung, modifier of pickup trucks for Tri Petch Isuzu Sales Plc, 
has been hit hard by the entry of the Toyota Sport Rider, modified 
by rival Thai Auto Works Co from Toyota's pickup trucks, which has 
been selling like hot-cakes since its introduction last year. 
</P>
<P>
		   Due to the economic crisis, the market for modified pickup  
trucks has plunged from about 10,000 units in 1996 to just 4,000 
units in 1998. But Thai Auto Works, minority-owned by Toyota, has 
already sold more than 5,000 Sport Riders. 
</P>
<P>
		   Sompong called on the government to lower taxes on modified  
vehicles, as well as restricting the right to manufacture this type 
of vehicle only to Thai-owned companies. 
</P>
<P>
		   ''If the government wants to open up the market, they must look  
at the consequences, too. Looking at the way it's going, Thailand 
will be losing the auto industry to foreign companies in no time,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
		   Ford said it did not make sense for the company to hire local  
companies to modify its pickup trucks, since it has its own factory 
which is already producing modified trucks for export. 
</P>
<P>
		   Sompong said that this was not the first time that the pickup  
modifiers have faced a problem. In the past, many manufacturers 
used loopholes to enjoy lower taxes, he said. They include the 
Mercedes-Benz 300 TD station wagon -- which enjoyed a public 
transportation tax-break by claiming it had seating capacity for 
over seven people -- the Suzuki Caribean, Daihatsu Mira, Mitsubishi 
Pajero and Isuzu Cameo. 
</P>
<P>
	Copyright 1999 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by  
WorldSources, Inc. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
