<DOCNO> APW19990805.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell early Friday as investors  
continued to worry about the Japanese currency's recent strength 
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average declined 76.33  
points, or 0.44 percent, to 17,281.86 in the first one hour of 
trading. On Thursday, the average slid 327.19 points, or 1.85 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.64 yen, up 0.02 yen from late Thursday in  
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 114.30 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said market players are concerned that the strong yen  
will hurt Japan's fledging economic recovery and force 
export-oriented Japanese companies to revise down their earnings 
forecasts for the current fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen hurts Japan's exporters as it makes their  
products more expensive abroad and reduces the value of repatriated 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's quite a bit of anxiety in Japan,'' said Robert Sasaki,  
head of the quantitative strategy group at Jardine Fleming 
Securities. ``It's pretty tough for Japanese exporters to make 
money, and Japan is an exporting country,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials have recently indicated that they would be  
satisfied with the dollar at around 120 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 3.74 points, or 0.26 percent, to 1,427.28. 
The TOPIX closed down 28.65 points, or 1.96 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.24 yen, down  
from 123.40 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.8400 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8250 percent, driving 
its price down to 99.65 yen from 99.78 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
