<HEADLINE> Aaron Amazed As McGwire Hits HR 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Hank Aaron saw Mark McGwire's 500th home run  
on the video scoreboard at Three Rivers Stadium. And baseball's 
career homer leader thinks he one day might watch Big Mac break his 
own record. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way he's hitting home runs, he could break the record next  
year,'' Aaron, who hit 755, said Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's hitting them in bunches. Seventy home runs? He might hit  
80 some year. Whew! That's a lot of home runs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron threw out the first pitch before the Atlanta-Pittsburgh  
game. He was honored for breaking Babe Ruth's career mark 25 years 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire hit No. 500 in St. Louis, and the highlight was shown on  
the scoreboard in Pittsburgh. Later, McGwire connected for No. 501. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire and the Cardinals begin a four-game series Friday in  
Pittsburgh and many fans had hoped to see him hit his 500th. The 
Pirates have a big advance sale for both Friday's doubleheader and 
Saturday night's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron, meanwhile, marveled at McGwire's power.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was sitting on the side at the home run derby (at the  
All-Star game), and it's impossible to hit the ball that far and 
that distance. He was hitting the ball into the light towers. 
You've just never seen anybody hit the ball the way he does,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, 35, reached 500 homers in fewer at-bats than anyone in  
history. Shortly after the Cardinals' 10-3 loss to San Diego, he 
was asked about breaking Aaron's record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I mean, there's a chance,'' McGwire said. ``But it's a long  
way away.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
