<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workplace Deaths Decline in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fewer Americans were killed in workplace  
injuries last year than any time since the Labor Department started 
keeping track in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Job-related deaths fell to 6,026 in 1998 -- about 17 fatal  
injuries each day -- down from 6,238 in 1997, according to 
statistics released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer workplace homicides -- the second leading cause of  
on-the-job deaths -- accounted for much of the overall decline. In 
1998, 709 people were murdered at work, compared with 860 in 1997. 
Overall homicide rates also declined nationally last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Most workplace homicides were related to robberies and occurred  
at grocery stores, bars and restaurants and gas stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Highway crashes continued to be the leading cause of on-the-job  
deaths and the number of those fatalities rose slightly in 1998, to 
1,431. About two-fifths of the victims were truck drivers. An 
additional 413 workers were fatally struck by vehicles last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Deaths from falls and electrocutions also increased in 1998, but  
the number of deaths from workers being struck by falling objects 
or getting caught in running machinery declined. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
