<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Sees HMO Compromise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats and breakaway Republicans  
announced agreement Thursday on legislation that strengthens the 
rights of patients dealing with managed care plans and lowers their 
barriers to medical care. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton praised the measure for providing ``meaningful  
patient protections to all Americans in all health plans, and it 
holds plans accountable when their actions cause harm to 
patients.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill includes a variety of provisions to ease access for the  
insured to medical care in emergency rooms, from specialists in 
clinical trials and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would establish an outside review process for patients  
who believe they unfairly were denied care. Companies obeying an 
independent panel's ruling still could be sued in state courts, but 
would not be liable for punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The point man for Democrats during the negotiations, Rep. John  
Dingell of Michigan, said the legislation ``covers everyone. You 
can appeal if you are denied treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Added GOP Rep. Charles Norwood of Georgia, who has shuttled  
between Republicans and Democrats in recent weeks: ``We need a law 
that will protect patients, not a bill that will protect 
politicians at the November ballot box.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norwood, a dentist, is one of several Republicans who are health  
professionals and have been at odds with their party's leadership 
on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Dingell and Norwood announced their agreement at a hastily  
announced news conference where they were joined by numerous 
lawmakers from both parties. They said the formal legislation would 
be introduced later Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	As news of the deal spread, lobbyists for insurance companies  
and businesses mobilized against the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	``This legislation is built on the erroneous premise that trial  
lawyers are the sole guardians of medical care,'' said Karen 
Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health Plans, an 
HMO trade group. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hold a narrow majority in the House, and the GOP  
leadership had been hoping to keep the issue off the floor until 
they had worked the differences among their rank-and-file. 
</P>
<P>
	The bipartisan agreement is a setback for that strategy, and the  
leadership will come under increased pressure to allow the 
politically popular issue to the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican-controlled Senate passed HMO legislation earlier  
this year that is significantly more restrictive than Democrats and 
the White House favors. It covers only some of the nation's 
insured, for example, and does not permit HMOs to be sued for 
denying care. 
</P>
<P>
	Dingell, Norwood and others stressed that their measure would  
cover all those who have insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure is designed to guarantee emergency room care  
coverage, without prior authorization by the insurance company, in 
any situation where a reasonable person would believe their health 
was in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a fact sheet distributed by Democrats, the deal  
also would: 
</P>
<P>
	--Guarantee access to specialists.  
</P>
<P>
	--Permit patients to get referrals to doctors outside their  
networks if no in-network provider were available. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ease access to clinical trials for certain patients, according  
to a fact sheet distributed by Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	--Give women direct access to obstetricians and gynecologists.  
</P>
<P>
	--Allow children to have a pediatrician as their primary care  
provider. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement followed a hectic few days of behind the scenes  
negotiating. Norwood met at length in reent weeks with Republicans 
in the search for a GOP compromise measure, and in recent days has 
been talking with Dingell. Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, a surgeon, met 
with House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt in recent days to 
discuss the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, according to congressional officials who spoke  
on condition of anonymity, Republicans made a late, unsuccessful 
effort to court conservative Democrats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
