<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 17:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Sides With Pepsi in Jet Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge weighing the merits of a lawsuit  
by a national park ranger has agreed with Pepsi that the company 
was only joking when it implied in a commercial that it was giving 
away fighter jets. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Kimba M. Wood found that ``no objective  
person could reasonably have concluded that the commercial actually 
offered consumers a Harrier jet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But John D.R. Leonard, a 24-year-old Seattle man working as a  
summer park ranger at Mount Ranier National Park, saw the 
commercial and concluded it was no laughing matter when Pepsi 
implied that 7 million points in its ``Pepsi Stuff'' merchandise 
campaign could be redeemed for one Harrier jet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't take it as a joke. I thought it was a great prize,''  
he said Thursday in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard said he had planned to start a business with the fighter  
jet, perhaps letting it be used for short fantasy flights for the 
public or in movie productions. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the company allowed customers to purchase points for 10  
cents each, Leonard raised $700,000 amongst wealthy acquaintances 
intrigued by a business plan he drew up and ordered himself a jet 
three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepsi wrote back: ``The Harrier jet in the Pepsi commercial is  
fanciful and is simply included to create a humorous and 
entertaining ad. We apologize for any misunderstanding or confusion 
that you may have experienced and are enclosing some free coupons 
for your use.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The issue landed in federal court in Manhattan after Leonard  
sued Pepsi. Pepsi responded by asking the court for a declaratory 
judgment saying it did not have to give Leonard a Harrier Jet, a 
McDonnell Douglas fighter jet that was used extensively during 
Operation Desert Storm in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	In her 42-page opinion, Ms. Wood said each jet normally sells  
for $23 million so the possibility it could be bought for $700,000 
was the first clue it was ``a deal too good to be true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his legal claim, Leonard noted that Pepsi increased the  
number of points required to buy a jet to 700 million and implied 
that the change proved the soft drink maker knew people would 
believe they could buy a jet. 
</P>
<P>
	But the judge wrote: ``The increase in the number of points  
needed to acquirer a Harrier jet may have been prompted less by the 
fear that reasonable people would demand Harrier jets and more by 
the concern that unreasonable people would threaten frivolous 
litigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David E. Nachman, Leonard's lawyer, said his client would  
consider an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're studying the decision. We're obviously disappointed,''  
he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Allen Seeks Hambletonian Win at 69 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Driving in the Hambletonian with three or four broken ribs is  
going to be quite a feat in itself for Carl Allen. 
</P>
<P>
	It's only half the story, though. In a world in which young,  
physically gifted, well-trained athletes compete for championships 
and titles, Allen will try to drive CR Commando to victory in 
trotting's most prestigious race at age 69. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen also trains the colt and CR Renegade, who will be driven  
on Saturday by his 43-year-old son, Rod. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would mean everything to win,'' Allen said Thursday in a  
telephone call from the Meadowlands Racetrack at East Rutherford, 
N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like winning the Kentucky Derby or the Indianapolis  
500,'' said Allen, who retired from the vacuum cleaner business in 
1967 to enter and develop one of the top barns in harness racing. 
``It's the ultimate in racing. It's a great accomplishment getting 
a couple of horses there, let alone winning it. If I could win it, 
it would great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 12 previous Hambletonians, Allen has finished in the money  
three times. The Ocala, Fla.-based horseman's best finish was a 
third with Olaf in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	After last year, most experts thought CR Commando was the colt  
to beat in the Hambletonian. The 3-year-old son of Royal Troubador 
led every step in winning last year's Breeders Crown final and won 
the Dan Patch Award as the top freshman trotting colt. 
</P>
<P>
	After winning two of his first three starts this year, CR  
Commando got sick and hasn't looked the same. The colt missed the 
Beacon Course Trot final -- won by CR Renegade -- on July 16 with a 
virus and then last weekend hung on to fifth to get a spot in the 
Hambletonian final. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen compounded the situation on July 22, breaking three or  
four ribs in a training accident while behind a pacer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ignoring doctor's orders to rest, he drove in the Hambletonian  
eliminations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody thought he went a bad trip last week but he  
didn't,'' Allen said. ``I knew that I could sit parked the whole 
mile and qualify. I just was afraid I couldn't hold him in the 
hole, hurting the way I was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While feeling a little better, Allen still will be only 80  
percent for the Hambletonian final, a race that most expect Self 
Possessed to win. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ron Gurfein-trained son of Victory Dream scored a six-length  
victory over CR Renegade in winning his elimination in 1:53. Angus 
Hall won the other elimination in 1:54 3-5, with CR Commando fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Self Possessed, Angus Hall and Raffaello Ambrosio will race as  
an entry that was 3-5 in the morning line. CR Commando and CR 
Renegade were the 7-2 second choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen admits CR Renegade has a better shot at beating Self  
Possessed than CR Commando. But if Commando ever gets back to last 
year's form, the elder Allen has a shot at becoming the 
second-oldest driver to win the Hambletonian. 
</P>
<P>
	Bion Shively was 74 when he won with Sharp Note in 1952 at  
Goshen, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, who used to race motorcycles, too, has no immediate plans  
to retire. He has told Rod to tell him if he ever becomes a hazard 
to other drivers or uncompetitive. He said he'll quit then. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I'll even drive next year,'' Carl Allen said.  
``I take each year as it comes. As long as I feel good and I'm not 
handicapped and I feel competitive, I'll continue driving. I have 
no fear whatever. If that comes, I'll quit, whether it's today, a 
year from today or five years from today.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
