<DOCNO> APW19990805.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:30:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hall Hopes for Redskins Kicker Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FROSTBURG, Md. (AP) -- Jeff Hall brought his homemade holder -- a  
contraption of one brick, duct tape, tomato cage wire and a brake 
hose -- to the Washington Redskins training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you were to buy a holder like that, you'd dish out about 35  
bucks,'' said Hall, whose father made the strange-looking object. 
``The thing I've got is cheap, homemade and fully adjustable. You 
can't beat that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for Hall, he hasn't brought the same accuracy that  
helped win a national championship last year at Tennessee. In the 
three-way battle for the Redskins kicking spot, the sixth-round 
draft pick is just beginning to recover from a difficult first 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know what I have done. I won't sugarcoat it,'' said Hall,  
who had four wide-lefts in one day. ``I feel like I have 
struggled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, Cary Blanchard and Brett Conway have been taking turns  
trying to put a few between the uprights over the first days of 
camp. Trying is the key word, for no one exactly is running away 
with the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would hope to have it defined by now,'' special teams coach  
LeCharls McDaniel said. ``But it's not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins have lacked a consistent kicker with distance since  
Chip Lohmiller was cut before the 1995 season. Eddie Murray didn't 
have much range. Scott Blanton's kickoffs were short and he was 
injury-prone. 
</P>
<P>
	Blanton lasted two games last year, and David Akers played just  
one in an 0-for-2 performance. Blanchard finished the season, 
making only 11 of 17 field goals, and Conway was signed for six 
games just to handle kickoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the Redskins desperately want to settle on one  
kicker. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, the way I'm looking at it is we need to improve  
on our field goal percentage,'' McDaniel said. ``I'd like kickoffs 
to play a role in it, but first and foremost we need to score.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The wild card in the competition is a new rule requiring a new  
ball to be used every time there's a kick or punt, an NFL response 
to allegations that some teams tampered with balls to make them go 
farther. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a stupid thing,'' Blanchard said. ``They don't throw in a  
loaded ball for Mark McGwire to hit the ball out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blanchard, McDaniel and punter Matt Turk said the rule could  
take as many as 10 yards off some kicks. Blanchard has heard 
stories of widespread tampering, but said he's never done much in 
his career 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't do a lot with the balls,'' Blanchard said. ``We'd  
just over-press or over-pump them so we could break the seams in so 
when you kick the ball it would go a little further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This week, Hall was able to put some kickoffs into the end zone,  
while Conway showed more punch on field goals. Both were 2-for-3 in 
a practice against Pittsburgh on Tuesday, and Saturday's scrimmage 
against the Steelers will probably determine which one gets cut 
this weekend and which one stays to challenge Blanchard. 
</P>
<P>
	For Hall, the adjustment to competition is not easy. He made  
62-yard field goals in high school and was never challenged for the 
job in four years at Tennessee, where he made 19 of 24 attempts his 
senior year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a path you get on and you see the end of that path,''  
Hall said. ``Well, I'm still trying to get to the path. It's been 
tough. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I don't like to lose. On game day I'm a high-strung,  
intense, ornery guy. At college, I had to be intense. I had to be 
nervous. I feel like when I'm intense and nervous, I'm focused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall's competitive enthusiasm on the field contrasts with his  
mild locker-room manner. Chewing on the cross he wears around his 
neck, he spoke of joining Darrell Green's Bible study group and of 
becoming a stockbroker if he doesn't make it in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not as interested in being rich as I am seeing things done  
with the money that I make,'' said Hall, who recently passed a 
brokerage exam. 
</P>
<P>
	But kicking is Hall's first calling. His mother tells the story  
that, when Hall was a child, he pointed to the television set when 
someone kicked a field goal and said, ``Mom, I'm going to do that 
someday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And if you look at me, I'm not going to do nothing else,''  
said Hall, who is 5-foot-11 and 190 pounds. ``Look at me. It's a 
wonder I'm even a kicker because I've got chicken legs.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
