<HEADLINE> Fla. Cop Charged in Suspect Beating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE WORTH, Fla. (AP) -- A videotape mailed anonymously to City  
Hall has led to criminal charges against a police officer who was 
filmed beating a handcuffed suspect at least 16 times with a baton. 
</P>
<P>
	Officer Stephen Danner, 33, was placed on paid leave Wednesday  
after he was charged with misdemeanor battery in the Dec. 7 
incident, police Chief William Smith said Thursday. The charge 
could bring a year of probation and a $1,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The videotape shows Danner repeatedly swinging his baton with  
two hands, presumably at 19-year-old David Weiler, who was lying 
handcuffed. A hedge partially blocks the view, so Weiler's body is 
not seen. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first reaction was I was shocked,'' Smith said. ``And I  
recognized the use of force was inappropriate for the 
circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Danner's attorney said his client's actions were justifiable.  
</P>
<P>
	``When all the facts are presented, we'll be able to show  
Officer Danner did not have any criminal intent do commit a crime 
but was simply doing what he needed to do to secure this 
individual,'' Scott Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Danner and two other officers had been called to a residential  
neighborhood about a bothersome stranger. 
</P>
<P>
	The videotape, which was mailed to City Hall two months after  
the incident, shows a shirtless Weiler wandering through yards and 
driveways. The chief said officers believed the teen-ager was 
experiencing a ``cocaine psychosis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to an internal affairs report, Weiler was handcuffed  
but refused to get into the back of a patrol car and got into an 
altercation with Danner. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief said he could not tell from the tape if the other two  
officers tried to stop the beating. They have not been charged. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
