<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 03:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Promotes Welfare To Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Eli Segal has spent the past two years prodding  
businesses to hire people off the welfare rolls, trying to convince 
them that welfare-to-work is good for the bottom line. But he 
doesn't like to be called a cheerleader for the cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Segal and his Welfare to Work Partnership are hoping to  
shed that image for good as they move away from persuasion and 
toward the nuts and bolts of helping companies make their programs 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were concerned we would be accused of being cheerleaders --  
of only being the good news boys,'' Segal said Wednesday as his 
group's national conference wrapped up a three-day meeting. ``We're 
sure that's behind us now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some 12,000 businesses have joined the partnership, pledging to  
hire at least one person off the rolls. But the group's internal 
polling finds that one-third of businesses haven't hired anyone 
yet. And focus groups conducted during the conference found 
lingering concerns about drug addition, child care, transportation 
problems and working with the nonprofit groups that train 
low-income workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best way we're going to help these businesses now isn't  
motivating them to join us -- that, we've done,'' said Segal, who 
formed the partnership at the urging of President Clinton, a 
longtime friend. ``We've got to move from recruitment to service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Getting more hires, Segal said, will require more practical  
advice. To that end, the group released guides to combating drug 
and transportation problems, and a new Internet site is meant to 
help people connect with groups that can help them. 
</P>
<P>
	But Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, who addressed the conference  
Wednesday, suggested that the cheerleading was still important, 
particularly among small businesses who may not have tried to hire 
off the welfare rolls yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Businesses have gotten the message, but I think you can't take  
that for granted,'' Herman said in an interview. ``This is an area 
where repetition is very, very important. This (welfare) is a 
60-year-old system. We're not going to change it in three or four 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, hoping to be more practical, the partnership plans to  
help businesses choose the right outside agency, sometimes called a 
service provider, to train and provide low-income workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Many cities have dozens of these mostly nonprofit groups  
offering such services, but businesses -- particularly small 
businesses -- have trouble figuring out which to use. Some are 
focused heavily on work skills, such as how to show up on time, 
while others teach practical skills, such as using computers. Some 
follow their clients for a year; others only work with them until 
they are hired. 
</P>
<P>
	The need for such services was supported by preliminary results  
from focus groups convened Monday that included businesses, 
nonprofit groups and welfare recipients, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is the perception that service providers and businesses  
often talk past each other, not to each other,'' said a summary of 
the results made available Wednesday. ``Businesses, particularly 
small ones, don't know where to go or even where to start looking 
for assistance ... with how to implement welfare to work 
programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One small business owner, participating in the focus group, put  
it this way: ``Business is being bombarded with 'what I can do for 
you' with no way of sorting through who can provide what and their 
success rate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The focus groups, run by pollsters from Wirthlin Worldwide, also  
found that nearly three years after Clinton signed the federal 
welfare overhaul bill into law, businesses are concerned with child 
care, transportation and training -- the same things policy experts 
were concerned about when welfare reform began. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
