<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Groups Boycott Burger King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- A coalition of American Muslims called  
Thursday for a worldwide boycott against Burger King because of a 
restaurant the fast-food chain opened recently in a West Bank 
settlement. The company said it will try to resolve the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	The West Bank has been at the center of the Middle East conflict  
ever since it was seized by Israel in the 1967 war. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our community views Burger King's decision to become a party  
to illegal occupation with profound distaste,'' said Khalid 
Turaani, executive director of American Muslims for Jerusalem, told 
a news conference held across the street from a Burger King in this 
suburb of the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to shutting down the West Bank restaurant, the  
coalition of about 10 Muslim advocacy and religious groups wants 
Burger King to make a donation to help Muslim refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Turaani said his organization tried to convey its concerns to  
Burger King officials but received only what they considered a form 
letter that ``reflects a lack of understanding of the current 
circumstances Palestinians face in the West Bank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miami-based Burger King Corp. said in a statement that it is  
``sensitive to all nationalities, religions and cultures, and it is 
our policy to be respectful of the needs of each in providing 
access to our products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Kim Miller said company officials ``take the issue  
very seriously and we will try to resolve it.'' They also are 
trying to ``encourage a dialogue'' with those involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Turaani said he expects Burger King to take the boycott threat  
seriously since the company has restaurants in Malaysia, Kuwait and 
Saudi Arabia and other nations where Muslims and Arabs make up the 
majority of customers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 13:10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Corn Down; Wheat Up / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures prices dropped sharply and corn  
wheat futures also fell Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid 
forecasts for rain in the Midwest growing region. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say prices were also down due to profit-taking from big  
gains in the past week and fears that prices are too high for the 
world market. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices had rallied sharply in the past week on thoughts  
that hot, dry weather has taken its toll on crops in Illinois and 
points eastward. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, wheat futures prices were up. Analysts say they're  
anticipating an increased demand for winter wheat since the spring 
crops were relatively smaller. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.94 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1 1/2 cents to $2.35 a bushel; December oats fell 3/4 
cent to $1.17 1/2 a bushel; and November soybeans dropped 14 cents to 
$4.80 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, beef and livestock futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .07 cent to 64.42 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle were up .35 cent to 76.42 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell .13 cent to 50.32 cents a pound; and August pork bellies 
fell 3 cents to 53.72 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
