<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle said  
Thursday it is ``appropriate'' for Texas Gov. George W. Bush to 
refuse to answer questions about his personal life. He also said 
the news media should apply the same standards to all public 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that it is absolutely appropriate and acceptable for  
Governor Bush to refuse to answer questions about his past personal 
behavior,'' Daschle said in a statement. ``What's not so acceptable 
is for the media to arbitrarily hold one public figure to one 
standard of behavior and another public figure to a far higher or 
lower standard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle denied a report Thursday that he had challenged the news  
media to investigate allegations of cocaine use by Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``That story is wrong,'' said his press secretary, Ranit  
Schmelzer. ``It completely misinterpreted what Senator Daschle 
said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former President Bush said a report that he  
considered dropping Dan Quayle as his running mate in 1992 is not 
true. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to USA Today published Thursday, Bush said that an  
article the previous day about Quayle's relationship with him was 
``factually and totally wrong and very unfair to the former vice 
president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The article alleges that ``Bush, never close to Quayle, almost  
dumped him from the ticket in 1992.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush defended his relationship with Quayle, saying ``not only  
have I always felt close to him, but I never even considered 
'dumping him from the ticket in 1992.''' Quayle is seeking the 
Republican presidential nomination in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The state Republican Party chairman wants  
to make sure Vice President Al Gore's recent canoe trip photo 
opportunity isn't just water over the dam. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest Republican attack on Gore, the front-runner for  
the Democratic nomination for president in 2000, state GOP Chairman 
Steve Duprey filed a complaint with the Federal Election Commission 
on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Duprey said the water released through a hydropower dam on the  
Connecticut River by PG&AMP;E Generating to float Gore's canoe amounted 
to an illegal corporate campaign contribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign dismissed Duprey's complaint as a publicity  
stunt and said it did not ask for the water release. 
</P>
<P>
	``Duprey's up a creek without a paddle,'' said Doug Hattaway, a  
spokesman for Gore's New Hampshire campaign. ``He should be ashamed 
of wasting taxpayers' money on a frivolous complaint that he knows 
is totally invalid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a week to go before a crucial Iowa straw  
poll vote, GOP presidential hopeful Steve Forbes will begin airing 
a radio ad attacking Clinton administration farm policy. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ads, Forbes denounces both Clinton's policies and high  
interest rates, which he blames on the Federal Reserve and its 
chairman, Alan Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Interest rates are too high, and while Alan Greenspan and the  
Federal Reserve raise rates, commodities prices have plummeted,'' 
Forbes says in the ad. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes also calls on the Clinton administration to ``tear down  
trade barriers, reduce taxes and regulations on farmers, 
investigate potential anti-competitive practices and encourage use 
of private crop insurance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ad is part of a $10 million nationwide summer media  
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Orrin Hatch challenged his fellow GOP  
presidential hopefuls to debate a few weeks ago to no avail. Now he 
is even providing a time and place for them to debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said in a letter to his fellow candidates Wednesday that  
he has reserved a meeting hall at Iowa State University on Friday 
so they can debate before the crucial GOP straw poll on Saturday in 
Ames. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know you share my strong conviction that only when the  
electorate is well informed on our positions can they make the best 
possible choice for whom they will vote,'' Hatch said in the 
letters. ``I'm convinced this debate will help inform not only the 
voters of Iowa, but voters across America as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters Douglas Kiker and Ann Kim contributed to this report.  
  	   	
</P>
