<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Tokyo Stocks Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar continued its slide against the yen  
after comments by U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers dashed 
hopes for market intervention. Tokyo stocks closed lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.62 yen in late trading, down 0.48 yen from  
its level of 115.10 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its late 
New York level of 114.29 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 327.19 points,  
or 1.85 percent, to close the day's trading at 17,358.19. On 
Wednesday, the average closed down 284.55 points, or 1.58 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar dropped after comments by U.S.  
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers failed to indicate that the 
United States and Japan would intervene in currency markets to prop 
up the greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	Some overseas players, including U.S. funds, sold the U.S.  
currency to take profits after intervention hopes faded, dealers 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We obviously watch what happens in markets, (and keep) in  
touch with our G7 partners, but that's as it has always been and 
there's been no change in that policy,'' Summers said in an 
interview with British broadcasting company BBC late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Zembei Mizoguchi, the International Bureau Chief in Japan's  
Finance Ministry, repeated today that Japan would take appropriate 
action against yen strengthening, but he declined to make any 
remarks on joint intervention with the United States. Traders said 
his comments were largely ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.40 yen, down  
from 124.12 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, a drop in the value of U.S. Internet and  
high technology shares on the U.S. Nasdaq Composite Index helped 
push down the Tokyo stock average, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq, which is dominated by technology stocks, plunged  
47.99 points, or 1.85 percent, to close Wednesday at 2,540.00. The 
Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped 2.54 points to 10,674.77. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger yen, which makes the products of Japanese exporters  
more expensive and therefore less competitive overseas, also hurt 
share prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The difficulties New York shares are having and the  
persistently stronger yen are combining to show that the (Japanese) 
market's recent gains have been unfounded,'' said Ryoji Musha, 
chief strategist of Japan Equity Research at Deutsche Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 483.47 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 472.49 million shares 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 1,036 to 195, while 80 issues  
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed down 28.65 points, or 1.96 percent, to 
1,431.02. The TOPIX closed down 22.32 points, or 1.51 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.8300 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.8850 
percent, driving its price up to 99.74 yen from 99.27 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
