<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Group Gets Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A federal bankruptcy judge on Thursday gave  
Mario Lemieux's group a second extension to wrap up what is 
becoming the much-delayed purchase of the bankrupt Pittsburgh 
Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	While granting the order sought by Lemieux, who was not in  
court, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz urged the myriad 
parties involved to move with haste to complete a sale he approved 
June 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's get this deal done,'' Markovitz said, directing his  
remarks to Lemieux lawyer David Salzman. ``It's time to get it 
together. I'll be pleased when this case is closed so we can start 
working on some other cases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salzman explained the delays ``should not be read as there are  
any problems, and there are not,'' but result from the complexities 
in completing a deal involving numerous investors and more than $50 
million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The paperwork itself is expected to run into the thousands of  
pages. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things are proceeding on track,'' Salzman said.  
</P>
<P>
	What has taken longer than expected is the completion of  
agreements with each of Lemieux's more than one dozen investors, 
including California supermarket millionaire Ronald Burkle, who is 
investing $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the team is to be run by a three-man board of directors  
composed of Lemieux and two of his top advisors, Anthony Liberati 
and Chuck Greenberg, some investors apparently have sought detailed 
agreements concerning control issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, the sale was to have been completed July 16. When  
that date was not met, Markovitz granted a 20-day extension that 
expired Thursday. The latest extension is open-ended with no firm 
closing date. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the various parties involved in the case, the new  
target date for the closing is Friday, August 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The delays are holding up a ticket-selling campaign aimed at  
increasing the team's season ticket base from 8,500 to 12,000 and 
also has caused some unanticipated problems. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, when the NHL paid the Penguins nearly $3 million in  
expansion fees, the money was deposited into the team's account in 
Societe Generale, the French bank that loaned the team $13.5 
million to operate last season. 
</P>
<P>
	But rather than making the money available to the Penguins, the  
bank worked out an agreement with the Lemieux group in which it 
applied $1.9 million toward the team's debt and made approximately 
$800,000 available to the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the nearly $3 million originally was to go directly to  
the Penguins, Markovitz had to approve the change in distribution. 
The bank also charged the Penguins $25,000 to extend the agreement, 
which expired Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins filed for bankruptcy in October, citing $120  
million in debt. The largest unsecured creditor was Lemieux, who 
was owed $32.5 million in deferred salary and other payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux will not take any cash out of the transaction but  
instead will exchange his debt for $20 million in equity. 
</P>
<P>
	At the closing, Lemieux's group will pay off the $13.5 million  
owed Societe Generale, less the money already applied, and $27.5 
million owed former co-owner Roger Marino, the NHL and unsecured 
creditors, plus pay back taxes and the mounting legal and 
accounting fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's group also will take on $22 million in debt owed three  
insurance companies from a 1997 loan and will pay the unsecured 
creditors, including former Lemieux teammates Ron Francis, Luc 
Robitaille and Kevin Stevens, $8.5 million over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The total sale price is expected to be about $91 million, or  
about what the Pirates sold for in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL Board of Directors also must approve the Lemieux  
takeover, but that is considered a formality. The NHL already has 
stated its support of Lemieux, who would become the first former 
star player to buy a major U.S. pro sports franchise. He retired in 
1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Waltrip To Retire in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Darrell Waltrip was always one of racing's  
great characters, spinning tires and tales with equal deftness and 
style. 
</P>
<P>
	Who could forget the good ol' boy from Kentucky doing the ``Icky  
Shuffle'' in victory lane in 1989 and wailing like a child, ``I won 
the Daytona 500! I won the Daytona 500!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though he still thinks he's a great driver, the 52-year-old  
Waltrip announced Thursday that, yes, it's true, he's retiring 
after next season. With a finale that he's calling ``Victory Tour 
2000,'' Waltrip will finish up one of the most remarkable, 
outspoken, fun-loving careers motorsports has ever seen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came into this sport in 1972, and I've been a headliner ever  
since,'' Waltrip said in an emotional announcement at Indianapolis 
Motor Speedway before qualifying for the sixth Brickyard 400. 
``When I'd go to town, people would say, `Are you here with the 
show?' And I'd say, `No, I am the show.''' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a glimpse of the arrogance that earned Waltrip the  
nickname ``Jaws'' in the early days, when he was viewed as stock 
car racing's outlaw. It's been quite a turnabout, because he will 
go out as the beloved ``old DW.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Admitting that the end is near left Waltrip momentarily  
speechless -- probably for the first time in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leaving this sport, hanging up my helmet, that's hard to talk  
about,'' Waltrip said, choking back sobs. ``I've done this for 40 
years. Ever since I was 12 years old, we'd get up, put on our 
racing gear and go to the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always thought about the future. ... Well, I'm running  
out of next weeks. That's really the bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, who ran out of former champion's provisionals two weeks  
ago at Pocono, unveiled a new car he'll use for the rest of the 
season. He made the bold prediction that he'll qualify consistently 
in the top 25 from now on. 
</P>
<P>
	The Victory Tour got off to an ignominious start Thursday when  
Waltrip stalled just before attempting his qualifying run. With 
less than a minute before time would run out on the session, 
Waltrip fired up the car and was 32nd fastest on the first day of 
qualifying at 176.478 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	With a sheepish grin, Waltrip explained the mishap.  
</P>
<P>
	``The battery cable was off the battery,'' Waltrip said. ``It's  
a good thing it came off when it did. If it came off during my run, 
I'd be in trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip has won three Winston Cup championships and leads active  
drivers with 84 victories, tied for third all-time with Bobby 
Allison. But ol' DW has been running on fumes for the past few 
years; he hasn't won a race since Darlington in September 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, who rarely misses a punchline, nailed the one  
pertaining to the name of his victory tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be kind of a fake tour, kind of a farce if we call it  
a victory tour and we don't produce a victory,'' Waltrip said. 
``Winning a race now would be just as special as winning that first 
one in 1975.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, a native of Owensboro, Ky., who lives in Franklin,  
Tenn., sold his race team last year after owning it for eight 
years, citing sponsor disputes and financial reasons. At the time, 
he said 1999 would be his last season. 
</P>
<P>
	That changed when Travis Carter and Carl Haas approached him  
about driving the No. 66 KMart Ford Taurus, signing him to a 
two-year contract. But Waltrip has continued to struggle, finishing 
25th in the most recent race at Pocono Raceway and placing 38th in 
the season points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess in every sport your legs give our, your arm gives out,  
something gives out,'' Waltrip said. ``I think every athlete that's 
been successful like I have, one thing never gives out. Your heart 
never gives out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His younger brother, who also is a Winston Cup competitor, can  
attest to that. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the book is written about NASCAR racing, he will  
certainly have a chapter in it,'' Michael Waltrip said. ``One of 
the things that I most admire about him is that he's been able to 
do it on his own terms, and that hasn't always made everybody 
happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip got his first victory at his home track in Nashville,  
Tenn., in 1975. He won 22 races from 1975-79, then captured the 
Winston Cup championship in 1981, '82 and '85. 
</P>
<P>
	His popularity soared once he learned to use his gift for gab  
wisely. 
</P>
<P>
	Once in the 1980s, Waltrip was asked what he thought of  
Chevrolet's new Lumina. Without hesitation, Waltrip said he'd 
received letters from fans who wanted to know, ``Why are they 
switching to those 'luminum cars? What's wrong with steel?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, a future TV commentator who says he also might go into  
politics after racing, still has plenty of one-liners left in the 
tank. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just haven't decided what state I want to be governor of  
yet,'' Waltrip said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like racing, politics probably would never be the same.  
</P>
<P>
	``DW ain't told all the stories he knows,'' Waltrip said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
