<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purdue Player Remembered As Vibrant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HILLSBORO, Ala. (AP) -- Tiffany Young, a member of Purdue's 1999  
national championship team killed in a car accident, was remembered 
Thursday by friends and family members as a vibrant young woman 
with strong religious faith. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,200 people, including Young's Purdue teammates, attended  
the funeral at Wheeler Chapel Full Gospel Baptist Church in her 
hometown of Hillsboro, a town of about 600 in north Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tiffany is not dead,'' said her father, Billy Young, standing  
by her casket at the front of the church. ``I'm sure you're looking 
up here and can see she's not moving, but she's not dead. I remind 
you -- you're just looking at the house where she used to live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young, 21, was killed last Saturday in a two-car collision in  
Gary, Ind., where she was visiting her boyfriend. Police said the 
car in which Young was riding was struck by a drunken driver. 
Arnold Eaton, 33, of Great Lakes, Ill., was charged with operating 
a vehicle while intoxicated, causing a death, and is free on bond. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue team members rode a chartered bus from West LaFayette,  
Ind., to Hillsboro for the funeral, and some former teammates of 
Young's also attended. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was a teammate, friend and sister in Christ,'' Purdue  
teammate Camille Cooper said. ``Tiffany, I pray that you continue 
to pray for us because we will continue to pray for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young's boyfriend, Neil Sinclair, was still recuperating from  
injuries suffered in the wreck and could not attend the funeral. He 
was driving the car. 
</P>
<P>
	Young was buried in nearby Courtland.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
