<DOCNO> APW19990805.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brothers Stick Together in Handball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- They fought, argued and tried to get  
the best of the other no matter what they did, which is the way 
brothers are, after all. 
</P>
<P>
	But on the floor, playing team handball for the United States,  
Tom and Joe Fitzgerald stand together. Throw in the support they 
get from their parents and two sisters and the Fitzgeralds might be 
America's first family in their sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are playing in the Pan American Games and both played in  
the Atlanta Olympics in 1996. Tom, 33, has been on the U.S. 
national team since 1989. Joe, 27, the self-professed ``tagalong,'' 
has played on the team since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some success, but it was in different sports so it's  
hard to measure who's the better athlete or better player,'' Tom 
said. ``Obviously, I'm more experienced from a technical 
standpoint. But from a competitive standpoint, we compete for the 
last chicken cutlet in the refrigerator -- and have knocked over 
chairs and china to get it. 
</P>
<P>
	``But at the same time, we're as loyal as anybody can be. If  
somebody steps on his toes, I'm the one who pushes the guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fitzgeralds and their teammates fell 38-20 to Cuba on  
Thursday night in the semifinals, losing their chance to go to the 
2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers got into team handball because it combines skills  
from football, basketball and baseball, the sports they played as 
youngsters. It requires agility and endurance. Players must be 
skilled enough to dribble a ball the size of a large grapefruit and 
strong enough to fling it past a goalie. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom first played e sport as a teen-ager in the Empire State  
Games, an Olympic-style festival for New York residents. Naturally, 
Joe had to try it, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in high school and went to a practice with him one time  
and they needed an extra guy,'' Joe said. ``So I went on the court 
and basically fell in love with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tom had played a version of the sport in gym class in high  
school, but it was more a free-for-fall than an organized game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, it was 15 against 15 and kill the guy with the  
ball,'' he said, laughing at the memory. ``We'd put a freshman in 
the goal and try to bean him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His game has come a long way since then. After playing point  
guard in basketball at St. Bonaventure, Tom took up team handball 
again, got back into it quickly and has played ever since while 
working as an accountant. He also played professionally for two 
years in Sweden and has just relocated in Atlanta, where the U.S. 
team trains. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe played football and baseball at Ithaca College and was a  
quarterback on the school's Division III national championship team 
in 1991. He was good enough to draw interest from the NFL, CFL and 
Arena Football League, but decided his future was in team handball. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks after graduating, Joe tried out for the national team  
and made it. The brothers were together again -- this time as 
equals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always the tagalong guy,'' said Joe, an eighth-grade  
history teacher in the Atlanta area. ``Whether it was baseball, 
basketball, football, hockey, if he did it, I tried to do it 
better. Sometimes I did. Most of the time he was bigger and pounded 
on me. I definitely took some beatings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Tom had any choice about Joe tagging along.  
</P>
<P>
	``We always made him the right fielder or official catcher,''  
Tom said. ``It was my responsibility to make sure he spent the day 
with us, if we went to the beach or played stickball or whatever. 
It didn't matter what I said or my friends said, it was the law of 
my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The family has provided the brothers with all the support they  
could ask. Their older sister, Elizabeth, was 8 1/2 months pregnant in 
the summer of 1996 and wasn't supposed to fly, but she flew to 
Atlanta anyway to watch her brothers. She gave birth a week after 
the closing ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	Their younger sister, Graceanne, moved to Atlanta before the  
Olympics, hung around with her brothers, helped promote the team 
and took part in numerous activities with them. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was almost a member of the team,'' Tom said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mom (Graceanne) and Dad (Thomas) were there as well, just as  
they always had been when it was time to drive someone to practice 
or a game or a football film session. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can imagine how proud my parents were to have two children  
in the Olympics,'' Tom said. ``Dad was walking around with a smile 
for a long time. They're the two best ambassadors we have.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
