<HEADLINE> Dolphins Quick To Offer Clean Slate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- The Miami Dolphins' roster includes three  
convicted felons and a receiver under federal indictment, prompting 
critics to complain that Jimmy Johnson wants to win at all costs. 
</P>
<P>
	There is, of course, no law against that.  
</P>
<P>
	Many Miami players are law-abiding, God-fearing, family oriented  
registered voters who have never even been guilty of illegal 
procedure. But Johnson's recent willingness to welcome players with 
criminal records has sparked wry speculation that the NFL will 
require the Dolphins to wear eight-digit numerals on the back of 
their uniforms this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson has always put speed and strength ahead of citizenship.  
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Hurricanes were the bad boys of college football when  
Johnson led them to the national championship in 1987. With the 
Dallas Cowboys, he assembled back-to-back Super Bowl champions who 
subsequently embarrassed the NFL with a series of off-the-field 
transgressions. Talented but troubled running back Lawrence 
Phillips was signed by Johnson and the Dolphins in late 1997, then 
released last summer after he was charged with hitting a woman at a 
nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	Felons can be found on the rosters of many teams, and most of  
the Miami players with police records committed their crimes before 
becoming Dolphins. Still, JJ has been a bit brazen this year in his 
eagerness to transform Miami into a tougher team. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson drafted rookie running back Cecil ``the Diesel''  
Collins, who avoided prison in April by pleading guilty to charges 
he fondled two coeds in their apartments. Then Johnson signed 
rookie receiver Robert Baker, who was released from jail in March 
after serving 10 months for drug trafficking. 
</P>
<P>
	The most notorious newcomer is veteran Tony Martin, who went on  
trial this week facing charges of laundering drug money. The 
Dolphins are counting on the speedy receiver to upgrade the 
offense, which means their Super Bowl chances may be in the hands 
of the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson acquired Martin, Collins and Baker well aware of their  
legal problems. He has also stuck with veteran receiver Lamar 
Thomas, who was twice charged with attacking his fiancee and spent 
nearly three weeks in jail in 1997 for violating probation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our whole country and our lives are dealing with second  
chances,'' Johnson said after signing Baker. ``A lot of people get 
second chances, whether it's a husband or wife or president or what 
have you.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *Vikings    	
</P>
<P>
	Gary Anderson, the first perfect kicker in NFL history, says the  
league's new kicking rules will make it next to impossible for him 
or anybody else to duplicate his impeccable season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The basic theory is they don't want us to do our jobs as well  
as we do them,'' said Anderson, who made all 35 of his field goals 
and all 59 of his extra points for the Minnesota Vikings in the 
regular season last year. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, whenever a kicker lines up for a field goal, an  
official will swap the game ball for a new one that hasn't been 
thrown, carried, or caught. 
</P>
<P>
	The league wants to prevent any possible tampering with balls,  
especially by kickers and punters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be very strange that you have two sets of balls.  
A quarterback throws one ball but as soon as it comes time to punt 
or kick a field goal, they're going to whip a different ball out 
there so we can't kick it as well,'' Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like maybe telling a tennis player with a really good  
serve, `We're going to give you a soft ball so you can't serve as 
hard.' `` 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *Falcons    	
</P>
<P>
	Tim Dwight wants to contribute more to the Atlanta Falcons than  
he did as a rookie last season. 
</P>
<P>
	With last year's leading receiver, Tony Martin, no longer  
around, coach Dan Reeves could certainly use additional help from 
Dwight, who made a pretty good splash on special teams his rookie 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want the ball more this year,'' said Dwight, a 5-foot-8,  
180-pound speedster who ran a leg on Iowa's 4x400 relay team that 
finished fourth in this year's NCAA track and field championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``My main goal is to make some plays,'' Dwight said. ``I want to  
find a role in this offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dwight's 10.45-second speed in the 100 meters made him valuable  
in returning kickoffs and punts last season. He had 36 kickoff 
returns for 973 yards and one touchdown and returned 31 punts for 
263 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	His biggest moment came in the Super Bowl, when he returned a  
kickoff 94 yards for a touchdown -- fourth longest in Super Bowl 
history. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *Eagles    	
</P>
<P>
	Nearly two weeks into his first stint as a starting quarterback  
in the NFL, Doug Pederson feels the Philadelphia Eagles offense is 
making progress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things have progressed for me and the offense,'' Pederson  
said. ``I feel real good about it now. Honestly, there have been 
some times when I could have been better. I'm always critical of 
myself and that's the only way you can get better. I look at the 
films from practices and see where I make mistakes and try to 
eliminate them when we practice again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pederson is starting because of his familiarity with the West  
Coast offense from his days as a backup quarterback in Green Bay, 
where new coach Andy Reid coached the quarterbacks for three 
seasons. While No. 1 pick Donovan McNabb matures, the 32-year-old 
Pederson, who has thrown just 32 passes in the NFL, gets his chance 
to be a first-string signal-caller. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be content just being a starter,'' he said.  
``I want to go out there and do well. I'm very, very excited about 
this chance. I'm pumped. This is what I've worked for my entire 
career. I'm going to make the most of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
                             	 *Jets    	
</P>
<P>
	The Jets' right cornerback slot was effectively decided Thursday  
when veteran Otis Smith broke his left collarbone during morning 
workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10th-year player, who was being pushed by Ray Mickens for a  
starting role, will be sidelined for up to seven weeks after 
suffering the injury during a passing drill. Smith, 33, fell hard 
after getting tangled up with wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Bill Parcells said that Smith will not need surgery. He  
may not be available, however, until the season's fourth week when 
the Jets travel to Denver for a rematch of the AFC Championship 
Game with the Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's our first big setback,'' Parcells said. ``Losing Otis  
hurts us. He's a good veteran player who knows what to do. He was 
also going to play special teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells admits to being nervous about the prospect of teaming  
Pro Bowl left cornerback Aaron Glenn, who is 5-9, with the 5-8 
Mickens. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still want big guys,'' Parcells said. ``I don't care; I want  
big players instead of little players.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
