<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corning Consumer Products Buys Ekco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHUA, N.H. (AP) -- In a marriage of pots and pans, the parent  
company of Corning Consumer Products Co. has agreed to buy Ekco 
Group Inc. for about $300 million, the companies said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	CCPC, based in Elmira, N.Y., said it would pay $7 per share for  
all outstanding shares of Nashua-based Ekco. The cash tender offer 
will open in about five business days and extend through Sept. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The price represents a 56 percent premium over Ekco's closing  
price Wednesday of $4.50 per share on the American Stock Exchange. 
The deal has been approved by Ekco's board of directors, but 
closure is subject to a majority of shareholders accepting the 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ekco stock surged on the news Thursday, closing up 50 percent,  
or $2.25, at $6.75 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	CCPC will assume about $150 million in Ekco debt, said Ekco's  
chief financial officer, Don DeNovellis. 
</P>
<P>
	Ekco, which has seen its stock price dip as low as $2.81 in the  
past year, began looking for ways to ``maximize shareholder value'' 
several months ago. The sale to CCPC was the result, DeNovellis 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He referred questions about possible layoffs to Corning Consumer  
Products. CCPC officials did not return calls Thursday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Ekco makes metal bakeware under the brand names Ekco, Baker's  
Secret and Farberware, and also makes kitchen tools. Its products 
are sold everywhere from supermarkets and hardware stores to 
department stores and kitchen specialty stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Corning Consumer Products makes glass and ceramic bakeware under  
the Corningware, Pyrex and Visions brands. It also makes Revere 
pots and Corelle dishes. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Campanella, president and chief executive of Corning  
Consumer Products, said the sale would bring together two leaders 
in cookware. He also said Ekco's line of kitchen tools would 
complement the higher-end Oxo brand made by General Housewares 
Corp., which Corning Consumer Products announced Monday it would 
acquire for about $143 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Corning Consumer Products is a privately owned affiliate of  
Borden Inc., which provides significant management and financial 
control. Corning Consumer Products had sales of $553 million in 
fiscal 1998 and employs about 3,000 people. Its largest shareholder 
is investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Ekco, which also makes cleaning tools and household pest control  
products, posted sales of $328 million in fiscal 1998 and employs 
about 1,150 people. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
