<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan May Cancel Boeing 777 order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TACOMA, Wash. (AP) -- Taiwan's flagship airline apparently has  
been told by the Taiwanese government to cancel an order for 12 
Boeing 777s in protest against the Clinton administration's 
mainland China policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing had been expecting the $2 billion deal to be formally  
announced at any time. It has been working on it since Taiwan's 
China Airlines signed a letter of intent to buy the jets in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing congressional and industry sources, the Tacoma News  
Tribune reported today that instead, China Airlines is expected to 
announce a major purchase of A-340 planes from the European 
consortium Airbus Industrie, perhaps as early as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	China Airlines is still expected to announce the purchase of 13  
Boeing 747s. 
</P>
<P>
	A China Airlines spokesman, commenting under the customary  
condition of anonymity, said the company does not like government 
interference and that he was not aware of any government decision 
to intervene on in the Boeing deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman also said that he was not aware if China Airlines  
is switching from Boeing to Airbus. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials were not available for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	China Airlines ceased being Taiwan's flag carrier three years  
ago and operates as a private company. 
</P>
<P>
	The apparent decision by Taiwan to use Boeing as a political  
pawn stems from the Clinton administration's reaction to comments 
made by Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui about the ever-strained 
relationship between the island nation and mainland China. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 9, Lee said Taiwan and China should regard each other on  
a ``state to state'' basis, a statement Beijing saw as a step 
toward a declaration of independence by what it still considers a 
renegade province. But the United States has stood by its ``one 
China'' policy with the Beijing government in control. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing was characteristically tightlipped about the deal.  
</P>
<P>
	``All the major Asian airlines have chosen 777s,'' said Marta  
Newhart, a Boeing spokeswoman in Seattle. ``Twelve (Asian) airlines 
have them on order. We believe it is the right airplane for China 
Airlines, but it is up to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., will be Taiwan-bound on Saturday in  
an effort to salvage the Boeing order. He has requested a meeting 
with Lee. Gorton met Wednesday with Stephen Chen, Taiwan's 
unofficial ambassador to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, meanwhile, has been in  
``government-to-government'' contact with Taiwan about the 
situation, said Helaine Klasky, a spokeswoman for U.S. Trade 
Representative Charlene Barshefsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky has ``communicated the view that such a decision  
should be based on technical and commercial merits,'' Klasky said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
