<DOCNO> APW19990805.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 20:04:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken's Back May Need Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken is convinced his second stint on the  
disabled list this season will last no longer than the required 15 
days, but he admitted that offseason surgery might be an option if 
his ailing back continues to be a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken woke up Sunday morning full of energy, but by the time he  
reached the breakfast table he was bent over in pain. He skipped 
the Baltimore Orioles' game against Seattle that day and was placed 
on the disabled list Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-time All-Star has since received a cortisone shot to  
alleviate the pain caused by back spasms. He was walking gingerly 
in the Baltimore clubhouse Thursday afternoon, dressed in street 
clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have every reason to believe the smartest thing is to get  
the inflammation out of there, continue to do the exercises and 
then go back and play,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have every confidence that I'll be ready to step back in  
after that time is up with a better body and be able to swing the 
bat,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	When he returns, Ripken will resume his quest to become the 29th  
player in baseball history to hit 400 homers (he has 399). He is 
also just 32 hits short of 3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken went on the disabled list the first time in his career on  
April 20. He returned on May 14 and said he experienced no back 
when whatsoever until Sunday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It came back when I least expected it to,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Now he has no idea whether he's stuck with a chronic problem,  
one that can be remedied only by surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, if surgery was the magical answer it would present  
itself. If (the spasms) continue to reoccur, then you have look 
seriously at a way to stop it, and surgery appears to be an 
option,'' he said. ``I'm not convinced that's it at this point. But 
that becomes an option if I'm not able to go out and play or keep 
it from being inflamed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, 38, played in a major league record 2,632 games until  
voluntarily ending his streak last September. This year he has 
proven to be a mere mortal, missing several games after being hit 
on the wrist with a pitch in addition to his initial two stints on 
the DL. 
</P>
<P>
	``It almost seems like two separate careers,'' he said. ``I was  
lucky enough to pound my back and hit it all these years; maybe 
what you're seeing now is the accumulation of all that pounding.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 22:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat, Humidity Tough on Chickens / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Heat and humidity in recent weeks have  
been especially cruel to the poultry industry, with losses 
experienced by Mississippi growers estimated at up to 400,000 
birds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last week was our worst week statewide for the summer,'' said  
state Board of Animal Health Poultry Epidemiologist Danny Thornton. 
``But with the number of birds we have in the field, that's really 
not too bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi Department of Agriculture figures show the state  
produced nearly 603 million chickens in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Thornton said in some cases, cooling systems used in many modern  
chicken houses failed due to power outages and mechanical problems. 
He said this, combined with the high humidity and blistering 
temperatures, killed a number of the chickens. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace Morgan, head of the Poultry Science Department at  
Mississippi State University, said chickens do not sweat and must 
get rid of excess heat through their respiratory systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when the atmospheric heat is higher than their internal  
heat, they can't get rid of it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan said heat-related chicken deaths are common during the  
summer months but that last week's losses were larger than usual, 
primarily because of the high humidity. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his office approved about 20 mass burials last week for  
chickens killed by the heat. He said the burials were needed 
because normal disposal devices used by farmers were unable to 
handle the numbers involved. He said each of the mass graves 
contained more than 1,000 chicken bodies, with the largest holding 
up to 60,000. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANDAN, N.D. (AP) -- North Dakota's wheat fields are an annual  
tourist attraction for wheat industry officials, researchers and 
others looking at yield and quality. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's Wheat Quality Council spring and durum tour, which  
ended Thursday, found the hard red spring wheat crop in 
southeastern and south-central North Dakota trailing last year's 
crop in yield, and average or a bit below average in quality. 
</P>
<P>
	The average calculated yield of unharvested fields was projected  
at 29.5 bushels per acre Tuesday, the first day of the annual tour. 
That compares with an average of 31 bushels in 1998 and 31.2 
bushels in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The wheat tour concluded in the Red River Valley. More than 60  
people participated, including wheat promotion council officials, 
researchers, grain buyers and marketers, millers and journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's projected yield is lower than actual yields  
throughout the region for any year between 1992 and 1998. 
Projections vary widely, however, from field to field, and from 
county to county, because of factors such as moisture, weeds and 
signs of disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, tour participants found disease problems more intense  
in the east. But they said projected yields are closer to average 
or above average in the east and fall off to below average in 
south-central areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the best-looking wheat was found in northeastern South  
Dakota, where projected yields were reported at 3.6 bushels to 2.5 
bushels above the 1998 crop. But in North Dakota, participants 
found little to get excited about. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything was average, very average,'' said Mike Hardy, of  
Spring Wheat Bakers in Fargo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
