<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Claims Rise by 4,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits inched up last week after hitting their 
lowest level in two years the week before. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported today that 279,000 Americans filed  
new claims for jobless benefits for the week ending July 31, up by 
4,000 from the previous week. Last week's level was the highest 
since July 17, when claims were at 315,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims had plunged by 40,000 to 275,000, the lowest  
level in two years, for the week ending July 24. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-week moving average for claims, which smoothes out  
week-to-week volatility, was down a little to 295,000 last week. 
That was the lowest level since March 27 when claims were at 
293,750. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week's increase was slightly less than some economists  
expected but still kept claims at a level indicating the nation's 
job market remains exceptionally healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists expect the nation's unemployment rate -- now at  
4.3 percent -- will return to a 29-year low of 4.2 percent when the 
government releases its July unemployment report Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	That results of that report are expected to offer an important  
clue as to whether the Federal Reserve may raise interest rates 
again when it meets later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists fear that as employers woo workers with higher wages  
and benefits, the higher labor costs could lead to higher prices. 
Thus far, that hasn't happened and inflation has remained low. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains in productivity -- the output per hour of work -- and  
competition from overseas are credited with keeping prices in 
check. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan said the central bank is keeping  
a watchful eye on all this and stands ready to raise interest rates 
at the first glimpse of inflation. The Fed nudged up rates on June 
30. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said today that for the week ending July  
24, six states and territories reported increases in jobless 
claims, while 47 had decreases. The state data lag a week behind 
the national figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest increase in applications for jobless  
benefits was Ohio, up 6,286, a gain officials blamed on layoffs in 
the transportation equipment industry. Other states reporting 
increases were: Maine, 224; Washington, 130; Colorado, 92; and 
Georgia, up 48. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan recorded the biggest decrease, 22,777, which was  
attributed to fewer layoffs in the automobile industry. Other 
states with large decreases were: New York, 6,864; South Carolina, 
6,169; Alabama, 5,470; and Illinois, down 4,948. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
