<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 14:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Andretti Anticipating Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Michael Andretti would rather be in front. Still,  
he's comfortable coming up through the pack. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why he could be a major factor in Sunday's Tenneco  
Automotive Grand Prix of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to a fourth-place finish in the U.S. 500 on July 25 for  
the Newman/Haas team at Michigan Speedway, Andretti currently 
stands third in the CART FedEx Series championship race with 107 
points. He trails rookie Juan Montoya, who has four wins and 129 
points, and Dario Franchitti, who has 116 points. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the 14th time in his 16 years in the series that  
Andretti has topped 100 points. But that's not why he could be a 
force on the temporary road course around Belle Isle. 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti has won more races (38), more poles (32) and led more  
laps (6.057) than any other active driver. He has earned 25 of his 
wins on street courses like the one on Belle Isle. 
</P>
<P>
	And, perhaps most important of all, Andretti has won this race  
twice, in 1990 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am really looking forward to this race,'' Andretti said  
Thursday. ``It is always an important race for us because it is 
Kmart and Ford's hometown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guess who two of Andretti's biggest sponsors might be.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite Andretti's high hopes, Montoya is the likely favorite in  
this race. Montoya, the only driver with more than one victory this 
season -- he has four -- has won on the short oval at Nazareth, 
finished second in the U.S. 500 at Michigan, and won on street 
courses at Long Beach and Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly he doesn't seem to matter what kind of course he runs  
on, which gives Andretti reason for concern. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been working hard to get our cars working well on street  
courses and we were competitive in the last race at Toronto,'' 
Andretti said. 
</P>
<P>
	His two wins in Detroit were as different as they could be.  
</P>
<P>
	``The 1990 race was like a dream race because we almost lapped  
second place,'' Andretti said. ``That was very different from 1996, 
when I really shouldn't have won the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That year, he was running second behind Christian Fittipaldi.  
When Fittipaldi went wide on the last restart, Andretti got by him. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Detroit course is so tight, passing is difficult. As  
a result, qualifying could be vital. Montoya, for example, has 
started on the pole four times this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Practice and qualifying Friday and Saturday are very important  
days,'' Andretti said. ``If you want to win here, you almost have 
to start near the front row.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite changes to the course to try to make it easier for the  
competitors to pass, most of the 72-lap event on the 2.346-mile, 
14-turn circuit looked more like a parade than a race last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Zanardi, who led 50 of the 72 laps, won the Detroit race  
last season. But he won't be around to defend his title. Zanardi is 
racing the Formula One circuit this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 20:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Sharpe May Play in Bowl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Denver Broncos tight end Shannon Sharpe  
has no serious damage to his ankle and may play in Sunday's 
American Bowl against San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe, who has fiercely criticized the game being played in  
Australia, strained the ankle during practice Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He attended Friday's light run but did not take part.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's much improved on yesterday and we'll have a better  
feeling about it after tomorrow's practice,'' Broncos coach Mike 
Shanahan said. ``We may not make a decision until game time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The teams will contest the 33rd American Bowl in Sydney on  
Sunday morning, which will be Saturday night in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan tried to play down Sharpe's comments from Thursday,  
when the seven-time Pro Bowl player complained about the rudeness 
of Australians. 
</P>
<P>
	While Sharpe was roundly criticized on radio talk shows and in  
local newspapers -- he was called a 250-pound gorilla by one shock 
jock -- Shanahan said he had enjoyed a different experience Down 
Under. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are probably the friendliest group of people I've ever  
met,'' Shanahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Broncos spokesman Jim Saccomano said Sharpe was allowed his  
opinion. ``But to say Australia is deficient in hospitality is like 
saying there's not enough sand in the Sahara or enough snow on the 
Rockies,'' Saccomano said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Sharpe's constant sniping has at least given him some  
profile in a city previously oblivious to his existence, he appears 
out of step with most other players on the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're having a nice time and it's just the time change that's  
been a problem,'' San Diego cornerback Dwayne Harper said. ``The 
people have been good to us, no one here's been complaining and 
we're just trying to enjoy Sydney and the new experience. I think 
it's great to be able to come and experience another country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
