<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Via Technologies Aiming at Intel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In another move to take on Intel Corp. in the  
chip-set-making industry, Via Technologies Inc. said it has agreed 
to buy the microprocessing unit of Integrated Device Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei-based Via said in a statement Thursday that it will  
acquire the WinChip microprocessor unit and x86-architecture 
microprocessing design team from Integrated Device Technology, 
based in Santa Clara, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Via and Integrated also agreed to a patent cross-license  
agreement for each company's chip technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Merritt, an analyst with Semico Research Corp., based in  
Phoenix, said the move ``substantially strengthens Via's position 
in the chip set market,'' where Via currently is the No. 2 
supplier, behind Intel. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Via announced a $167 million agreement with  
Santa Clara, Calif.-based National Semiconductor Corp. to buy 
National's Cyrix unit, which makes low-priced PC computer chips. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, in response to falling processor prices, Integrated  
Device Technology announced it was exiting the x86-chip market, 
chips designed to be clones of Intel's popular x86 chips. 
</P>
<P>
	Via's action this week should increase pressure on manufacturers  
to lower prices in the market for chip-sets, components designed to 
perform and manage one or more related functions, such as those of 
a modem, in a PC. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
