<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> St. Louis Fans See History Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- In a frenzy rivaling last year's march toward  
70 home runs, Mark McGwire gave St. Louis fans even more than they 
expected Thursday -- not just his 500th homer, but his 501st, too. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire's third-inning blast set off three minutes of fireworks,  
streamers and well-behaved chaos among the sellout crowd of 45,106 
at Busch Stadium. As an encore, he hit No. 501 in the eighth 
inning, setting off another round of hysteria. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never even saw the ball leave his bat because there were so  
many cameras going off,'' Marshall Gralnick said after No. 500. 
``It took me a minute to tell that he got a home run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The atmosphere was reminiscent of last September, when McGwire  
pursued, equaled and then toppled Roger Maris' single-season home 
run record. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's history in the making, and I love it,'' said Ron  
Hallowell, who drove to the game from St. Joseph, Mo., with his 
7-year-old son Kyle. ``I told my son that we're going to keep his 
ticket to tonight's game. We'll probably still be talking about 
this in 30 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fans also hoped to see San Diego star Tony Gwynn get two hits  
become the 22nd member of the 3,000-hit club. Instead, he went 
1-for-4 with a two-run double in the ninth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd gave Gwynn a standing ovation as he goes to Montreal  
with 2,999. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being here tonight was exciting because of McGwire, but I am  
rooting for Gwynn, too,'' Gralnick said. ``I was glad to see 
everybody stand up every time he came up to bat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A dozen of Gwynn's relatives and NL president Len Coleman were  
part of the standing-room-only crowd which included a few who paid 
scalpers $150 or more for tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it would happen tonight,'' said Linda Mahfood. ``I was  
here to see McGwire hit his first and 70th home runs last season. I 
just knew tonight was the night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Midway through the game, a variety of collectibles went on sale  
at venues throughout Busch Stadium. Pro Player and Joy Athletic 
preprinted T-shirts marking McGwire's milestone. Rawlings Sporting 
Goods Co. made 500 hand-numbered commemorative baseballs and 1,999 
mini bats, while Fotoball had 5,000 baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people who got me in here told me I owed them one big, and  
I'm here to buy them shirts,'' said Joe Reid of St. Louis. Sadly 
for Reid, all the shirts and other 500 memorabilia were gone by the 
time he got to the front of the line. 
</P>
<P>
	But 9-year-old Andrew Walker and his 8-year-old brother, Joshua,  
packed their gloves into the stadium in hopes of catching the real 
thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We bought our tickets back in April,'' said the boys' father,  
Don Walker. ``It wasn't until last week that I realized we might 
have a chance to see history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The family from Broken Arrow, Okla., picked the game because it  
featured players favored by Andrew and Joshua. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew wears Gwynn's No. 19 on his Little League uniform, while  
Joshua sports McGwire's No. 25 on his back. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we walked up to the stadium, they kept saying, 'This is so  
cool. This is so cool,''' said their mother, Wendy Walker. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
