<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magic Look to Post-Penny Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Four years after they looked like the NBA's team of the future,  
the Orlando Magic are starting all over. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's trade sending Penny Hardaway to the Phoenix Suns  
completed the dismantling of a once-dominant club that made it to 
the NBA Finals in 1995, then was unable to build on that success. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaquille O'Neal fled for the Los Angeles Lakers, Dennis Scott  
wore out his welcome, and Nick Anderson and Horace Grant were 
traded away this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Hardaway, he'll be remembered as the player who begged to  
be united with Shaq and then whined his way out of town. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly the goal for this franchise is to still win a world  
championship, even though that may not come just next year,'' 
general manager John Gabriel said. ``The trade of Penny Hardaway 
sets the foundation for us for the relaunching of this franchise 
and this team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gabriel also pulled off trades the past six weeks to unload the  
other starters from the team that that was swept by Houston in the 
'95 Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant was sent to Seattle in a draft-night deal that brought  
Corey Maggette, a flashy 19-year-old swingman who left Duke after 
his freshman season. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, the lone remaining player from Orlando's inaugural  
season 10 years ago, was sent to Sacramento for Tariq Abdul-Wahad 
and a first-round draft choice. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for Hardaway, Orlando received 32-year-old Danny  
Manning, second-year pro Pat Garrity and two future first-round 
picks. Despite Manning's age, the deal followed a plan to put 
together a younger, more athletic team under first-year coach Doc 
Rivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabriel lauded owner Rich DeVos' courage to give his blessings  
to part with Hardaway, who did not handle the role of team leader 
well after O'Neal's departure in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-time All-Star orchestrated the firing of former coach  
Brian Hill in 1997 and bickered the past two seasons with Chuck 
Daly, who retired in May after Orlando lost to Philadelphia in the 
first round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway also infuriated fans, who grew tired of excuses for  
disappearing at crunch time and what was perceived as his 
unwillingness to forgive them for booing him when a draft-night 
trade brought him to the Magic in exchange for Chris Webber in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after the Magic bowed out of the playoffs, he said he felt  
unappreciated in Orlando and that a change of scenery might be best 
for him and the team. He apologized the next day, but the damage 
had been done. 
</P>
<P>
	Callers to talk radio shows in Orlando were overwhelmingly in  
favor of getting rid of the 28-year-old guard, although few felt 
the Magic got enough in return. 
</P>
<P>
	Most fans thought Tom Gugliotta should have been obtained in any  
deal with the Suns. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabriel, noting that the team had explored the prospect of  
trading Hardaway more than once, suggested he didn't have many 
options. The deal sat on the table for several days, and there 
wasn't a flood of last-minute offers from other clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it fits our goal and our plan, maybe more than one  
that would perceive that he had to get a superstar for a 
superstar,'' the general manager said, adding that he talked to 
Hardaway twice in the 24 hours before the trade was finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to make sure that we spoke to him and that this was  
the road he wanted to go. ... He said, `Gabe, I can tell you right 
now, it's not about not loving Orlando. It's about wanting to be in 
Phoenix.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal adds to an impressive stash of first-round draft picks  
Gabriel will have to help rebuild the franchise. The Magic will 
have three first-rounders next year, including picks from Golden 
State and Denver, and seven more in the following four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Moving Hardaway, Grant and Anderson also has positioned them to  
be active in the free-agent market in coming years. Gabriel expects 
to drop more than $10 million below the salary cap by 2001. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
