<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese-American Memorial Gets OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A small memorial park near the Capitol to  
recall the 115,000 Japanese-Americans the U.S. government interned 
in World War II got unanimously approval Thursday from the National 
Capital Planning Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Ground-breaking is scheduled for October, with work to be  
completed a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	A 15-foot statue of two winged cranes struggling through barbed  
wire will dominate the site. The three-quarter acre park will also 
commemorate the Japanese-Americans who fought in the U.S. armed 
forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``The walls around the plaza are intended to evoke a sense of  
confinement, commemorating the experience of internment,'' the 
commission's staff said in evaluating the project. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be a row of Japanese cherry trees, a shallow pool  
with boulders to recall the islands of Japan and an 18-foot bell 
like those in Japanese temples. 
</P>
<P>
	Cherry Tsutsumida, who has been directing the project, said $8.6  
million has been collected for the work, with an additional $2 
million sought. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington's Fine Arts Commission has yet to approve a final  
model of the statue, and the inscriptions along the 7-foot tall, 
3-inch thick granite wall around the central plaza. Approval could 
come at a meeting in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some wonderful quotes, but too many of them,''  
Chairman J. Carter Brown of the Fine Arts Commission said after a 
meeting last month. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the names of Japanese-American veterans, the wall  
is expected to carry statements from postwar presidents repudiating 
the internment. The Supreme Court had upheld it as a war measure 
but Congress has voted compensation to those interned. 
</P>
<P>
	The planning commission also approved without discussion another  
small park with a memorial to Mahatma Gandhi, whose campaign of 
nonviolence helped bring independence to India. The government of 
India is donating an 8-foot-8-inch statue of Gandhi, to face the 
Indian Embassy on Massachusetts Avenue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Americans set Pan Am Swim Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Record performances by Staciana Stitts  
and Karen Campbell finally gave the beleaguered United States 
women's swimming team a major boost at the Pan American Games on 
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-year-old Stitts, who has the disease alopecia, which  
causes hair to fall out, smashed the Pan Ams record in the 
100-meter breaststroke with a time of 1 minute, 9.16 seconds in 
leading a 1-2 American finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell, 22, a black belt in taekwondo, shattered the record in  
the 100 butterfly in the preliminaries in 59.70, then won the final 
in 1:00.05, the first time in this competition the final was slower 
than the heats. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, which has dominated the men's races, added two more  
golds for a total of five, and Canada won the other men's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's 400 freestyle relay team of 100 freestyle champion  
Fernando Scherer, Cesar Quintaes, Andre Cordeiro and 200 freestyle 
gold medalist Gustavo Borges set a Pan Ams record of 3:17.18, after 
teammate Luiz Lima won the 400 freestyle in 3:52.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Another games record was broken in the men's 200 breaststroke as  
Canada's Morgan Knabe won in 2:14.73. Americans Steven West, 27, 
the oldest member of the team, and 16-year-old Mark Gangloff 
finished 2-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The victories by Stitts and Campbell stopped the Canadians' gold  
rush in the women's events. Before Thursday, the Canadians had won 
seven of eight finals, with the Americans winning the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Stitts said her baldness, which she has had for five years,  
works in her favor in the pool. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's totally awesome,'' said Stitts, who will be a freshman at  
California in the fall. ``It's beneficial to swimming when I'm 
shaved down. I'm so glad I'm in swimming. I don't know where I'd be 
without it. The sport is a big ego-booster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stitts, of Carlsbad, Calif., said she doesn't know whether the  
disease is genetic or an immune disorder; no one in her family that 
she knows has had it. 
</P>
<P>
	``My hair grows back in the summer ... it sprouts,'' she said.  
``I shave it off because it looks silly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the hair began falling out, Stitts tried hiding her head  
with hats for a year, then stopped wearing the caps because she 
felt comfortable with her look. 
</P>
<P>
	Her winning time broke the Pan Ams record of 1:10.30 by American  
Tierney Dorsay in 1991. The next two finishers also went under the 
previous record. Kristen Woodring of Sinking Springs, Pa., was 
second in 1:09.65 and 200 breaststroke champion Lauren Van Ooosten 
of Canada finished third in 1:10.06. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell's performance in the prelims broke the record of  
1:00.53 set in 1979 by Jill Sterkel, an assistant coach on the U.S. 
swim team. Sterkel watched in surprise as her record fell. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes me feel old,'' she said. ``I didn't even remember  
that I had the record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Campbell nor Sterkel thought the fifth-year senior at  
Southern California would go out so fast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went out faster than I had planned,'' the co-captain of the  
U.S. women's swim team said after clocking 27.39 for the first 50 
meters. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was looking to go out in the high 27s,'' Sterkel, an  
Olympic relay gold medalist in 1976, said. ``It was neat to see 
that kind of speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The door is open for her to go as far as she likes. People  
used to think that when you reached a certain age, you were washed 
up. Not now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell's first 50 meters in the final weren't as quick as in  
the prelims. Still, she had the lead with 27.55 and wound up 
beating two Canadians. Jessica Deglau, already a gold medalist in 
the 200 freestyle and two relays, got the silver, followed by 
Karine Chevrier. 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's races, the United States also picked up silvers in  
the 400 freestyle, with Austin Ramirez finishing with a 
personal-best 3:53.64 behind Lima, and in the relay. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
