<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bear Stearns Settles for $38.5M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Investors defrauded by a small brokerage will  
get $30 million from Bear Stearns &AMP; Cos. Inc., a big Wall Street 
firm that processed their transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement announced Thursday, which totals $38.5 million  
and was accompanied by the resignation of a top Bear Stearns 
executive, closes a two-year investigation by federal and New York 
City authorities into Bear Stearns' relationship with the smaller 
brokerage, A.R. Baron &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Bear Stearns neither admitted nor denied  
wrongdoing in agreeing to the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Bear Stearns processed trades, a lucrative financial function  
known as clearing, for A.R. Baron from mid-1995 through mid-1996. 
The now-defunct A.R. Baron, which also was based in New York, 
failed in 1997 and is in bankruptcy proceedings. Customers, some of 
whom have sued, have contended they lost a total of $75 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Walker, enforcement director of the Securities and  
Exchange Commission, said at a news conference in New York that 
Bear Stearns ignored repeated signs that A.R. Baron was cheating 
its customers. Walker said the sanctions are meant to punish Bear 
Stearns and send a message to other financial firms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would hope the responsible people in the industry will see  
this and realize that you cannot turn a blind eye to fraudulent 
conduct,'' said Walker. He was accompanied by Manhattan District 
Attorney Robert Morgenthau. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Thursday, the SEC filed fraud charges against Richard  
Harriton, the president of Bear Stearns Securities Corp., a 
subsidiary that clears transactions for other brokerages. 
</P>
<P>
	Harriton resigned from the firm and said he would fight the  
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement with Bear Stearns includes a $5 million civil  
fine, one of the largest levied by the SEC on a single company in 
recent months but far from record. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement headed off a civil lawsuit by the SEC, which was  
believed to be imminent, as well as criminal prosecution by 
Morgenthau's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Bear Stearns is not required to plead guilty to any criminal  
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will pay $30 million to establish a fund for  
compensating defrauded investors. Bear Stearns also will pay fines 
of $1 million to New York state, $1 million to New York City and an 
additional $1.5 million to Morgenthau's office to cover costs of 
its investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Bear Stearns agreed to hire an independent  
consultant named by the SEC who will review the company's 
operations and make recommendations. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Bear Stearns said its agreement to settle the  
case ``was a prudent business decision undertaken to end what has 
become a distraction for the company, its shareholders, its 
employees and its customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company said the settlement would not materially hurt its  
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	An official at a securities industry trade group said the  
stepped up regulation on the profitable sideline to trading may 
have a bigger impact on regulators than clearing operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The firms, in terms of tracking some of this information, may  
have more work,'' said Mike Udoff, a staff advisor for the 
Securities Industry Association. ``I think they can handle that 
without it having a major economic impact on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The real stress, he said, would fall on the exchanges and  
regulators themselves, which will have to process more information 
from all of the clearing houses. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgenthau won securities fraud convictions in 1997 and 1998  
against 13 former A.R. Baron executives and brokers for using the 
firm to defraud investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling A.R. Baron ``a corrupt criminal enterprise,'' he said  
Thursday that its victims included ``some people who invested their 
life savings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In late June, Bear Stearns disclosed a $25 million tentative  
settlement with the SEC, comprised of a $5 million fine and $20 
million to settle claims of A.R. Baron customers. Negotiations had 
been continuing since then. 
</P>
<P>
	Bear Stearns is one of the two largest clearing operations in  
the country, along with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc.'s 
Pershing division. Bear Stearns processes about 200,000 trades a 
day, or about 10 percent of the New York Stock Exchange volume that 
is cleared through the National Securities Clearing Corp., an 
organization formed by stock markets to enable brokers to process 
their accounts with one another. 
</P>
<P>
	All the clearing firms are facing stiff new compliance  
requirements from the National Association of Securities Dealers, a 
self-policing industry group. The new rules require clearing firms 
to forward customer complaints to the authorities and keep more 
detailed records. 
</P>
<P>
	Bear Stearns stock was little changed on the news, edging up 6 1/4  
cents to $41.68 3/4 a share on the NYSE. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
