<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Seeks To Aid Tobacco Growers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- They grow a crop the government doesn't want  
people to buy, yet the Senate wants to give tobacco farmers $328 
million to stay in business. 
</P>
<P>
	The farmers say they need the cash that's tucked in a $7.4  
billion package of farm aid to compensate for the money they're 
losing from declining cigarette sales and lagging exports. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tobacco farmers have their backs against the wall in terms of  
this agricultural crisis as much as any other farmers,'' said Larry 
Wooten, a North Carolina grower. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics say tobacco isn't just any crop.  
</P>
<P>
	``This was a step backwards,'' said Sen. Dick Durbin, D-Ill.  
``It certainly is inconsistent for us to be subsidizing tobacco 
while we tell people how dangerous it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders put the money in the farm assistance package  
at the request of senators from tobacco growing states. Most of the 
money in the legislation, about $6 billion, would go to grain and 
soybean growers. 
</P>
<P>
	The drought that has parched much of the East Coast this summer  
has largely spared tobacco crops. But the government, which 
stabilizes tobacco prices by regulating production, cut back 
sharply on how much tobacco farmers could grow this year because of 
declining domestic and foreign markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The quotas were reduced by 29 percent for burley tobacco and 17  
percent for flue-cured. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is putting a lot of farmers in a financial bind,'' said  
Blake Brown, an agricultural economist at North Carolina State 
University. ``They can't grow or sell tobacco without a quota.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco growers will share in a $5.2 billion trust fund that's  
being set up by cigarette companies to compensate them for 
declining cigarette sales, and growers also are likely to get a 
share of the industry's $206 billion settlement with state 
governments.	   But money from the trust fund won't start flowing before next 
year, and farmers say they need help now. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the emergency aid package, other farmers are getting  
compensated for lost income, and I felt that tobacco farmers 
should, too,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky. ``While prices for 
other commodities will rise in the future, the income lost due to 
the cut in tobacco quota will not return.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Senate bill, the $328 million would be distributed  
according to the same formula as the trust funds, which has yet to 
be finalized. That money is likely to go to quota owners, who don't 
necessarily farm themselves, as well as growers. 
</P>
<P>
	The House version of the agriculture spending bill for fiscal  
2000, which starts Oct. 1, has no money for tobacco farmers. A 
House-Senate conference committee will work out the final version 
of the farm-assistance package after lawmakers return in September 
from a monthlong recess. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it will survive,'' Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D.,  
said of the tobacco money. ``I don't think the United States as a 
policy wants to be supporting tobacco.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Antismoking groups have been trying to persuade tobacco farmers  
to plant other crops. The Senate aid won't help that cause, ``but 
the farm economy is in such a bad state that telling them to switch 
to something else like corn or soybeans doesn't make sense,'' said 
Scott Ballin of the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd like to see this money to go to other uses, like buying  
out quotas or economic development funds,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 13:00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BMW Plans Thailand Output Mext Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- German luxury car maker BMW AG will  
start rolling sedans off the production lines at a new plant in 
Thailand early next year, hoping to capitalize on a nascent 
economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesus Cordoba, president of BMW (Thailand), told The Associated  
Press in an interview that production targets of 10,000 vehicles 
per year should be reached by 2004 and will initially be aimed at 
the Thai market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Afterward, we will study the possibilities of expanding our  
market to cover all the countries around Thailand, the Southeast 
Asian markets, and expand production to 20,000 to 30,000 units a 
year,'' Cordoba said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The $32 million plant in the eastern auto production center of  
Rayong, where U.S. automakers Ford Motor Co. and General Motors 
Corp. also have facilities, is viewed by BMW as getting a bigger 
foot in the Asian market. Until now, the firm has relied on a local 
partner to assemble the vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Thailand has become the primary offshore Southeast Asian  
manufacturing center for many of the world's big carmakers, 
particularly the Japanese. 
</P>
<P>
	The domestic market shrunk when the Asian economic crisis struck  
in 1997, but manufacturers are increasingly tooling Thai plants to 
export vehicles to other parts of the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordoba said location, availability of suppliers, trained  
workers and infrastructure were key factors in locating a plant in 
Thailand. It will join BMW's non-German factories in South 
Carolina, South Africa, Austria and Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have come to Thailand as long-term investors,'' Cordoba  
said. ``You have to look at the possibilities of the country. The 
Thai market has huge potential.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Talks With Hispanic Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George Bush stepped up  
his courtship of Hispanic voters Thursday, telling community 
leaders, ``You are part of the dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A week after angering Hispanics by skipping a high-profile  
advocacy group convention, Bush rejected English-only proposals, 
called for ``more humane'' border enforcement and backed trade 
deals aimed at bolstering relations with Mexico. ``A healthy Mexico 
is good for America,'' Bush told about 50 leaders of the Hispanic 
community. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no doubt that Bush was making his meeting with  
Hispanic leaders the centerpiece of his latest campaign swing. It's 
long been a part of his effort, but there have been a couple of 
high-profile meetings he's skipped that angered some Latinos. 
</P>
<P>
	During this swing, Bush sought to ease those worries.  
</P>
<P>
	``I want Republicans to see that I am willing to make an active  
effort to reach out to the Hispanic community,'' said Bush. ``This 
is a concerted effort to broaden the base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meeting with the activists, Bush slid back and forth between  
English and Spanish, taking occasionally pointed questions in both 
languages. Speaking in Spanish at one point he apologized for 
switching to English. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to destroy a beautiful language.'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush routinely include snippets of Spanish in his stump  
speeches, and did well among Hispanic voters in his last election. 
</P>
<P>
	But he angered some in the Hispanic community recently when he  
declined to speak to the National Council of La Raza, a Latino 
advocacy group. Bush was vacationing in Maine at the time and cited 
that conflict in declining. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Bush declined to speak at a meeting of minority  
journalists in Seattle, though he was campaigning in that city at 
the time. He did make a brief appearance at that event. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore -- who, like Bush, routinely speaks  
Spanish on the campaign trail -- addressed both groups, and Bush 
sought to repair any damaged relations. He invited reporters and 
photographers into a session where he courted Hispanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things this campaign is going to do is bring new  
faces and new voices into the Republican Party,'' said Bush. ``We 
must have a bigger base if we hope to capture the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He faced a broad range of questions on immigration issues, and  
he firmly rejected volatile issues like English-only which have 
caused problems for Republicans among Hispanics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I support English-plus, not English-only,'' said Bush.  
``English-only says to me that if Hispanic happens to be your 
heritage, you're not part of the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush pledged to revisit guest worker programs and other ways for  
immigrants to come into the country, but said he would insist on 
immigration controls and a waiting period before citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	Some argued that Bush has ground to make up, and said many  
Hispanics noticed his skipping of important meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a start for us to start to repair the damage,'' said  
Paula Plasencia. ``He needs to have a Hispanic agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Hispanic voters have been heading to Democrats, some  
argued that there was an opportunity for Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time both parties have taken the minorities for  
granted,'' said Mike Murillo. ``We have been a pawn and we need to 
have our needs addressed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's comments could bring some tensions to the GOP race.  
Conservative Republicans generally take an anti-immigration line, 
with some like commentator Pat Buchanan calling for construction of 
a fence along the southern border. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope my fellow Republicans think it's a good idea,'' Bush  
said of his appeal to Hispanics. ``I hope they understand how 
important the Hispanic community is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others made it clear Bush has some ground to make up before  
Hispanics will move into the Republican Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandra Sanchez said many Hispanics remain deeply offended by  
ballot issues in California and elsewhere widely viewed as 
anti-immigrant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to listen to people talking in our own language,  
we want to hear them talk about our issues,'' Ms. Sanchez said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 10:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Suit Seeks Checkups, Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Healthy but still worried, thousands of  
people who took the fen-phen diet drug combination are seeking 
millions to pay for years of medical checkups in case they develop 
heart or lung problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Evidence linking the ``fen'' half of the drug duo with sometimes  
deadly disorders forced two versions of fenfluramine off the market 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection began this week in a class-action lawsuit against  
American Home Products, which made fenfluramine. If American Home 
loses the civil trial, it could be forced to pay more than $1 
billion over the next decade, one economist estimated in court 
documents. 
</P>
<P>
	``The implications are huge,'' said Hemant Shah, a drug industry  
analyst with HKS &AMP; Co. in Warren, N.J. ``You're talking about as 
much as $1,000 per year per patient. Then if you take the national 
implications ... you're looking at some serious problems for the 
company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suit by New Jersey residents is the first class-action case  
against American Home to come to trial and the only one seeking 
payment for medical checkups rather than financial awards. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison, N.J.-based American Home already has settled several of  
about 3,100 individual suits, but those settlements are estimated 
to total only around $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	During closing arguments of a fen-phen trial in Canton, Texas,  
on Wednesday, attorneys for Debbie Stone Lovett said American Home 
hid evidence that its diet drugs caused heart valve damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Lovett, a 36-year-old manicurist, said she developed leaky heart  
valves after taking fenfluramine. She is seeking unspecified 
damages in the case, now before the jury, which deliberated today. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide, about 6 million Americans took either fenfluramine,  
which was sold under the brand name Pondimin, or its chemical 
look-alike, dexfenfluramine, sold under the name Redux. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home pulled both drugs off pharmacy shelves in  
September 1997, several months after the first reports from the 
Mayo Clinic linking the drugs to potentially fatal heart valve 
damage in some patients. 
</P>
<P>
	The company insists there's no scientific proof that patients  
who stopped taking the drugs about two years ago and have no 
disease now will be injured in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to believe that routine echocardiograms are not  
medically warranted for patients who have taken these drugs,'' said 
company lawyer Anita Hotchkiss. 
</P>
<P>
	Studies since the drugs were recalled generally indicate a  
slightly elevated risk of valve disorders, but that it appears to 
fade after patients stop taking them. 
</P>
<P>
	The other half of fen-phen, phentermine, was never associated  
with that damage when taken alone and is still on the market. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Race Car Driver Waltrip To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Darrell Waltrip said today it's true -- he is  
retiring after next season. 
</P>
<P>
	In an emotion-choked announcement at Indianapolis Motor  
Speedway, one of stock car racing's legendary drivers confirmed 
what has been widely reported for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 52-year-old three-time Winston Cup champion is calling his  
final season a ``victory tour.'' Waltrip, who hasn't won since 1992 
and rarely misses a punchline, nailed this one on the nose. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be kind of a fake tour, kind of a farce if we didn't  
get at least one victory,'' Waltrip said. ``Winning a race now 
would be just as special as winning that first one in 1975.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In making his announcement before qualifying for the sixth  
Brickyard 400 at Indy, Waltrip broke down in tears and summoned his 
wife to the podium for support. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leaving this sport, hanging up my helmet, that's hard to talk  
about,'' said Waltrip, the man who stormed into racing and earned 
the nickname ``Jaws'' for his loud mouth now choking back sobs. 
``I've done this for 40 years. Ever since I was 12 years old, we'd 
get up, put on our racing gear and go to the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always thought about the future. What am I going to do  
next year? If I don't win this week, I'll get 'em next week. Well, 
I'm running out of next weeks. That's really the bottom line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, a Kentucky native who lives in Franklin, Tenn., leads  
all active Winston Cup drivers with 84 career victories but has not 
won a race since Darlington in September 1992. He finished 25th in 
the most recent series race, the Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono 
Raceway, and is 38th in the season points. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip sold his team last year after owning it for eight years,  
citing sponsor disputes and other financial reasons. At the time, 
he said the 1999 season would be his last. He changed his mind when 
asked by Travis Carter and Carl Haas to drive the No. 66 KMart Ford 
Taurus for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Waltrip, who has frequently used the former champion's  
provisional to keep his career going, vowed to qualify consistently 
in the top 25 with a new car -- trimmed with flames instead of 
Waltrip's favorite chrome look -- that was unveiled today. 
</P>
<P>
	``There should be no excuse for me and this car to miss races,''  
Waltrip said. ``This car should not need a provisional.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
