<HEADLINE> Daschle: Jerry Springer Is a Joke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Maybe refereeing all the brawling and bawling  
guests was just training for the real fights. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Springer, the TV talk show host reviled by many as a pox  
on American culture, is contemplating a run for the U.S. Senate as 
a Democrat. The prospect is drawing condemnation from editorialists 
and office holders across the political spectrum. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want him to run. I think he is a joke,'' Senate  
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told The Columbus Dispatch for 
a story today. 
</P>
<P>
	But observers warned against underestimating Springer's  
political skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've known Jerry Springer for many years, and I consider him  
the most dangerous man in Ohio politics,'' said Bill Cunningham, a 
conservative talk show host on WLW radio in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he runs, I think he would bring thousands and thousands of  
his fans to the polls just as Jesse `the Body' Ventura brought his 
fans to the polls. Jerry is a fabulous politician.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer, 55, has said he'll consider running for the seat of  
Republican Sen. Mike DeWine, who is seeking re-election next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he would spring on the back of Mike DeWine like a  
jaguar on a ledge springing on the back of a passing water 
buffalo,'' Cunningham said. 
</P>
<P>
	Springer is a former two-term mayor of Cincinnati who ran for  
governor in 1982, then embarked on a TV career, working as an 
anchor and commentator before discovering that foul-mouthed, 
chair-throwing guests could make him the nation's No. 2-rated 
daytime talk show host. 
</P>
<P>
	DeWine is a former prosecutor whose low-key earnestness led  
colleagues to choose him to preside over Monica Lewinsky's 
deposition in President Clinton's impeachment trial. Messy affairs 
like that are mainstays of ``The Jerry Springer Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeWine has not commented on Springer, but the state's Republican  
chairman, Bob Bennett, has quipped: ``Was Howard Stern busy?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some residents of Springer's hometown say they'd be embarrassed  
to send him to Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a joke,'' said Alvin Bell, 37, of Cincinnati. ``If people  
are dumb enough to vote for him, they deserve what they get.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Carol Batis, 43, thinks Springer would make a great senator.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's a real good person. He tries to help people on  
his show and help solve their problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea of a Senate run surfaced July 20 in The Plain Dealer of  
Cleveland. Hamilton County Democratic Party Chairman Tim Burke, a 
friend of Springer, told the newspaper the talk-show host would be 
a ``viable, fascinating, interesting candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Wrong, wrong and wrong,'' the Plain Dealer editorialized the  
next day. A spasm of righteousness rippled across the state. An 
editorial in The Vindicator of Youngstown called Springer 
``ringmaster of the nation's sleaziest circus.'' Toledo Mayor Carty 
Finkbeiner said Springer would get in the way of his party's 
emphasis on ``family values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer put out a statement saying: ``I'm obviously flattered  
and honored by the interest. It's just that at this time I don't 
know whether it's practical or possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Springer said he'll decide by Labor Day.  
</P>
<P>
	Springer left the country for a vacation late last month after  
his show went on hiatus and was not available to comment further, 
his publicist Linda Shaffron said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio Democratic Chairman David Leland said party officials would  
decide later this year whether to endorse a candidate. Columbus 
lawyer Richard Cordray, the party's unsuccessful candidate for 
state attorney general last year, is seeking that backing. 
</P>
<P>
	Leland said he hadn't heard from Springer, but if he does he'll  
tell him that people across the state have strong feelings about a 
possible candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are people who are incensed about the fact that he would  
do this,'' Leland said. ``They think it would not be a good 
thing,'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Leland said, some people are volunteering to help  
Springer, others think he has no chance and yet a third group is 
scared he'd win. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
