<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plant Evolution Theories Challenged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The plant and animal kingdoms actually  
represent five distinct groups, according to scientists who 
announced discoveries that fundamentally alter long-standing 
theories about the evolution of plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers presented data showing that green plants, red plants  
and brown plants (mostly algae and seaweeds), evolved from three 
different one-celled plants, and so deserve to be considered 
individual kingdoms. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers are among 200 scientists from 12 countries  
involved in the ``Deep Green'' project, a five-year effort to 
reconstruct the evolutionary tree of life for green plants. 
</P>
<P>
	They found that the many families of green plants living on land  
today descended from a single, green freshwater ``Eve,'' a relative 
of which still lives in pristine lakes as it did more than a 
billion years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	New data indicate that the ``Eve'' was something similar to  
today's coleochaetes, tiny green plants about the size of a pinhead 
and just one cell thick, which require fresh water that is 
completely free of pollutants. 
</P>
<P>
	``This overturns traditional thinking among scientists and what  
is taught in every textbook in America,'' said Brent Mishler, a 
biologist at the University of California at Berkeley and one of 
the team leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Current texts say land plants evolved from saltwater plants.  
</P>
<P>
	Scientists involved in the study presented their work Wednesday  
in St. Louis at the 16th International Botanical Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The group has produced the most complete tree of life of any  
group of living things on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	Their findings are important because evolutionary relationships  
among plants are crucial in knowing how plants work. Understanding 
this allows researchers to examine chemicals in plants for their 
medicinal value. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Deep Green's other key findings:  
</P>
<P>
	-- The members of what has traditionally been called the plant  
kingdom should actually be divided into four separate kingdoms. 
</P>
<P>
	-- One of those kingdoms, fungi, is more closely related to  
animals than to plants. That means a mushroom is more closely 
related to a human being than the tree it grows on. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't really think of life on Earth in terms of only the  
`animal kingdom' and the `plant kingdom' anymore,'' Mishler said. 
``In fact, there are five kingdoms of complex organisms on Earth 
today.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990805.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Jobless Rate Rises in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's unemployment rose above the politically  
charged 4 million mark in July as job growth continued to lag 
behind the recovery developing in Europe's largest economy, the 
Labor Office said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The unadjusted number of jobless rose to 4.027 million, or 10.3  
percent, up from 10.1 percent a month earlier, the Labor Office 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor Office president Bernhard Jagoda blamed the increase on  
summer vacations and the end of the school year, when companies are 
hesitant to hire people who they know will be taking their 
traditional lengthy summer holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The German central bank, which releases seasonally adjusted  
numbers, said the jobless rate was unchanged at 10.5 percent in 
July, with only 1,000 more people out of work. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase was not as bad as some expectations. But analysts  
said real improvement would likely not be seen until the end of the 
year, when recent positive indicators for the German economy -- such 
as rising orders and exports -- begin to make a dent in the jobless 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no bad number, but it's also not a good number,'' said  
Ulrich Beckmann, an analyst with Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt. ``The 
only thing which you can see is that it's not deteriorating 
anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagoda, though, said even an improvement in the economy won't  
help the job market much. He said structural reforms to Germany's 
notoriously rigid, expensive labor market are the key. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're waiting for the warm rain of the economy, then  
you'll be disappointed,'' Jagoda said. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of unemployed Germans topped 4 million in 1997 and  
has remained stubbornly stuck around that level. 
</P>
<P>
	The unemployment rate contributed to last year's defeat of  
long-serving conservative Chancellor Helmut Kohl. Chancellor 
Gerhard Schroeder's government has pledged to reduce the level by 
at least 1 million by 2002, but has had little success so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagoda said economic conditions were improving most markedly in  
the former West Germany, where most industry is located. 
</P>
<P>
	Western Germany's unadjusted unemployment rate was 8.6 percent  
in July, up from 8.4 percent in June. That compared with 17.4 
percent, up from 16.8 percent, in former communist eastern Germany. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
